text_long_wave1:
I am more worried about getting access to my normal healthcare at  the moment, than being concerned about Corona. My usual treatments have been halted, so my health will deteriorate even if I don't catch the virus!
I am struggling to get routine prescriptions and medical appointments, which is making me feel powerless and anxious.
I am also feeling very sad, as I can not see my children and grandchildren and can not celebrate birthdays and anniversaries with them.
I have been advised to stay inside my house for twelve weeks. The thought of this is making me unhappy, as all that I want to do is to go outside for a walk, but that is not possible right now.
text_short_wave1: Not being able to cuddle my family sucks!
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2:
I am hopeful that the vaccine will help to bring back normality, but I am also worried that sending children back to school next week will start another wave of the virus, as numbers of infected people are still quite high.
I hope that I can see my family again soon. It has been a tough year for us all. Five loved ones have died, and a new baby has been born. We have not been able to either mourn the loses or celebrate the new baby. It has been a time of mixed emotions for us all and we need to know that we can come together some time soon to support each other.
text_short_wave2: #Hopeful, but still scared.
employment status_wave2: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave3: I am just getting over Covid, so in a way I feel relieved that I have had it and I have survived. I am feeling more relaxed about going out now, as the chances of catching it again in the next few months are minimal. I feel that I can do the things that I have been putting off, like going to the hair salon. What more can I tell you, I have written my feelings, but you still need more characters? Still need more characters, I don't know what else to write. Surely this is over 500 characters by now?
text_short_wave3: I caught Covid and survived.
life_event_descr_wave3: Catching Covid! It is both a negative and positive thing. Negative because I was quite ill, positive because I hopefully won't catch it again for a while.

text_long_wave1: I am a little concerned that so many people are not staying at home and risking themselves and others just to enjoy the sunshine. I think the situation will get worse of the next few weeks but, hopefully, will then start to slowly improve. I'm worried what state the country will be left in as so many businesses will close down and the way we live in this country will be changed forever. So many small businesses and self-employed workers will struggle to survive. I am hopeful that a vaccine will be developed before the end of the year.
text_short_wave1: Spending time at home with the family and working from home as I normally do. The big difference is not going out. I miss going for a drive out the the beach or the countryside with my dogs, or just to wonder around some shops and stopping for a coffee when I want. Stay safe
text_long_wave2: Over the past twelve months, there has been little to look forward to with the constant lockdowns and other restrictions. At the moment, I think the current situation is starting to look better than it has for the last twelve months. Now that more and more people are being vaccinated, the infection rates and deaths are starting to fall rapidly. I think that provided that people respect the rules for a few more months then, hopefully, life can start getting back to something like normal later this year.
text_short_wave2: Things are starting to look better
text_long_wave3: I'm very relaxed about the current Corona situation. It has now become a normal part of everyday life. Most people are going about their lives almost as before the pandemic. There are very few restrictions and businesses are returning to normal. I currently feel that we are over the worse and are now treating Corona much the same as other viruses and just accepting it as part of everyday life. The only slightly annoying part is having to still wear facemasks inside shops and other premises. Hopefully, that restriction will also be removed soon.
text_short_wave3: Everyday life is returning to normal and we can get back to are normal lives.

text_long_wave1: I feel relaxed. I'm aware of the risks and I'm doing my very best to mitigate against them & I'm also pleased to see others in my local community doing the same. I feel positive about the future & about life going forward from this point. I find it hard to conceive of the disease touching me personally, yet I know there is every chance that it will. I have concern for older relatives, particularly my mother, and for other people I know in the community. I'm trying to remain positive and look ahead to the end of the lockdown period whenever that may be.
text_short_wave1: I'm OK, I'm feeling positive, but also a little apprehensive. On the whole, I believe we will get through this very soon.
text_long_wave2: I feel the Corona situation is getting better, however I also feel it has been badly mismanaged by the government. I feel saddened at the amount of avoidable deaths that have occurred because we didn't lockdown soon enough on 3 occasions, I feel angry at the way the government has tried to blame people for behaving badly when they made the biggest mistakes. I feel like the recovery will hit the poorest hardest and that will be incredibly unfair. Once the situation has been improved, I suspect the NHS will once again be left to fend for itself and won't be funded to the degree that is necessary. I suspect that the government will seize the opportunity to impose more austerity on the population.
text_short_wave2: I feely our government's response like we are getting over the worst, but we will be disadvantaged by our governments long-term response.
text_long_wave3: I feel angry that precautions have been completely removed whilst infections remain extremely high. I feel less than safe in crowded places where the majority of people do not wear masks. It seems to me that other political interests have once again been given higher priority by the government than public safety, particularly the safety of vulnerable people who have been abandoned. Whilst I appreciate the eagerness to go back to normal, it could and should have been handled much more carefully. It is frustrating to see the UK once again doing this differently to other countries and I fear the outcome of that could be more infections and more deaths.
text_short_wave3: Whilst I'm appreciative to see restrictions easing, I feel we should still be taking sensible precautions (masks, working from home) wherever possible in order to preserve the freedoms we all value.

It feels a little claustrophobic at times being stuck indoors.
I feel that it will take a lot longer than most people think to get back to normal, with a longer lockdown than anticipated.

text_long_wave1:
I have conflicting feelings.

What's happening in the world is horrible, there's no doubt about that, it incredibly sad to see and hear of so many deaths in the world because of this awful disease and I really do hope that we find a way to contain/cure this soon and save as many lives as possible.

Looking for a silver lining, however, I'm working from home and my mental health has massively improved because of it. My day usually involves waking at 5am, driving 30 miles to work usually stressing out in traffic, and once I get to work I'm tired before I've even started, then I have to do it again in the evening, usually getting home late in the evening, not having time to cook properly because I just want a few hours on the couch to switch off before I have to go to bed and get up at 5am again.
With my current working from home situation, I'm getting twice as much sleep as I normally do (usually only get around 4 or 5 hours tops), I'm not stressed and tired from driving for over an hour, I'm able to switch off at a reason time in the early evening and actually cook healthier meals, spend more time with my partner etc.
So although the whole reason we're in this mess is awful, by being forced to stay home and work, my mental and physical health has hugely improved.
text_short_wave1: Praying for all of the family affected by this awful disease, and that we find a cure soon. Huge respect to the key workers keeping us safe during this difficult time. Stay home, save lives!
text_long_wave2:
I have had mixed feelings about Covid from the start. I've followed all the advice, taken all precautions etc so I'm sad to see such a devastating effect it's had on millions of families around the world, from death to financial losses.

On the flip side to this, I am quite an independent person who genuinely likes to stay in, watch movies, play games, play the guitar, work on my garden etc - so having the pressure of being a 30 something who is usually socially expected to be 'out and about' all the time taken away from me has made me more relaxed.

I also think that Covid in a way has saved my life. I haven't had the virus myself, but the shift in working from home and offering that flexibility in working hours and locations has been a game changer for me. I'm no longer getting up at 5am every day to do a 1 hour commute to work and being tired before I've begun, and then doing it again at the end of a long day. I get more sleep, I am more rested, I save hundreds of pounds extra a month from being at home rather than commuting, and I get to spend more time with my partner - the work/life balance has never ever been better for me which has led to me being more happy

I'm happy to get boosters, and I will probably even wear masks in the winter months going forward, but I'm not as worried about Covid compared to two years ago.

There is a lot of misinformation which is very frustrating. A lot of squabbling about hoarding and how long it is appropriate to exercise for. It’s difficult to tear myself away from social media and news - I know it’s not helpful for my mental health, it’s exhausting but it’s compulsive.

I feel hopeful that we can get back to some sort of normality again, see people etc, at some point in the future. Vaccines are very hopeful and positive. It’s frustrating to not know when that time will be but understand that for the good of everyone it is what it is.

I don’t have anything more to say but trying to make up the 500 characters and again trying to make up the 500 characters. Want to say something meaningful.
text_short_wave2: A whole year of Covid. So many sacrifices made, so many lives lost, so many people kept apart. Feeling hopeful that we’ll one day return to whatever ‘normal’ is. Looking forward to hugs again when the time is right.
text_long_wave3:
The situation is frustrating as the government says it’s all over, yet people are still getting it. It’s a real risk for vulnerable people. Long Covid is a real risk too. I worry we may be back to square one before long.
I’m continuing to wear a mask in shops etc to protect myself and others.

I don’t know what else to add. I don’t know what else to add. I don’t know what else to add. I don’t know what else to add. I don’t know what else to add so am trying to make this 500 characters. It’s difficult to know what else to say, I tend to write in a concise way.

text_long_wave3:
It is driving me quietly mad that people seem to think the pandemic is over. It is not over. Cases are rising, again; people are being hospitalised, again; people are dying, still. No matter how much our useless government wants to stick their fingers in their ears and pretend it's not happening... it is.

PLus I'm a bit fed up of being stuck inside, not being able to go anywhere.

text_long_wave3:
I mostly feel sad that hardly anyone cares about vulnerable people with compromised immune systems. It's really not difficult to wear a mask indoors (in poorly ventilated areas at least), yet hardly anyone does. I understand that people have had enough, and have been through enough, but Covid can still be serious, even if you have had the vaccinations etc. My household caught Covid a couple of months ago. I think I still have brain fog, and my daughter (too young for the vaccine) has been ill twice since then (once I had to call the NHS number because I was so worried). Both times she had Covid symptoms but tested negative. 

I also feel quite confused. I think there is more to Covid than the general public know about. Something doesnt add up. There will be a reason why globally, restrictions are being lifted even though deaths and cases are still high. And why the UK leaders were having parties while the rest of us were only allowed to leave the house once a day for exercise. 

I am more concerned about the effects of long covid than anything else. We won't know the full effects for years, as many may be long-term and might not be visible yet. I read an article yesterday that there is an increase in children with hepatitis caused by a virus, and the author was very confused as to what could have possibly caused it (in the UK, EU and US). A virus? What could it be? 

SUmmary - sadness at the lack of thought for others, confusion that the overall situation doesn't make sense, and concern about the long term impact.
text_short_wave3: Covid can cause long term health problems and can be spread to those who have had it before and the vaccinated. It can mutate when spreading. Why is the official message now """"""""Covid is over""""""""? What am I missing?

I am concerned for the ill and especially the vulnerable who may suffer in the future. I am also sad about the poor government preperation and response to the pandemic - I believe that its effects in the UK would be less had preventative actions been taken.

I also think the media response has been somewhat mixed. While it is indeed sad that the Prime Minister is in hospital suffering with the corona virus, he and his government have consistently damaged the NHS's ability to act correctly and his own lacklustre leadership has only cemented this. His """"""""herd immunity"""""""" strategy all of a sudden doesn't seem so smart when he and his ministers realise their wealth and power doesn't put them above the rest of the herd, does it?

text_long_wave2:
With vaccination against the virus now possible I feel there may be an end in sight to the long period of lockdown. I think that the virus will not go away fully however, and would not be surprised if new variants continue to emerge and Corona flare ups become similar to flu in the winter, especially if there are incidents where strains not affected by the vaccine develop.

I also wonder if the governments responsible for large numbers of deaths (e.g. the US & UK) will be called to account for their poor handling of this crisis when compared to others who were much more successful in their dealing with it (e.g. New Zealand).
text_short_wave2: Is the end in sight? Will Corona finally be vanquished via vaccination this year and life can return to some form of normality?
text_long_wave3:
I feel that people have largely forgotten it exists due the government declaring it """"""""over"""""""", despite the fact infections continue to occur and people continue to be hospitalised & die of Covid. This makes me feel somewhat angry & upset, especially with the evidence that government officials ignored the rules during the pandemic (e.g. Partygate, PPE contracts) but due to other events in the world such as the Ukraine invasion this is all getting ignored.

I feel that Covid deaths will rise again as further mutations arise or the weather turns colder again - becoming a seasonal occurrence, but I think that officials are unlikely to have additional lockdowns or any preventative measures. 

I think that the pandemic also exposed an ugly side to our society, with anti-maskers/vaxxers feeling emboldened to thrust their views onto others in unpleasant ways and with no credible evidence to back them up.

This goes against infection control procedures which we are used to using and is worrying  for when we do get confirmed cases. It feels like the NHs is not fully prepared in the area where I live.

I feel calm and sensible. I understand the risks and I follow the NHS guidance of limiting my time outside of my home and practising social distancing when I am out and about. 

Covid-19 will be with us for a long time and we must be calm and rational in how we deal with everyday life.

I am currently working from home with ease. I keep in regular contact with work colleagues and friends and family using video conferencing. I live with my wife, so I don't suffer from any self-isolation issues. We have regular chats about the current situation. 

I feel wider society need to play their part by respecting the rules of social distancing and not leaving the home for unnecessary trips.

I feel that after this crisis is over key workers and NHS staff will be more valued than ever.

I've also lost a close friend to cancer in the last couple of months, and have felt robbed of seeing him during his last few months, and frustrated at not being able to give our mutual friends and his husband a hug at the funeral. text_long_wave1: I am one of the people who got a letter saying to stay in for 12 weeks so for me I am not anxious about when the lockdown will end because it won't end for me. I have severe asthma so I am a bit worried about getting it because I have a high risk of needing ventilation and of dying from it. Staying in really isn't an issue for me. I have been living with chronic illness since I was 12 and at my worst I was housebound for 2 years as a teenager so this is nothing compared to that. It has actually been annoying and anger inducing to see so many people complain about the lockdown and staying in, especially if they are middle class/rich with nothing to really worry about, when I have been through worse and was completely ignored and forgotten about like so many others and the key workers are going through much worse too. People are finally experiencing what it is like to live as a disabled person where you have to cancel and grieve for events, stay in for days at a time and survive on what little money the government decides is enough for a week. But still these people can go out and exercise and we still can't. It is also very anger-inducing to see so many people flaunt the rules and go out for BBQs and sunbathing. Also plenty of people going out for 'exercise' are gathering in groups and not observing the 2-meter distance with strangers. I also find it sad that the scientific literacy is so poor in this country. People really don't understand simple things that are being told to them about how the virus works, the symptoms, when to self isolate and what the lockdown means. People are dying every day because of this stupidity. There are also way too many stupid people trying to take down 5G masts because they are transmitting the virus. There are no words for that level. I find there is a bit of toxic positivity and toxic productivity on facebook and social media in general. Like people sharing the numbers of recovered to focus on the positives because everyone else is talking about how many died when these deaths matter. It isn't just the flu. A few days ago a 13 year old died alone and now he has been buried alone with no funeral. I don't want to hear about the recovered because that shouldn't be the focus and people need to be more scared and panicked so they stay indoors and don't get complacent. There should be video from the ICUs on the TV every night to make people think. Many of my friends are taking up new hobbies and getting round to decluttering and finishing those jobs around the house you never end up doing. This is great for them and I am happy they can have some time where they aren't burned out by work constantly but it makes me feel bad because I can't do that. Being as ill as I am is like a full time job and my spare energy goes on cooking, showering and if I am lucky cleaning. I had a migraine yesterday and the most I managed to do was water my plants. I won't be joining my friends in fun creative pursuits and making my space nicer to live in during the lockdown.   I have had some darker thoughts too that maybe we deserve this. I don't believe in any higher power or some personification of mother nature but this has revealed the true nature of humanity in the west. When this started at first people just got really racist ranging from joking about Kung Flu to actually beating up ethnically Chinese people who may never have been to China. Then there was the panic buying of everyone for themselves and protecting their own and screw the rest. A week later I saw images of bins filled with rotting food they had over-purchased whilst elderly and disabled people went hungry because there was nothing in the shops or they couldn't book an online slot. Panic buying continued at pharmacies and now people are short on necessary prescription medication. And now there are people breaking social distancing for selfish reasons like when everyone treated it like a bank holiday and went to Mount Snowdon or just didn't bother because they would be fine if they got the virus. No care about those of us who are the worst affected. Even my aunt who is a nurse went out whilst having the virus to get shopping and medication and could have spread it to many more. It is just a shame that this virus disproportionately affects the elderly and sick and doesn't target selfish and stupid people instead. Now my main worry is about the antibody test because the government wants to get the country and the economy going because money matters most and will possibly allow those who are immune back to work and leave the rest of us behind. It could be that the healthy and young can go back to work and I will still be left behind until there is a vaccine. I really can't risk my life and will lose even more of it than I already have to illness if most people go back to normal. Right now everyone has been dragged nearer to my level so for me that feels okay and something I can live with. My friends are doing virtual socials and chatting online more when usually I have to cancel party invitations and skip nights out. I do have an academic interest in this too as I studied infectious diseases before so it has been frustrating to see the government go against a lot of public health research but interesting to read the latest articles on the biology of the virus. I am probably one of the few who is not getting scared at reading about the virus itself even though I am susceptible to it
text_short_wave1: To everyone complaining about the lockdown and wanting to go and sunbathe: Stop being so selfish. Us disabled lot have been doing it for years so you can cope for a few weeks without the sun. It isn't worth killing a load of people over a tan #covidiots
text_long_wave2: I feel very conflicted right now. I am hopeful for the future and about to have my vaccine and can see some things returning to normal. I am also realistic and I follow a lot of scientists on this and know that the vaccine is unlikely to be the end of the pandemic as most 3rd world countries will have to wait years for it and there will be those who refuse it. Plus the virus will mutate and the vaccine gives evolutionary pressure yet we aren't looking at permanent vaccination centres or how we would deal with this. I have been shielding for nearly a year now and want to feel safe but I feel most people my age just want to go back to the pub. I also feel that disabled people have been largely forgotten. I'm finding it a little more bearable than a week ago, because there is not quite so much overload of scary information and situations getting exponentially more dramatic - BUT still preoccupied every minute of the day because of the threat to myself and those I know in my age group. So whereas at the start I was wanting to communicate with friends and family, making sure they were ok and being sensible, now it's the getting through it stage. And that is fairly dull and saddening, thinking of all the things in life one is missing out on, on a beautiful warm day in the country.

But let's be clear, the real anxiety-inducing factor is when the politicians and their advisors look like screwing up. I was completely panicked when they talked glibly about the herd immunity strategy, because it was obviously a mass experiment without informed consent. And every day I try not to watch the 5pm briefing, because the performance of Raab, Whitty, Harris etc makes me even more concerned they are inadequate to deal with a national emergency. And that makes me anxious again. I was quite calm today until I caught a few minutes of their latest performance. Some of those mentioned above would be overpromoted if they were in charge of a bank branch in a small provincial town.

text_long_wave2:
Well of course I am thankful just to be alive ... but so saddened by the wasted year and the separation from those dearest to me. I detest our government for mismanaging it so grossly and directly causing tens of thousands to die needlessly by choices it was warned against. And I feel sad and anxious that activities that mean the most to me - travel especially - may not be possible for a while, or in similar ways as before.
I feel the virus has found out all the weak spots in our society and in our lives - it's prised open a gap between me and my partner because I respect the rules and she does not.
I feel it has left me like a desert island castaway, living in fairly miserable solitary conditions, but still thankful to be alive. And I do not trust the  vaccines not to be the ship that appears on the horizon and then passes by - not that the vaccines themselves are not wonderful  (they are), but I don't trust our government, or other governments, not to screw up exiting the situation, and set off a third wave of vaccine-resistant variants.
I also have to come to terms with the long-term impact on my aspirations and life choices. I have had to abandon plans to relocate to Europe before Brexit, and have to reorientate to a new situation where work from home may be much more common (the latter is no bad thing, but it's a big readjustment).
In short, I feel I am trapped on plague island, and governed by incompetent charlatans.
text_short_wave2: stuck on plague island

text_long_wave3:
I remain very pessimistic about the lack of sound public health management by the UK government that has led to 166k excess deaths so far during the pandemic (figures just released). While the immediate risk of serious immediate consequences for triple vaxxed adults from omicron is very low, allowing such wide circulation of the virus by removing all restrictions and ending free testing is a recipe for new and more sesrious variants. It means that those who wish to protect themselves must continue with an abnormally restricted life. If even modest measures (masking on pulic transport, free testing, legal requirement to isolate) had remained, we could have reduced circulation to much lower levels.

And no one knows the long-term systemic consequences of this pathogen, which could lead to a generation of low-level disability (Prof Danny Altmann today) placing huge strain of heathcare resources.

But that's what you get for having the worst possible Prime Minister at the worst possible time.

text_short_wave1: Im doing better now, numbers (whilst not truely accurate, due to a lack of testing) are still pretty scary.  Lockdown will probably last a few months more, by which time numbers will flatten out hopefully.
text_long_wave2: I would say I am cautiosly optimistic currently, as I feel that progress is slowly being made and we are through the worst the pandemic.  There is stil a way to go yet, but I am hopeful that within about 6 months the world will be mostly back to some sort of normal.  I'm still appauled at the way the government handled it from the start - a great many lives have been lost that could've been easily avoided with proper management of the situation.  I appreciate that it is an unprecedented event recent history, but it is very much an expected event in long-history: humankind encounters pandemics like this every 100-200 years, so we knew it was coming - we had been warned years ago by people like Bill Gates and virologists and generally more globally aware people etc ...at least now we would be better prepared for the next one.
text_short_wave2: I believe we are through the worst of this, but now is not a time to relax any social distancing or hygeine practices.  If only we humans would using animals(SARS, MRSA, Bird Flu, Swine Flu, Foot and Mouth, Covid etc) - all due to our interactions with animals.  Enough is enough
text_long_wave3: Thankfully I haven't contracted covid yet - I know many who have and I've lost a few friends during the pandemic.  I still wear a mask in shops, wash my hands often etc (always did anyway, is basic hygeine).  I notice most people in shops don't wear masks anymore which is frustrating.  It isn't over yet, despite many people acting like it is.  I expect everyone will catch it at somepoint and it is just a matter of time...thanks to the vaccines, I'm hoping if/when I do it will be a mild flu like experience (I'm asthmatic and rather scared of catching it)
text_short_wave3: It isn't over yet!  Keep wearing masks, washing hands and stay safe!

text_long_wave1: I'm feeling sad for friends who've lost people they love. I'm worried for my elderly father, aunts and uncles and for friends who are older or who have health concerns. And I'm concerned for myself because I have underlying health concerns, and the media seems to be daily assuming lives like mine are less important. I feel disposable to society. And I'm angry that Boris Johnson didn't act sooner to save lives.
text_short_wave1: So many people are losing loved ones. The NHS are fighting to save us. Stay home.
text_long_wave2: At the moment I am weary of the situation. I have tried to keep very carefully to the rules. I am high-risk, and a year of the media acting as though my life is less important has been very difficult. I am missing my family, my friends, swimming, eating out, seeing my colleagues and mooching around charity shops on rainy afternoons. I am also incredibly frustrated by the people I see breaking the rules and acting as though Covid-19 is a joke. I want this to be over, and they get in the way of that.
text_short_wave2: This feels like it has been going on forever. I desperately want to give my elderly dad a hug. Every time I see someone breaking restrictions I want to tell them that they're making this go on even longer for the rest of us.
text_long_wave3: I am aware that I am still at moderately high risk. I've had three injections, but I'm aware that my immunity is waning and that cases are rising - two close friends have had it in the last week. One has been hospitalised. So, I am still anxious, but I'm aware that the general expectation is that we all 'move on'. I don't feel like it's over, but everyone else seems to? I also feel that there should be more air filtration systems in workplaces and schools, and that we should still be wearing masks when in crowded indoor spaces.

I wish people would stop being selfish and just stay at home to minimise the spread. I'm angry at the government for how poorly they've handled the situation, and wish that they'd looked at how well other countries were doing and followed their lead.

text_long_wave1:
It is frustrating not knowing when it will end or when things will get back to normal, or even if they will get back to normal. It's hard to believe it won't change society in a fairly major way, although it's impossible to say how.

At the moment, it feels like everything and everyone is in a state of limbo and only experiencing a half-life.

I would say I currently have a permanent sense of low-level anxiety.

I am also angry that the government has clearly not taken this seriously and, even now, isn't doing the things it needs to, in terms of supplying PPE, testing and respirators in the necessary quantities.
text_short_wave1: The sooner this is over, the better. I'm starting to feel like I'm going slightly mad.
text_long_wave2:
Things seem to be looking more promising, thanks to the vaccination programme but, with a 3rd wave feared in mainland Europe and schools having reopened here, as well as mutant variants, things could turn bad again.

There's also the fact that few people have received their second dose of the vaccine yet. Until that happens, there still have to be concerns.

Personally, I feel I can make it through this period without getting infected (assuming I've not already had the disease), provided I continue to take sensible precautions.
text_short_wave2: The situation seems to be improving but we all need to keep being careful. It wouldn't take much for things to turn nasty again, and there's still along road ahead of us.
text_long_wave3: At the moment, I am unsure where I, or others, stand. The way I feel in my head and the mood I get from other people when I'm out and about makes It feels like the pandemic is as good as over. Having said that, the number of cases and hospitalisations is on the rise again, and the number of deaths may also soon start to rise. On top of that, there is  a new variant on the loose and I am not clear as to whether that is more dangerous than previous variants. Because of all this, there is, therefore, plenty of uncertainty as to what the future is going to hold and I hope to be getting another booster jab in the coming weeks.
text_short_wave3: Given that there is a new variant on the loose, and the number of infections is on the rise, it's hard to know how to feel, right now.

text_long_wave1:
I have various feelings about this.
1. I am anxious on a personal level because myself and my wife both have health conditions which make us potentially vulnerable to this virus, and so we are doing everything we can to minimize risk.
2. I am also anxious for the country, and the world, as I see health services at full stretch and struggling.  I am also concerned for all those at risk of losing their jobs and livelihoods.
3. I am sad for all those who have lost their lives, and for their families and loved ones.  I am also sad for all those who have lost their jobs and livelihoods or are suffering financial hardship.
5. I am concerned for all those living in countries where available funds and health provision are woefully insefficient to protect the population.
6. I am angry with our Conservative government for cutting back on our health service during the last 10 years, and for failing to prepare for such a pandemic.  As a consequence our NHS is stretched to the limit and the staff are under huger pressure.  I am also angry that the government have failed to provide adequate PPE or testing, placing NHS staff in danger, and exacerbating the spread of the virus.  I am also angry that the government initially had a reckless dangerous strategy to let the virus freely infect the population, which would have killed hundreds of thousands of people.  Even when they changed strategy and began to take measures to control the virus they acted too slowly, again exacerbating the situation and costing lives.
text_short_wave1: Angry with the government for their pathetic response to the crisis, but impresses with the people for rising to the challenge, especially NHS staff.  We will get throuhg this...
text_long_wave2: I am sad that so many people have suffered and died from Coronavirus. I am proud of the effort so many people have made in the interestes of the public good.  I am also angry that our government handled it so bacly and condemned tens of thousands of people to death.  I am also a bit anxious about how the government is going to deal with the huge debt incurred, and that the poor will take the brunt of it. But I am also now starting to feel a sense of optimism that, with the vaccine programme going well, that we are close to getting back to some kind of normality soon.
text_short_wave2: We are almost there.  We can do this!
text_long_wave3: I don't feel the same amount of fear about getting the virus, in terms of health impace because I have had all the vaccinations and boosters.  Having said that my wife, who is considered extremely vulnerable cannot be certain that the vaccinations will offer full protection to her, so some unease about that is still present.  I practical terms I feel frustrated and slightly anxious about getting the virus because I am constantly tested by the companies I work for (in the film industry).  If I test positive I will lose jobs and money, as happened to me in January 2021.  So I have to remain as isolated as possible from other people as is practical, so no socialising.  It's frustrating that all the restrictions have been lifted as people not wearing masks threatens my livelihood.
text_short_wave3: Please continue to be sensible and wear masks, as the virus is a threat to my job and livelihood.

I am at home at the moment, with my family, and none of us yet have experienced any illness.

However we are all locked down in the UK at the moment and I am sad that I cannot see my usual friends and family.

We are making the best of it by keeping busy, and trying to eat well, but it’s a constant worry there, as I have asthma so may not fade to well.

Seeing the numbers of dead shooting up across the world every day brings me great sadness for those people and their loved ones, and particularly worry that it may also take someone I know.

We are actually quite content at home without thinking of the wider picture, and I feel that we are very lucky. We have enough food and things to keep us entertained, and we all get along very well, so actually spending more time together is very lovely, apart from the low level anxiety whenever we tv ink about what is happening.

I have had my first dose of vaccine, which helps reduce my anxiety, but I do have some younger family members not vaccinated yet.  Older members of my family have had their vaccines, some both doses, so that really does reduce my anxiety about their health.

text_long_wave2: At this exact moment I feel weary of Corona - I am a community nurse manager and just home from a night shift I had to work at short notice (again) as I could not find cover for staff shielding or off sick with covid. I am tired of nagging my team about PPE and other trust rules, tired of following those rules myself, weary of all the extra time every simple task takes, weary of trying to reassure patients and families and keep myself and my team safe. My community NHS trust has gone above and beyond to keep us as safe as they can - not all covid patients are in hospital - I cannot fault their efforts, but they can’t knit me any nurses to replace those told to shield or who are isolating or ill or who have retired early because they can’t take the pressure of covid anymore. I am angry at people who think the rules don’t apply to them and mix with friends and family because they are ‘OK’ and they are ‘safe’, angry at a small number of colleagues who claim to be such high risk they must not see covid patients under any circumstances yet have refused to be vaccinated, upset for their colleagues, some equally at risk,  who then have to take more than their fair share of the ‘covid team’ to cover for these fools, but overall I am just very very weary and would walk out of this job tomorrow given the chance. text_long_wave1: The uncertainty of this unprecedented situation is deeply worrying. It is the uncertainty that unsettles me the most. How many people will ultimately be affected physically? What will the final mortality number be? What will we be able to learn and ascertain about the virus itself? How will our economy recover? Has anyone thought of the added bill to the NHS for the impending mental health issues this may all cause? It's all just so unknown and the fear of the unknown is the biggest of all. Personally speaking, I feel extremely fortunate to not feel affected though that too may change. My children are thankfully healthy and my parents, too. I was looking after my mother after she sustained a subarachnoid haemorrhage, she was discharged from hospital 3 weeks ago which is unbelievably fortunate timing. We feel very lucky that she managed to get home.
text_short_wave1: Focus on the positives & don't lose sight of the happy stuff. It's too easy to get bogged down, we all still have a lot to be thankful for!
text_long_wave2: I feel that this third lockdown has been lifted too soon, we are nowhere near out of the woods yet despite the roll out of the vaccination. I am incredibly concerned about schools reopening next week also, I think this is a step in the wrong direction. On a positive note though, I feel that Rishi Sunak has done an outstanding job in dealing with the situation and cannot praise him enough. Yes, not everyone is happy and there will always be someone left out, but he was under a baptism of fire over the last 18 months and has been outstandingly fair.
text_short_wave2: The reopening of schools is a step backward, inviting yet another wave to ensue.
text_long_wave3: I feel as though people think it is is all over, but it is not and may never be anything more than 'under control'. Until it gets to the stage of being controlled like the Flu, we should continue treating it as a threat. Now that I am triple vaccinated this makes me feel like I am well protected against the virus and this makes me feel like I can start to move on from the past two years and start to live my life more, it makes me excited that I can now go on holiday without any worries such as isolating or taking test before and after.

I feel that this coronavirus situation is a very ugly event for humanity. I also feel that it could end up killing tens of thousands, potentially even hundreds of thousands if preventative measures aren't taken.

However, I also believe that we will get through this and be stronger in the end. Hopefully, it will also lead to long term changes in how we work, the economy, etc. I also think that there will be a lot of research done into this virus and how to prevent such a thing from happening again (as well as general virology research).

Finally I'd say that I do worry a little about my elderly father. Even though he has had his first COVID vaccine dose, he may still be vulnerable, especially as he has lung issues.

At the moment I am really sick of Corona virus, I feel it has taken over peoples live and has now gone on so long! 
I want life to go back to normal and try and have some of our lives back. It has massively impacted my children’s lives and their education and also the impact of not seeing their families. My job has been put on hold as I work in a school, I had received a promotion not long before the first lockdown happened. Then it happened and I feel I never had time to show myself. Which I very frustrating. My husband also works for the NHS and he has been working extremely long hours, which has resulted in him not seeing the kids much which we understand but it is really hard.
text_short_wave2: Whilst I understand how awful Covid is and how much some people have lost I am feeling now that It is impacting our children regarding their education. I want what is best for my children and I worry about what they are missing out on with education. Fingers crossed it sorts out!

I feel I have just gotten used to it, I feel there are more important things happening in the world at the present time which are more worrying. Like the war which is currently happening in Ukraine. To me it is a very volatile situation at present, it really upsets and maddens me to see what the people are going through, it feels like as soon as we pass one negative thing another one just seems to be there waiting!

text_long_wave2:
I am very concerned that despite all the actions taken over the past year, mutations within the virus mean we are no better off. I worry about having to keep restrictions going indefinitely and the impact on the country economically and socially; but if we don't I worry about the effect on people's health, the NHS will be overwhelmed and a lot of people will die.
On a personal level, I miss family and friends,band I'm currently pregnant and very worried about what contracting Corona would mean for my baby.
text_short_wave2: Light at the end of the tunnel seems further and further off, I'm scared for the country and for my baby.
text_long_wave3: I feel angry and frustrated that for reasons of political opportunism our country has effectively declared the pandemic over, and is trying to maintain we can live life as we did two years ago. Rates are going up and up, the NHS is on its knees, and we're being told there is no need to isolate or take any precautions. I'm angry at the way rich countries have treated poorer countries, leaving them pretty much unvaccinated. I'm angry and perplexed that official guidance seems to ignore the fact the virus is airborne. We no longer live in a precovid world, we need to change the way we ventilate buildings just as the Victorians had to create proper sewerage systems to get rid of cholera. We need to properly resource care for all the people left with ongoing symptoms. Yet bone if this is happening, and the health secretary says rising case rates are not a concern! Soon we won't even know what the case rater are because testing is stopping and they aren't funding ONS and ZOE. It's almost Orwellian in scope. I'm just despairing and very afraid for the future.
text_short_wave3: We cannot return to a precovid world - we must properly resource masks, testing, ventilation, worldwide vaccination and medical care for those with ongoing symptoms to provide everyone with the best possible postcovid world.

I support the UK governments’ current strategy but wish that the lockdown had been implemented at least a week sooner. The warning signs from Italy and Spain were plain for all to see. I also don’t entirely believe the figures released from China and suspect the infection rates and overall death toll is far higher than reported. 

Since the lockdown being implemented, it has really frustrated me to see some people still ignoring the rules (gathering in parks, on beaches etc.) but on the whole, the vast majority of the public are complying. I worry about the exit strategy and whether or not there will be another wave of infections before winter. Although research on vaccines has been swift (it’s been fantastic to see the world pulling together on this) it won’t really be able to help for at least 18 months. 

Finally, I’m also extremely worried about the economy and how long the inevitable damage to that will last.

However, I do worry about the problem on a global scale, especially how vaccines programs will progress in poorer nations. Corona is the world’s problem.

In the UK, most of the restrictions have been lifted. Life is getting back to normal. The same trend is happening all over the world. Hopefully what has been learned from this crisis will help us better react when a similar one emerges in the future. Time will tell how fast we can recover from the damages done the economy and to the people by the way the government has managed the situation.
text_short_wave3: COVID is over, please resume your normal life. And please, next time, do not let fear drive your behaviour.

text_long_wave1:
I am worried and sad about the current Corona situations. I've had to close my business until further notices which I completely understand but I'm also sad about it as I love what I do. 

I am worried about friends and family. I have a relative in a care home and we know that if he gets the disease then it is very unlikely that he'll survive. This makes me feel extremely sad and also guilty that I can't visit him though I understand the reasons why I can't.

I'm also worried about a number of people that I know that live with mental ill health. They are struggling, really struggling and I do what I can by texting and talking to them.

I'm also very proud of my family. My children are now home from university. One of them is waiting to hear about what is happening with her finals and the other is in his first year. I couldn't be prouder of how they are responding to the virus. They are both doing everything they should and shouldn't be doing and they are being very supportive and helping keep morale high in our house. 

Sad, anxious, worried but proud.
text_short_wave1: Stay home, stay safe and help protect our NHS. This is serious, people are dying. Phone friends and family. Keep in touch but don't meet up. Sad and scary times but we can get through this if we stay home!
text_long_wave2: The corona situation makes me feel slightly anxious. I am worried that there may be another wave and I've already had to shut my business for 8 months in the last year due to the virus. The lockdowns have also made me feel proud of myself. Early on I decided that I would live the best life I could during lockdowns and use the time to evaluate what I want with my life.  There are aspects I will take forward such as living in the moment more and making sure I make time for me after this is over which I didn't do much before.   I appreciate things more. I realise how much much I love my business, my family and my friends. It has been an appalling year but I have come through it stronger than I was and I glad I had the opportunity to make the most of this year.
text_short_wave2: #covid Feelings hopeful we're moving towards normality. Sending love and luck to everyone going back to school tomorrow...the start of getting our freedom back. First #vaccination last week...moving towards brighter days? FIngers crossed
text_long_wave3: I can't believe the coronavirus is still so prevalent in our lives. I no longer fear catching it, despite never having it yet, but the number of changes to my business does make me anxious.  Clients are having to cancel in much larger numbers as they choose not to have treatments when they have the virus.  I'd much rather they did cancel.  It just means that I don't know, from one day to the next, how much money I'll be earning.  Yesterday and today everyone cancelled.  Bills are getting higher and I seem to earn less.  At least I am doing some work though and that keeps me positive.  This is  much better than lockdown when I couldn't work at all.  We will get through this.  I will get through it.
text_short_wave3: Feels like I throw all my appointments in the air and see how they land.  Some fall on other days. Some miss the diary completely.  This happens daily.  I am one of the lucky ones.  I AM one of the lucky ones but aghhhhhhh! And breathe.
life_event_descr_wave3: The virus itself.  It bought friends and family together, Great sadness but also friendship, love, care and filtered away what I didn't need anymore.
life_event_descr: I just feel closer to my husband and son as we have spent so much time together. It has been lovely being close.

text_long_wave1: Feeling trapped within the house, anxious and irritable. Fear fueled by the news. No end in sight. Conflicting information form the government and a constant list of government advisors in the media. Feel like health is suffering, can't get teeth checked. For situation means not able to shop for the healthiest diet. Exercise is severely limited. House is dark and am desperate for fresh air. Not able to see my family or friends. The children are struggling not been able to see their friends. Money worries and the future is not available to view.
text_short_wave1: Trapped, no control, anxious, worried and can't do the best for my family. There is no future
text_long_wave2:
At this moment I feel a lot of sadness, as it's been a year since we started lockdown, this 'anniversary ' has caused me to reflect. It will be another of my nephews birthdays we will miss been together (27th March). I'm organising a gift this morning to send to his house, as cannot visit again.
My children have been in school for this lockdown, previously weren't. All their class friends went back with them yrsterday, the excitement. I worry that by autumn they will be off again. This horrid virus has robbed us of what it means to be a human, hug, spend time with family. Feeling very sad today.
text_short_wave2: Trying to find the strength to keep hope and optimism alive for the coming months.
text_long_wave3: At this moment I feel anxious. Although a lot of things have returned to normal, I do feel like I am waiting for the next thing to happen, be it a new variant or mutation and everything which follows on from that. My daughter currently has Covid, she is only 11 years old and has been really unwell. Angry that people say kids don't get affected by it, they really do. Confused how she has it, but the rest of us (3) haven't been affected. There don't appear to be any clear, concrete facts about Covid, what it does and how it affects us.
text_short_wave3: All the information and guidance I've been told about Covid doesn't feel true. How can I cuddle my very sick child for hours and not catch it. Children can get really ill. Just waiting for the next variant. What is the truth?
life_event_descr_wave3: Moved house during the first lockdown, May 2020. House needed builders, plummers and no cooker.
life_event_descr: We have had to miss seeing our grandchildren

text_long_wave1:
I'm more worried about mum catching it than anything else.  She's in her 70s and has a hole in her heart so has always suffered difficulties with her breathing and cannot walk far without getting out of breath.  

I've also read a lot of stories lately about people who've been out once or twice since lockdown and have still caught it, so I'm worried about catching it myself and unknowingly passing it on to mum.

Those are my main concerns right now.  I actually don't mind the whole self-isolation thing as I'm happy with my own company and have lots I can do at home.  I'm also able to work from home which alleviates any financial worries.
text_short_wave1: For God's sake just #stayathome!  It's not about you, it's about protecting our loved ones and those who are most vulnerable, and not putting an unnecessary strain on the NHS.
text_long_wave2: To be honest, I'm completely fed up with it now, I just want to be able to travel and see my friends and family.  I'm feeling a little less anxious now that my mum (who is high risk) has had her first vaccine but I'll be happier still once she's had her second.  I have enjoyed getting to know my local area better, discovering new running routes and doing some work on my house, but I'm more than ready to get back to normal again now.  Apart from the work aspect.  I'd be quite happy to work half my week from home on a permanent basis.
text_short_wave2: Totally fed up with #covid19 now...I just want to be able to travel again now and to see my family and friends :-(
text_long_wave3: I'm pleased that restrictions are lifting and that I can travel again, and I have been taking full advantage of this over the past few months.  I am also happy that I can meet up with friends and family socially.  I've had covid and didn't get any symptoms and I'm aware that most people I know who've had it have had very mild symptoms, so this has meant that I am no longer feeling as anxious about it as I did.  I am still continuing to wear a mask in busy places though and on public transport, in order to reduce my risk of catching it again.
text_short_wave3: Third month of the year, third trip of the year.  After two years of restrictions, I'm feeling happy that I am finally able to travel again.
life_event_descr: I started developing anxiety and got panic attacks which got worse as covid started
life_event_descr_2: Started seeing a therapist, which in addition to helping with anxiety helped me handle the pandemic

text_long_wave1: I feel sad that so many people are dying with this virus, and all the health professionals struggling to keep as many people alive as they can. My health isn't the best and I have to make sure I stay indoors so I can be safe and not catch the virus.  It can be a little scary and annoying seeing some people disobeying the rules and still going out and acting like everything is ok.
text_short_wave1: So sad, so many people dying and yet some are ignorant enough to ignore guidelines

text_long_wave3: I feel very anxious and afraid regarding Corona.  I have lost close relatives over the past two years and it has increased our anxiety.  I am afraid I will contract it and be seriously ill.  I also worry about my wife and children contracting Corona, and the effect it will have on them, in the short term and log term.  We continue to wear masks and use sanitisers everywhere we go.  Even being fully vaccinated we are still anxious and worried, as close friends have still contracted Corona after getting all their vaccines.
text_short_wave3: I am anxious, worried and afraid regarding the Corona situation.
life_event_descr_wave3: The passing of close family and friends due to Corona
life_event_descr_2_wave3: Again a passing of another close family member

text_long_wave1: I am worried about the virus but for the first time today I feel more like my normal self. My husband left his work and he contacted them to ask if he could be reinstated and furloughed. They said yes! So I am so happy we are at least getting 80% of the wages. Universal Credit just would not have been enough. The last few weeks I have not felt myself. I have thought about my relationship with my husband in a negative way. We have two children and have not gone out for three weeks. The sun was out today, we had a chat with a neighbour over the fence and things are looking ok finance-wise. I have heard on the news that the number of deaths has dropped slightly and that has given me hope. Cross fingers.
text_short_wave1: We are all just about managing. Keep smiling. Get out in the sunshine (for a brief while) and it will be ok.
text_long_wave2: I have had my first vaccination but my husband hasn't. He restarts work on Monday 8th March and I am worried the virus will increase within the community and will put him at risk. This makes me really scared. I am also worried that the EU will withhold the AstraZeneca vaccines from the UK and we will be short of the vaccine. I have seen what they have done to Australia. I am therefore worried that we will suffer and see more deaths. I also have an elderly mother who is suffering mentally with not seeing family.
text_short_wave2: How long is this going to go on for? I see a light at the end of the tunnel but the light seems to fade as we get nearer. There is always something holding us back.
text_long_wave3: I think the situation is muched improved and I feel more relaxed about it. I feel annoyed that no one believes you can get false positive tests though. I was positive on two days last wee, negative two days earlier this week and postive yesterday. I have had false positives since January. I suppose I should not feel annoyed but feel glad that Corona seems to be much milder and most people get off lightly with a cold. The temperature, coughing and other symptoms don't seem to appear. However, our offices are constantly getting people that have tested positive.
text_short_wave3: It's is an annoying pain but I'm glad Covid is now appearing to be milder in the population.

text_long_wave1:
I am not worried at all and I believe that even if I do catch it I will recover swiftly. I am also not that worried about my family catching it because they take a lot of precautions regularly and are following government guidelines. I also don't believe that anybody in my family is at risk of dying from coronavirus.

I am feeling pretty relaxed right now and nothing is affecting me. I am in good spirits and good health. I am not feeling down, and I am perfectly fine in financial terms as well. This also applies to my family who are paying bills as usual.
text_short_wave1: Feeling relaxed and happy but I understand that others are not in this situation. Stay safe everybody!
text_long_wave2: I feel like we are on the way out of the pandemic because of the vaccine rollout. This makes me feel a lot less anxious than before. I don't feel as in danger as I did a few months ago when the cases were high. I am hopeful for the future but will continue to follow the rules until told otherwise. I hope to get a vaccine soon so we can all get on with the rest of our lives. I feel good right now because there is light at the end of the tunnel. Once this is all over, we will probably have a gathering, maybe go for somewhere to eat as a family with lots of our relatives. I am quite happy at the moment and enjoying staying at home.
text_short_wave2: Can't wait for to get my vaccine and for this long pandemic to be over!
text_long_wave3: I feel a bit relieved because it seems like we are out of the worst parts of the pandemic and on a recovery. Though I worry that the government isn't taking the situation seriously enough right now and they need to do more. They need to reimpose some restrictions and not remove mask wearing as immunocompromised people would be more at risk if they did this. Masks on public transport should remain mandatory. I also think that the vaccination campaign has stalled because not enough is being done to encourage vaccination through media channels anymore. Overall though, I feel like I am in a good place right now and everyone else is similar in regards to the pandemic.
text_short_wave3: Happy, but worried about the govt releasing restrictions.

text_long_wave1: Finishing work at my dining table. Lovely to hear my kids playing on the trampoline outside and to chat with husband. Enjoying saving cash in things like gym membership so we can build up our emergency fund. Checking the news occasionally but not all the time so no one is getting anxious about the current situation. Enjoying the sunny weather today and having extra time to enjoy it at home now I’m not commuting. Planning to pot up my tomato plants at 5pm when I finish work at my laptop. My garden has never been so weed-free so I’m happy about that
text_short_wave1: No commute; sunny day; my kids laughing; being with my husband; in work and healthy. Feeling very blessed
text_long_wave2: I’m happy to be spending more time at home with my family. I don’t feel under time pressure as I’m not wasting two hours a day commuting as I’m working from home. I’m relaxed as there’ more time to do things I enjoy like gardening. I can exercise every day after work and then make dinner without rushing. I love hanging out with my kids and my husband and my dog. There’s time to chat and have fun together. We get chance to do things together like going on walks and chatting. I choose who to hang out with outside of my family and go for a walk to chat with a friend once a week rather than once a month like it used to be. I can see colleagues in meetings and get the job done together. It allows me to be more focused on my work and get stuff done.
text_short_wave2: Enjoying being at home with my family and asking the most of the extra time working from home gives me. I want to carry on like this even after I’m vaccinated and things start to return to normal
text_long_wave3: Feels like the day to day problems with it are coming to an end which is a relief. Feels like it will be with us a long time but we can now live with it. Feel less concerned about wearing a mask indoors, though still wearing it in some situations eg the train to work. Enjoying still working from home four days a week. Feels like my home/work life is more in balance. The vaccines have really made such a difference to how we can live our lives. Very grateful for them - not something that everyone has been able to take advantage of. Feel grateful to all those who looked after people when the pandemic was in full swing
text_short_wave3: Coming out of the storm into calmer seas thanks to the covid vaccines
life_event_descr_wave3: Being at home more instead of at the office has let me be there more for my family

text_long_wave1: I am in week 3 of 12 due to health issues. I suffer anxiety and depression. Today has been a bad day as stress and poor sleep patterns are taking its toll. I do not fear the virus even though I am high risk but the tension and need to do something is getting too much. I  have no doubt the world will survive and there will be changes, I think we will live more like we did when I was a child in the 70's and 80's, much simpler with more emphasis on balancing home and work. The ridiculous so called celebrity culture of 4th rate nobody's has been seen for what it is.
text_short_wave1: It's taking a long time but will be worth it. I feel as though the means is worse than the end right now but will look back on this time as a necessary part of our national restructure.
text_long_wave2: Having had my vaccine I am starting to feel more secure. I am high risk but the figures recently released are looking positive.  I spoke to my elderly parents face to face this week for the first time in several months. They have also had the vaccine so I was less fearful of both catching and spreading COVID to them. Depression is getting much worse and I really need to get out. I am struggling to sleep and am having nightmares. A few signs of hope are there, though it may be down to better weather.
text_short_wave2: Light at the end of the tunnel.

text_long_wave3:
The situation appears to be over in terms of a separate entity. It is now like any other disease. I am not thinking about it any more than I would flu. I am high risk and will take my jabs as and when same as any others. I look forward to a tablet being released for when we catch it. 
 We are all suffering financially as a result of the lockdown. I am annoyed at the spiralling costs directly due to the economy being shut down.  The government ran around like headless chickens closing the country down. The knock on effects were obvious. Empty shelves, no lorry drivers, and skyrocketing prices for everything.
text_short_wave3: It's all over. Nothing to see here. The country is on it's knees but at least some very ill people managed to survive an extra month.
life_event_descr_wave3: My dad died of cancer. There is no way I am wasting any more of my life hiding away.

I have enjoyed the time off though and people should take the postives from it rather than only looking at the negatives

text_long_wave1: At present I feel slightly anxious and uncertain as to what the future will hold. I am also in some ways hopeful that the crisis we are in will have some positive influence on the future direction of our society. It may lead to a greener way of living, having highlighted the damage caused by unrestrained economic growth. Certainly many of us have time to reflect on our situation now; which can be good for society as a whole. It should also help everyone appreciate how much we depend on one another, and maybe act as a spur to greater equality.
text_short_wave1: Coronavirus? We can overcome. We can be strong. Stronger together, stronger working together, stronger in unison.

text_long_wave2: I am relieved that at last, with the rollout of effective vaccines well on course to almost eliminate the incidence of coronavirus infections within a few months, we shall be able to return to something resembling normal life. I look forward to being able to meet family and friends, go out to the pub, have meal out, go on holiday again. I am optimistic that the vaccines can be modified if required to deal with any variants of concern. I hope that the pandemic will give more impetus to global efforts to combat climate change and improve the environment and measures of economic success.
text_short_wave2: Coronavirus: Let’s start the recovery cleanly, greenly. Time for hope.

text_long_wave3: Although I know the coronavirus pandemic is still with us, it no longer feels threatening or dangerous in the same way as it did in the past. It seems to have been downgraded to a similar status as flu. I still take precautions like hand washing as a matter of course. I think the attitude it has instilled will remain. Before long I shall hardly think about it, except when it becomes newsworthy again for whatever reason, or I am summoned for another booster jab. It has been superseded by other situations now and is no longer a subject of concern except for those who have been severely affected by it in some way.
text_short_wave3:
Coronavirus has passed by us we are the lucky ones. We should spare a thought for those who have not been so lucky, now it is no longer in the news, and remember to take care to continue safeguarding the vulnerable. 
Remember it could remain a danger for years, so keep safe.

text_long_wave1: I feel a little anger at the government who I feel are not always using logic and common sense in their approach to dealing with the covid 19 situation. My main worry is for how the long term impact of the situation will effect my ability to live my """"""""old life"""""""", and effectively plan for the future. I feel fear that the economic impact will leave so many people unemployed and helpless. I feel some relief that my elderly mum with Alzheimer's died just before the coruna virus started because it would have been incredibly hard to maintain her care with all the restrictions in place. I'm worried still about protecting my dad who had cancer. My strongest emotion is sadness, at how many people will suffer long term consequences in terms of health, mental well-being, and financial capacity.

text_long_wave2: I feel worried that the end of the situation is not really in sight. I fear we will go through all this again and again when new variants of the virus rear their head again and governments can't afford to offer free universal vaccines. I am anxious that the wider  affects of the Covid situation such as economic collapse will be more devastating than the virus itself. So overall I feel a certain sense of despair and hopelessness. I feel depressed at how little the needs of the poorest and most vulnerable in society have been considered when the authorities have planned their Covid situation response. This makes me also feel angry and frustrated. I feel sad when I think of people I love who I have not been able to travel to see as I know because of their ages, I must have lost my last chance to see them in person.

I feel annoyed that Covid is being treated by the government now as an inconvenience - numbers may be high but you have to pay for your own test, can be made to go into work etc - whereas when numbers were this high before we were told to worry more. I feel confused about how serious covid is. I also feel the authorities no longer care about caring for everyone in this time.
