text_long_wave1:
I am very worried about the virus and that myself or a loved one might catch it. I am practicing isolation as much as possible and am not leaving the house in fear that I might catch it or pass it on. I am only leaving for the shortest period of time possible to get anything I absolutely need.
However I am glad that the planet is getting a break from pollution with less cars and planes, that communities have pulled together to look after each other and show support and that people are thinking of ways to be less wasteful and greedy.
People are thinking of new ways to use food so it doesn't get wasted and more people are thinking about the things they really need rather than things they want.
text_short_wave1: I am scared out of my mind and trying not to think of the worst possible outcomes but also trying to look at the positives- less waste, less pollution and people coming together. You have to try to look on the bright side!
text_long_wave2:
Pretty relaxed as seeing a few select people is a small risk, no more dangerous than going to the supermarket.
I don’t think there’s a high risk I’ll catch it or pass it on.
I am worried about catching it and how it would affect me but think the risk is small and after not seeing anyone for a year took its toll and has lasted too long.
I am excited about being able to socialise properly and enjoy the company of our usual group of friends who used to meet every week for drinks or dinner.
I am hoping the vaccine is a success and means the risk to people is much less so life can go back to some sort of normal and the NHS can cope.
text_short_wave2: Bloody fed up with lock down and making my own rules.
text_long_wave3:
I feel as though it’s blown out of proportion now and we need to start getting on with it and let people take their own precautions as they see fit.
I gave birth recently & my partner wasn’t allowed to the recovery ward for support and I really needed him. Common sense needs to play a factor now rather than strict rules with no flexibility.
I am hopeful this will all be over soon so we can get back to normal which Is what everybody needs now. This nonsense needs to stop so that people can get back to their lives without everything being put on standstill
text_short_wave3: Enough already. Everyone is sick of Covid. Please can we just go back to some sort of normality
life_event_descr_wave3: Baby
life_event_descr: I haave used the guise and cover of Covid to completely revamp & reform my life.

text_long_wave1:
Very frightened. Scared of the unknown and how it could be caught by myself or my friends/family. Not knowing if the cough that I have is related to the pandemic or if it’s just a normal cough. Currently still in work albeit working from home. How long with this last for? Will my pay be effected soon? Will I loose my job? It seems a very small issue compared to all of the above but my health as in my weight and mental health. 
Anger. At the people that arnt listening. That are still out and about. If they aren’t following the rules of staying in I have no faith that they are washing their hands!
text_short_wave1: Anxious. Extremely anxious about what tomorrow will being. Everyday brings more sadness and fear
text_long_wave2: I am very fearful of this pandemic, I am fearful for my family. It angers me that there are many individuals who are ignoring the lockdown rules and are then moaning about how long we are locked down for. If they had the intelligence they would comply for a short time period and then we would be out again. I worry about friends who are struggling to live as they work in the tattoo business and beauty business. I can’t see us coming out of lockdown in June as I have noticed that people are back on the roads in a morning. I can’t see it being “normal” ever again. I can see face masks sticking around.
text_short_wave2: Comply now. Live life sooner.
text_long_wave3: I think it has genuinely been forgotten about by most people! The news is quite rightly about the war in Ukraine so we are not bombarded with covid news each day either. There are an odd few people still wearing masks in shops and out and about but most arnt. I have been being very careful during the pandemic due to ill health in the family so it all feels a little strange to me at the moment. I feel uncomfortable in crowds still and I think this will continue for a while. I am travelling on a plane soon which feel uncomfortable and i am not sure at this stage if masks will be worn.
text_short_wave3: Where's covid gone?
life_event_descr_wave3: cancer diagnosis in family
life_event_descr: My Mother in Law accusing me of not letting her son have a vaccine.

text_long_wave1: Feel worried, concerned, uncertain, fear, anxious, a lot of thoughts. Fear of contracting the virus or family and close ones. Uncertain about the current situation and future, worried about job, financial income as currently not working, and work has been paused. Scared, and feeling some sadness and anger received from racial discrimination from people due to the coronavirus as it has affected everyone. Safety concerns and whether or not to go out for groceries, worried about who may or may not have it
text_short_wave1: Fear, anxiety, uncertainty, and worried. Hoping everyone stays home and stays safe
text_long_wave2: At this very moment about the corona situation I feel quite worried and concerned, slightly afraid and uncertain but different and not as much compared to a year ago. More hopeful and optimistic, compared to last year, as there was feelings of fear, unknown, worried, stressed and anxious because did not know anything about the corona situation, wasn’t informed, no knowledge. However Now feel ok, still worried but not as much as before. Still feel happy and relaxed, getting on with life, getting on by
text_short_wave2: Feeling hopeful, optimistic about the future and the end of corona situation soon. Compared to last year, when feelings of stress, anxiety, uncertainty was high
text_long_wave3: With the corona situation I feel uncertain and worried and wish it would be over as it’s been going on for a few years. I am also worried about myself, family and friends health and also future impact due to household finances. I am hoping the corona situation will end soon so life can go back to normal and everyone will be safe and healthy and happy. There’s also uncertainty as there are high risks and new variants of the covid and unsure if it is safe and what risk there are, since they situation has been going on for  ages people are getting fed up.
text_short_wave3: This corona situation has been going on for a few years and everyone is feeling fed up, uncertain and worried and everyone wants life to be back to normal

text_long_wave1:
Constant feeling of worry for my family's safety as they are all key workers. As I'm not living with them I worry if I go a day without hearing from them.

Annoyed at the people who are flouting social distancing rules, especially if it results in daily exercise no longer being allowed for the rest of us who are following the rules. 

Trying to filter out the media that is trying to scaremonger, but daily death toll makes it hard to not take the threat to public safety seriously.
text_short_wave1: Brain is frazzled, missing my family but I know it's for the greater good.
text_long_wave2: Very anxious that schools are reopening on Monday despite local rates still being higher than the rest of the country. I feel it was a mistake to give an end date of 21st June as I feel people will start ignoring the rules, as previously proven when dates are given too far in advance. I will personally feel like I can relax a little bit more when both my parents have had their vaccine, and there’s a more concrete idea of when I might be eligible for my first vaccine. I hope that this is the last lockdown we have to endure as I’ve found it very challenging from a mental point of view this time, largely due to cold weather and shorter days.
text_short_wave2: Let’s not count our chickens before they’ve hatched. Behave like you’ve got the virus to keep others safe.
text_long_wave3:
Feeling a bit more wary at the moment as cases are so rife within my workplace at the moment, and it's putting a strain on the remaining workforce. 
I also feel frustrated that self-isolation is now optional as it means people have other people's health and wellbeing in their hands if they choose to go about normal day to day life knowing that they are positive for coronavirus. I do also feel an element of us as society needing to learn to live with the virus, but the last two years has made me feel so conditioned to stay at home when poorly and to try and keep distance from other people the rest of the time, and this is a difficult mindset to forget about or move away from.
text_short_wave3: No self isolation...I wonder why the cases are the highest they've been...hashtag nocoincidence
life_event_descr_wave3: having to postpone my wedding

text_long_wave1:
I am worried for the safety of my son as, of course, I still have to leave the house and am fearful of contracting the virus while out or passing it along to him. I am a little angry (though rather more annoyed) with people who flout social distancing guidelines and continue to meet in large social groups or travel unnecessarily as they are preventing others from returning to normality.
I also worry that I go out too much, however these are only for trips to the shop for food for myself or vulnerable family members, though I know there is more I could do.
text_short_wave1: Is there a particular reason people aren't staying inside? Feels like I've been inside forever.
text_long_wave2:
I am beginning to experience fatigue with lockdown, though I still understand why it is necessary. I am also concerned that we will end up with further restrictions again if we rush through lifting restrictions. I am more sad than anything, however, as my 1 year old has missed out on many things in his life so far that I had taken for granted he would experience, such as birthday celebrations and playing with cousins etc. 
I feel like we all need to continue to be careful even after lockdown ends, though I absolutely understand the desire to """"""""get back to normal"""""""".
text_short_wave2: Lockdown fatigue is real. Gotta keep focused.
text_long_wave3:
I feel as if the majority of the threat from covid has subsided as almost everyone has taken up the vaccine and especially because my loved ones have all either had covid or have had all three doses of the vaccine.
I am still very aware that people are still frightened and i myself still try to keep my distance from others as best I can, however I no longer feel substantially anxious when others come over and leave a small distance. I am extremely relieved at this as my 2 year old is finally able to do things I've been afraid to allow and we are going out and socialising with others his age also.
text_short_wave3: Nearly there. So glad I can go out and experience the world again.
life_event_descr: covid killed my cousin so upsetting

text_long_wave1: I feel extremely worried about my family, friends and myself it has caused my anxiety to massively spike. I am sad I can't go and come as I please. Completely overwhelmed by this situation and the unknown outcome of what happens and how life will be on the other side after this is over. I am fearful that I and/or my partner will lose my job. I am particularly worried for the long-term effects of our way of life. Feel quite helpless as it seems society is ready to judge or turn on each other. It is very depressing especially when you realise we are no where near the end of this horrible pandemic.
text_short_wave1: Am extremely worried and overwhelmed about the well-being of loved ones. Worried how society will recover from this. Just seems so depressing with no way out.
text_long_wave2: From the beginning of this pandemic i have been anxious about it, i am worried for my and my families' health as well as the fear of job losses.    At this point I feel very tired and sad of the situation but get annoyed at how things have been handle by the Government and press.  Some people i know haven't taken the situation seriously and this attitude has worried my greatly as I feel I am trying my best but other people do not.  I can see their point when people in power can do what they like so they feel """"""""why should I bother?""""""""  When you are around these types of people it becomes depressing as it makes you feel that what you do doesn't matter and that they don't care how their behaviour affects others.
text_short_wave2: All this time of feeling anxious is overwhelming and breaking point cannot be far away.
text_long_wave3: I am still worried about coronavirus.  I am worried for family members who have had it and how it will affect people who get it (including people who have previously had it).  I am torn between trying to get back to 'normal' and relaxing restrictions too quickly without a solid solution.  I am surprised that I still feel anxious when so much time has passed, while in groups, commuting or working. My main feelings are fear and anxiety, it makes me not want to go out apart from work or grocery shopping.
text_short_wave3: I am fearful as there does not appear to be a solid solution, I believe we still need restrictions. I don't want to socialise in person and prefer staying at home.

text_long_wave1:
I am worried that a large part of society is not respecting the lockdown and that makes me afraid more people will suffer as a result.

I am afraid that my family or I may get it and what if we have underlying conditiond we are not aware of. 

Also, its impossible to get medical care for anything else at the moment... I have had issues that have not resolved for three weeks and still have another week to wait on a blood test they told me I will be turned away from if I have a temperature... I have a suspected infection... So my temp is higher... I am afraid I will get ignored.
text_short_wave1: Your mental health will be better if less people die, stay home to save lives.
text_long_wave2:
Mixed. I don't think there is a right way to handle the current situation.  Yes, distance and wear masks at every opportunity ams avoid gatherings.  But at the same time the government can't pay its way out and support everything without this having a huge knock effect for years to come.

And its terrible that we have to accept there will habe to be a certain amount of expected deaths annually... But there does, we need to keep going, kids in school, people at work.

So, its both worrisome and challenging.  I hate risk but risk seems inevitable.
text_short_wave2: Social distance all you can, and rebuild a safer future.
text_long_wave3:
I think it is utterly ridiculous for the government to end off covid restrictions amd measures, especially masks and lft tests.  This completely incapacitates society's ability to manage covid.  I work in a special needs school where many children are medically vulnerable and yet there is no mention of free lft so we can try and minimize tge spread.

I am literally at the end of my first time catching covid and my symptoms were not typical.  I would never have thought I had covid without the lft tests nor that I am still positive on day 9!
text_short_wave3: #freeLFT save lives.  Learnimg ti live with it requires us to be equipped.
life_event_descr_wave3: I have retrained and found my way into working with special needs kids.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: I lost my job as a sushi chef
life_event_descr: My mum passed away on her own while partygate apparently happened , It is very upsetting.
life_event_descr_2: My son getting so stressed at univeristy

text_long_wave1:
I have had two job offers taken away from me due to this situation, untold frustrated at this as I worked really hard across several interviews. The level of mismanagement of the situation by the government is appalling - no plan, no idea and no planning. Shambles.
People are being used as cannon fodder, NHS staff, gig economy staff are all being sacrificed in the fights to save lives. 
Lies upon lies, denial and more lies by the government leadership team, they don't know their numbers nor do they have an ability to tell the truth. 
Our family is separated due to age and health, no government support to care for them, community, family have done more for them than the government has. 
The lack of planning has led to this ongoing outcome.
text_short_wave1: Covid19 will break this government apart and it will be for the benefit of the country going forward.
text_long_wave2:
Disgust at how the UK government has handled the corona situation the majority of the public has suffered as a result and it is completely frustrating that no actions has been undertaken over the outright lies.
There seems to be a cabal of people close to the government or within government that are shamelessly profiteering from the situation, ultimately at the cost of human lives. 
There is hope in the vaccines but even then the UK Gov. are playing games with the supply to the home nations.
2022 before things get back to normal i think and even then the loss of life should not be forgotten.
text_short_wave2: The government should have supported the NHS by fair pay, fair investment and trust the NHS to deliver services in a crisis and not outsourced to people with no expertise and they were tory donors, married to Tories or linked to cabinet, or went to school with them.
text_long_wave3:
Covid is on the rise, again, causing an impact on the nhs to recover and deal with back log and waiting lists as there are no beds. 
Not testing people and reduction in wearing masks has contributed to this so it's been slower to burn out.
Goverment and people seem to not understand this at all, profit before people and stealing peoples money seem to be more important for the government and its friends.
Following the data, science has been largely abandodned so there is not data to explain infection and in many cases reinfection of of vaccinated and unvaccinated people.
text_short_wave3: Help the NHS, continue to test and isolate.
life_event_descr_wave3: Started to work for the NHS

text_long_wave1: Slightly worried as I'm in a high risk category but am doing everything I can to keep safe and occupied mentally and physically while I remain inside most of the time. I feel lucky to have a garden to relax and exercise in. Concerned about older relatives around the world and how other places such as the US are tackling the situation. As I'm self-employed there's a constant sense of anxiety that I haven't been able to work for several weeks and government help won't be coming as quickly as would be useful.
text_short_wave1: Finding the best way of dealing with Corona anxiety is to bury myself in a good book for a few hours
text_long_wave2: Grateful that a vaccine is being rolled out well and that my dad has had his first dose. Concerned for the long term impact of the virus on several friends who've had it. Slightly anxious about how the world will look next year. Pleased that there is light at the end of the tunnel and looking forward to being able to walk somewhere other than the same old streets soon. Worried that people won't be sensible and relax things far too soon impacting on the good work that's been done to get us this far.
text_short_wave2: Pleased that the vaccine rollout is going so well, can't wait to get mine and finally see something other than the same old, pretty boring, streets on my daily walk. First thing I'll do is take a bus to a nice country park! Thank god for the NHS.
text_long_wave3: Confident that things are getting back to normal. Able to travel a bit more though still taking my own personal precautions re COVID. Feel relaxed about interacting with people more now than before. Concerned at the rate of COVID cases but confident that the vaccination programme has done its job and COVID is less of a threat now than it had been. Pleased that more places are opening up. Slightly annoyed that more people aren't taking mask wearing seriously but using my own judgement as to when and where to wear masks.
text_short_wave3: Finally feeling able to travel and interact with people as the country opens up - looking forward to more museum and theatre visits in the next year.
life_event_descr: We moved house and we got married

text_long_wave1: I feel extremely sad being away from friends and family. Sad for others who are suffering and sad for all the people who have lost their lives or loved ones. I am nervous about what the future holds for everyone and worried about whether we will return to normal. Scared whether this will ever stop and how we will cope. Worried for all concerned. It is a stressful time for all but I also feel annoyed at those who are not sticking to the rules. I’m staying indoors and everyone else should too.  I have been quite emotional about the whole situation in recent days and I fear that it is going to get worse over the coming weeks
text_short_wave1: Sad for all in these worrying times.
text_long_wave2: I am feeling quite fed up of covid. It seems as though it is never ending. I’m a teacher and have worked throughout. Fed up with hearing that schools are closed when they are clearly not!  I am expected to work within close proximity of 30 children but I can’t see my own family. Annoyed that people are still furloughed knowing that the government are stalling the inevitable.  Then the people who have worked throughout will be penalised. We need to get back to normality. I am so sorry that people have lost their lives but would question how many would have died anyway.
text_short_wave2: Fed up with covid now. Desperate to get some normality into my life so I can start planning ahead. Can’t wait to say bye to covid and lockdown and hello to a tropical beach, cocktails and some sun.
text_long_wave3: I am worried that Coronavirus seems to have been forgotten even though many people are still catching it.  I also think that it is not over and there will be other mutations. We do have to live with it like the flu and I feel that many of the recorded deaths were not due specifically to Covid but it was an added factor.  I think that like the flu it will be ongoing and different variations will keep occurring.  Many questions to be answered regarding the vaccination and whether it will have long term affects
text_short_wave3: Coronavirus is silent at the moment but it is a deadly silence and will raise its voice at a later date

text_long_wave1: I feel anxious and worried that my family might get the virus and I won't be able to help them. I'm concerned we aren't testing enough people and that the NHS doesn't have the resources to cope with the surge. I worry that the general public are not taking the social distancing seriously especially with Easter coming up.  There are still too many people out and about whi aren't following the rules. I'm also worried my employer will have to make redundancies once this is over. when will it end? How can we get back to normal life without a vaccine?
text_short_wave1: Worried people aren't taking social distancing seriously - stay home Northern Ireland and protect your loved ones and the NHS
text_long_wave2: I’m feeling bored and tired of the pandemic and restrictions. I still feel a little anxious but less so now that the vaccines are being delivered. I’m a lot less worried about clinically vulnerable family and elderly family catching the virus now they are vaccinated.  I’m back on furlough which is fine but overall I am a bit frustrated. I would also like the schools to go back as I’m concerned about the mental health of my kids- this is the number one worry for me. They need to be with their friends and away from the screens much more. I just want my life back!
text_short_wave2: About time the schools in NI went back, I’m worried about the long term damage to our kids mental health. Get the vaccine people!
text_long_wave3:
I am quite relaxed now as most people have had it without being seriously ill. I’m vaccinated and still haven’t caught the virus even though everyone else I know has. I do worry about my brother though as he is CEV. I am still wearing a mask at shops but I’m more comfortable socialising with other people and working in the office again as well as at home. The only thing that still worries me is the potential emergence of a new variant which is more deadly and as transmissible as Omicron.
The government response has been appalling and this makes me angry. So many people have died and their attitude stinks with their breaking of lockdown rules by partying and drinking while people were dying alone away from their families.
text_short_wave3: Hope everyone keeps wearing their masks to keep the CEV groups safe and give them confidence to restart their lives.

text_long_wave1: My feelings are essentially of anxiety and fear for my family - both young and old. I am also extremely proud of how the country has pulled together though, including the NHS and other key workers. I am not sure how I will feel as the situation continues and the lockdown lengthens. While it was a novelty at first - this has long since passed and my stress levels are increasing. However, I try to be optimistic - I am in a good position compared to others and we must all try and continue as best we can.
text_short_wave1: The Corona virus has caused huge stress, sadness and despair - and as yet it sows no sign of getting better. That said, the reaction to the people in the country, particularly the NHS and key workers in all industries has been truly inspirational and we must continue to be positi
text_long_wave2: I am starting to feel more confident that we will be coming out of these terrible times in the near future. While I am not sure that everything will be back to normal for some time, I am confident that the vaccine will allow a greater degree of normality. My anxiety is starting to reduce and is being replaced by feelings of excitement and happiness. There are so many things that we have all missed over the last year that it is almost overwhelming when you think about what is to come. I am sure that we can cross the finish line and bring some of the benefits that we have seen over the last year with us. Working at home has been a real benefit for me, and I know many others as well. While it will not be positive for everyone, at least having the choice will be a positive thing.
text_short_wave2: After a really stressful and taxing year, I am starting to become more confident that we are on the road to freedom again. If we all stand together for the last stretch, I am sure we can get there and win the battle. Exciting times lie ahead for us all, I am increasingly confiden
text_long_wave3: I am feeling a lot more relaxed about it. I am still uneasy mixing in large crowds and I am suprised that all measures have been removed, including masks. However, I continue to wear a mask in public places and due to the increased cost of living have less opportunity to go out anyway. It is all starting to be forgotten, superseded by the current crisis in Ukraine. I wonder if we may come to regreat that as time goes by and as yet unidentified varients begin to appear. That said, I think that the vaccination programme is now working well and I understand that it is possible to tweak the vaccines fairly quickly in response to potential new varients.
text_short_wave3: I am feeling much better about the corona virus situation since the vaccination programme was rolled out fully across the counrtry. I do wish that some of the protective measures had been retained, particularly the wearing of masks in public spaces and the call to work at home.
life_event_descr_wave3: Sadly the passing of my mother. While she did not die of the virus, I was unable to see her in hospital.
life_event_descr: cancer diagnosis in family

text_long_wave1: Frustration at the situation and how there's no end in sight to anything. It seems without a vaccine there's no way for this to end because our government is not competent enough unlike Germany or South Korea. Anger and resentment at the government for having made the political decision to do all this when other countries handled it better and they had months to prepare and only decided to do something just recently. And anxiety and caution about trying to do basic things like shopping. Everyday I have a mild panic attack about some mild pain or twinge I feel, suddenly worried I'm developing it.
text_short_wave1: Completely frustrated, wishing we had competent leadership who were handling this weeks ago and competent leadership to lead us out of this now.
text_long_wave2: The situation seems to be improving because of vaccinations, but there's a lot of cause for concern about smaller countries having access to vaccines. Vaccinating the planet will be crucial in stemming further Corona mutations, which are already happening in Brazil. I'm upset, frustrated and angered that over 130,000 British people have died and nobody in government has resigned or said sorry and the Tories are remaining high in the polls. It's mind boggling that so many selfish greedy choices have been made at the cost of human lives and nothing has been learned or done but a lot of Tory donors have been enriched.
text_short_wave2: Enthusiastic about the rate of vaccinations in many countries but concerned about the slow rates in many third world countries. Completely angry and fed up that so many British lives were lost and no Tory will take responsibility for it but just enriched their donors.
text_long_wave3: With the rise of BA.2 and the lack of any mitigating protections at all I feel very nervous about the current situation. I had to go to a doctor's appointment last week and almost nobody there had a mask on, at the doctor's where potentially very sick immunosuppressed people could be. It's incredibly disheartening to see the government and people of this country refuse to take anyone else's wellbeing into concern. Long Covid greatly concerns me and yet there seems to be almost nothing available to prevent it or help with it.
text_short_wave3: Feeling incredibly dismayed about the current Corona situation. Nobody wearing masks, almost no public mitigations, the rise of BA.2 and almost no discussion about the long term health impacts of Long Covid. No faith in the government at all.
life_event_descr_wave3: I developed a few underlying health concerns regarding my thyroid and my economic situation has worsened.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: The economic situation.

text_long_wave1:
I am fairly safe in a secluded location, however I am very worried about the safety of my family and friends that live in big cities.
I worry for my pensioner parents as my dad has COPD yet they both still smoke and are doing daily trips to the shops for more cigarettes.
I am angry there has been so little investment in critical services and this is causing illness, stress and deaths that may have been avoidable.
I hope lessons have been learned and people that work in essential services are treated with far more respect.
text_short_wave1: '@stayathome!
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2:
With the current vaccination rate I feel we are seeing the light as the end of the tunnel.
I am anxious to see family and friends again.
I do have concerns about the effectiveness or possible long term effects of the vaccination, but it is a gamble I am happy to take if it means we can safely visit loved ones.

The paranoia and fear seen on social media news comments has been enlightening, quite worrying seeing how a minority think!

I was asked to write a few sentences, not an essay, this box is refusing me to continue until I have written enough text, I hope this does it...
text_short_wave2: We can see the light at the end of the tunnel! Get your vaccine, stay safe!
employment status_wave2: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave3:
Currently I feel fairly safe, I live in a remote area and I don't socialise much at all, however I am concerned for family and friends in cities.
I have been vaccinated but I am aware of new variants and concerned how these will affect us all.
You really want me to sit and write an essay for 80p?
What more can I say.
I clearly need to think of other things to say before I can complete this survey. 
I have already expressed how I feel above, please define """"""""a few sentences"""""""" you clearly want much more!
text_short_wave3: See previous statement
life_event_descr_wave3: My father was ill, I live in Scotland and he lives in England. I have to be careful as I am immunocompromised, but seeing my father was more important than the risk to myself, so I travelled
employment status_wave3: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)

text_long_wave1: Disgusted how unprotected NHS staff are and how late the government has been in trying to resolve this. Disgusted at the amount of people not adhering to guidelines for the safety of others. Sad about the amount of people dying without their families, dying alone without even care staff having the time to sit and hold their hand whilst they take their last breath. Disgusted at the attitude of current staff when someone needs to take the week off, but also feeling the pressure of having to stay at work even though they are experiencing symptoms themselves.
text_short_wave1: Stay at home.
text_long_wave2: I think it's a situation that could have been resolved a lot better if lives were deemed more important than the finances of the country. However, I don't feel fear for the virus and have already had it. I just think more could have been done to keep us safe in public areas, e.g. sufficient cleaning of tables during the 50% off eat in to help out. or proper guidance on how to properly dispose and wear masks, the same way we get taught in clinical environments. text_short_wave2: Stay home and save lives

I'm frustrated that the situation wasn't addressed more decisively earlier, but have to accept it is what it is.  The situation is also nice in some ways because I'm able to homeschool my daughter, and spend more time with her, but I would rather she were in school.  
I'm anxious for the health of my parents, who are elderly, as they have to be isolated and we do all of their shopping for them.  
My partner is very frustrated that she can't get out and about but is accutely aware that it's stupid to be out there and socialising or breaking the rules.  We are all adhering strictly to the government guidelines and are looking to do what's necessary.  
Personally, I miss the team and sporting activities that I would like to have been doing.  Also, I'm finding work is less productive than before and I'm one of those who falls between two stalls; I get nothing from the government but I appreciate the way that they have responded with financial packages that are relatively generous.

I still feel there are concerns for the people who are not vaccinated (myself included) and for the elderly, especially in the light of the Manaus strain being in the UK.  I'm happy in a way that the R number has dropped and the figures locally for cases is very low, but I do feel things should have been done differently in the early stages to slow death figures.
text_short_wave2: People should be doing what's right rather than what suits them.  The Covid situation is still serious and people are still dying, so do what's right and try to avoid contact with others unless unavoidable.
text_long_wave3: I feel that the current situation is reminiscent of the pre-pandemic days.  Instead of flu, we now have covid.  While the situation is obviously still very serious for some of those with underlying health conditions, the reality is that fully-vaccinated people are unlikely to suffer much with the disease.  The alternative to freedom is to lock down and restrict the populace; I now see that as a thoroughly unwelcome and unnecessary move.  We are reaching the point of herd immunity, despite the objections of a few idiots, and there seems little benefit in imposing any restrictions.  Almost everyone has had the disease, and to restrict the economy at this point is counter-productive.

text_long_wave1:
While it is weird the my life is 'on hold' I was too busy before, and am grateful for some time out. I am enjoying being with my immediate family, being able to relax, read, sit in the garden. I am learning new skills/hobbies (crochet, sourdough). I recognise that I am privileged because I do not need to worry about our financial situation, we have enough food, and no-one in my immediate family is ill.
In general I am not anxious about the virus. I understand that statistically speaking, I will get the virus, but will survive. I also understand that I am not a statistic!
As a Christian I feel as safe now as I ever did, knowing that God is in control, both of the global situation and indeed of my own personal one.

text_long_wave2:
I am frustrated that lockdown continues even though cases have dropped so low. I feel we are risking the lives of younger people who are missing cancer screenings etc, and I know of several people who have committed suicide because of the current situation. 
Somehow government is no longer taking off a trade off between lives, it’s all about saving the elderly and vulnerable. But they have had their vaccines by now!
We should reopen the country and get the economy working again as soon as we can. It’s not a case of money vs. lives, the economy is lives. 
Also our children have missed out on so on much of their youth and their education.
text_short_wave2: Enough is enough: let’s end the lockdown now and get our kids back in school, our youth back at uni and ourselves back to work. Life has to go on!
text_long_wave3:
Where I live, Covid numbers have risen hugely in the past few weeks and all the other members of my household have been ill with it in the past month. 
However, it has not been worse than a bad cold and they have all recovered. 
I still feel angry for my teenage children who have missed so much of their schooling and are struggling to catch up- one taking A levels in the summer and another doing GCSEs without having received all the necessary input. 
I’m much sadder though for the ordinary things they’ve missed out on. My 16 year old had her birthday last week, and because she was ill with Covid she wasn’t at school. That’s the third birthday in a row she hasn’t been able to properly celebrate. We are planning a party in a few weeks but it’s not the same as actually on the day. 
They’ve also missed out on sleepovers, trips with school, time with friends etc which can never be replaced. 
As a primary school year 2 teacher I notice how fragile the younger children are emotionally. I had children crying on the last day of term before the Christmas holidays, anxious that they might not be coming back. Many of them need the reassurance of a cuddly toy at school, which I wouldn’t have allowed in previous years. 
 They are constantly needy of adult intervention, unable to sort out the ordinary playground squabbles. I’m assuming this is because of the lack of interaction with other children during the lockdowns. I’m also noticing language delays and academically they’re certainly ‘behind’ as a cohort.
I fear that a whole generation may turn out ‘weird’ because I’m not sure that some of what they have missed can be provided at a later stage.
text_short_wave3: Covid: the thief of a generation’s well-being and childhood. Or maybe that was just lockdowns. We should never have locked down. Just protected the vulnerable and left everyone else to live their lives.
life_event_descr_wave3: I trained as a teacher and started working full time following a 20 year career break raising a family.
life_event_descr: Due to not being able to go out my health has gotten worse.

text_long_wave1:
I am very anxious at the moment. I have generalised anxiety disorder, and usually my mood is well controlled and stable. This current situation however has undone a lot of the work I've managed to do in the past few years to take control of my mental health.
As a microbiologist, I have volunteered to work in one of the government testing centres and I feel like this will help me manage my anxiety however, as it will help me feel like I have a part to play in managing the situation. Other than that, I am sadder than usual, and I feel like I have lost faith in some people who are not taking the advice and warnings of the WHO and government seriously.
text_short_wave1: I am pretty sad now. My anxiety is through the roof and I want things to go back to normal. Everything I've done to fix my mental health has been undone and I'm feeling pretty broken right now.
text_long_wave2:
I still feel very sad about all the people that have unnecessarily died, and worried that my parents are still somewhat in danger as they’ve not received their dose of the vaccine yet. I am less anxious than I was a few months ago but I am sad to how this year has negatively affected my mental health and potentially my future - I feel my career has been negatively impacted and I will be undergoing treatment for my depression for years to come. 
I am afraid that people are becoming complacent with the rules and I am worried things will get worse once schools go back this week. I am more hopeful than I was about things in the past but it’s still overshadowed by fear and worry.
text_short_wave2: Still majorly worried. I’ve been sad for so long and I just want things to get better. The UK government needs to do better.
text_long_wave3:
I am sad at the disregard of people to the health of others. I have lost faith in people, and feel disappointed with people. I feel let down and am worried for the future.
I am angry at the government decisions to get rid of testing and mandatory isolation. I am sad that so many people seem to not care about anyone other than themselves. It's disheartening to know that so many people are suffering from a lack of hospital and social care resources, and that so many other people will suffer due to the effects of how we handled covid on the NHS, social care, and living costs. I am so sad that our country prioritised the economy over people's lives, and that many people in the country seem to think that was the right decision. I feel like I don't belong here and that I don't identify with the majority of British people.
text_short_wave3: The government let us down. Selfish people let us down. We should be caring about others, not just ourselves.

At this moment in time I feel annoyed because many people are ignoring the Quarantine rules despite knowing the consequences. They are going to their friend's houses, going to public parks and socialising and not taking anybody else into consideration. By doing this they are putting the rest of us at risk. I feel like the current lock down will be extended because of people's inability to follow simple rules.
I also feel worried because many people are dying from the disease. Quite a few people's parents are dying and I find this worrying and upsetting. The fact that people have to dies a lonely death is quite disturbing.

Lastly, I feel rather isolated. I am staying with people, but it would be nice to see my friends. Facetime and Houseparty will have to do for the mean time.

I now have other hobbies that don't require social contact with a large number of people, so I am not as bored as I initially was. On the other hand, COVID is still very much real and it is sad that so many lives have been lost. I do hope that this pandemic will soon end (some way, some how), so that I can walk through the streets without a mask through large crowds, without worrying that I will get COVID. I miss the carefree Pre-covid life.

text_short_wave1: Over a couple of weeks life as we knew it changed. Lockdown is 100% the correct thing we should be doing a nation - in it together, but at the same time you shouldn’t feel discouraged to express how you truly feel. I for one won’t be taking for granted mundane things in my life!
text_long_wave2: I feel sad that it feels it has gone on for so long when compared to other countries successfully managing the pandemic more successfully than us. I feel sad for the people that have lost their lives and those that are going to be heavily impacted by a future economic downturn as a result of the pandemic and those who have already lost their jobs. Loneliness is also something I’ve been feeling more and more, I feel that maintaining friendships is harder and not being able to see family is frustrating. I do feel lucky though that I’ve been able to stay employed and haven’t been impacted by the virus and neither have my family.
text_short_wave2: Getting tired and saddened by the ongoing crisis, why has our government failed us this poorly. We deserved better than this continuing crisis.

Covid has been awful but I feel as a society we need practices in place that will allow us to move forward so it causes as little disruption in our lives going forward. I’m all for vaccines and measures in place but I don’t want a continued life of self isolating/lockdowns in place - we need to adapt better past these measures.

text_long_wave1: I'm not worried about the effects of Corona on my personal well-being, but I'm concerned about the long-term economic consequences of mass quarantine. I find it frustrating how scared and anxious most people seem to be because of Corona, even though it poses little to no threat to the majority of them. I think the current measures meant to stop the spread of the virus will do more harm than good in the long run, because life can't just stop for several months. I do, however, appreciate the new opportunities to spend more time by myself at home, including working from home (which I've never done before).
text_short_wave1: The world is overreacting to the Coronavirus. It's going to get worse, but not in the way people expect.
eng_native_wave1: No but I speak it fluently
text_long_wave2: I am frustrated and angry about the fact that my life has been put on hold for almost a year due to the lockdown, but a little hopeful that with the vaccine the situation will finally go back to normal. I'm also worried about the long-term financial impact of the government support measures taken in the last few months. The prime minister just went into ICU, so my anxiety and fear it high at the moment. My chest feels tight. This is huge.

I am anxious that the curve is not flattening quickly. Will this end? How many people will be lost.

I am worried people out there working, such as my ICU nurse sister in law and feel guilty surrounding any deliveries we have.
I worry about my job and my own company and I wonder about the ethics of luxuries and I worry about people who may be suicidal. So many emotions. It’s many ups and downs but right now my fear is very high and my thoughts are racing. This is a scary moment

at this moment i am angry at the damage these lockdowns have had to my kids - their wellbeing, their education, their future. We are being subjected to lockdowns to protect the vulnerable - who are now vaccinated and yet we are being told - at least in Scotland that we are not behaving enough to be allowed to eat out or go to a shop until at least May - thats another 2 full months - which means our lives will have been on hold for 14 months by that point. I am angry at how the goalposts for exiting lockdown are being moved - our tier levels in scotland are being altered so that to move down a tier the infection rate per 100,000 has to be much lower than last years tiers. My LA was sitting at an IR last week that under last years tiers would have us in tier 1 but under her revised tiers keeps us in tier 3 which is almost still lockdown. We had 1 infection in our LA last saturday - 1 !!!!! we have been mostly in single figures for the past 2 weeks.
I have felt recently that whats the point in being alive if i cant live my life and government are dictating to me who i can and cannot see , wher i can and cannot go.
We are heading for an overwhelming mental health crisis in this country and we are not equipped to deal with it. The pandemic itself no longer frightens me - our response to it is more frightening at this point

Very worried about how much the situation will worsen and how to keep my loved ones safe. 

Angry about the number of people still failing to take it seriously and endangering others.

 Anxious about how to keep my little one safe and entertained whilst isolated.

 Anxious about my own job prospects and sad about not seeing the wider family regularly.

Sad for those in less fortunate positions who cannot stay safe, have no one and have lost their jobs.

text_long_wave2:
I am somewhat worried about how things will progress and whether there will be pressure to return to the workplace before I feel safe. I am worried about the behaviour of others and not being able to keep my loved ones safe.

I am sad that I haven't seen some family members who live abroad and that we had to postpone our own wedding but ultimately grateful that my loved ones have remained safe to date and financially secure. 

I am mindful that not everybody has coped as well as I have or had as many positive aspects such as increased family time in my household which I am forever grateful for.

text_long_wave3:
Disappointed that the government is treating it like it's no longer a concern and the lack of precautions taken by others in shops etc. Particularly worried about the lack of concern about the spread in schools and among preschool children who cannot be vaccinated. Grateful I have managed to get all vaccines and continue to take precautions myself.
Understand the need to get back to some type of normality but think this leaves behind vulnerable sections of our community.

text_long_wave1:
I feel disgust towards a lot of people that refuse to isolate. It also highlights how everyone thinks they are an expert, despite the real experts  admitting they've never dealt with this before.
I have no bad feelings or effects about isolating as I normally isolate myself most of the time.
I feel lucky I live in the UK as we have the NHS. I have a friend in the US who is more worried as their health services are fragmented.
I am a little concerned about catching the disease as I have a high BMI and am pre-diabetic so I can't be sure if I'm classed as vulnerable or not.
text_short_wave1: Hard to believe people cannot isolate when many millions of people in poorer countries would give anything to have to live in a warm safe house for several months.
text_long_wave2:
I feel quite anxious when I have to go food shopping as many people are not social distancing properly.
I am also quite anxious waiting to be vaccinated as I have no idea when this will happen.
I am hopeful once the vast majority of people have been vaccinated I won't have to be worried when going out again.
I happen to be in a very vulnerable group of people as I have chronic bronchitis and I am overweight so I do worry about my life if I were to contract the virus.
I am also a little worried about my job prospects as I am unemployed at the moment and I cannot see numbers of vacancies going up any time soon,
text_short_wave2: Feeling concerned when going out as most people are not social distancing properly. Thankfully online food shopping has reduced the need for me to be around others drastically.
text_long_wave3: I feel anxious as I am classed as vulnerable and most people seem to have forgot the dangers. They have stopped wearing masks on buses, not social distancing etc. It saddens me as it shows there is no such thing as society where people care about other people. As I am unemployed at the moment, I am also forced to attend interviews in cramped conditions with many other people close to me in the building. This makes me very fearful and stressed when I am forced into that position. My only hope is anti viral medicines are getting better and I have had all the vaccine jabs that have been suggested for me.

I’m also becoming anxious which brings on funny symptoms such as pains, headaches etc which in turn makes the anxiety worse. I know this will pass. One thing I do like is how quiet it is, the birds singing, the air is clearer and nature has started to take over in places just from a few weeks of being left untouched. I know this will all come right in the end but I reckon everyone will be a lot different and also the planet. It has to be.

text_long_wave2:
I think that it has gone on long enough and that there has never been any clear guidance on how we now deal the outcome of it all. 
I think that it had been mismanaged from the start and that things could have been a lot better. 
I think it has shown the best of people but also the selfishness of the vast majority of the country. Having spent time minding my own family and doing everything I could, I see too many others doing what they want. I haven’t seen my family in months and yet others have as they don’t care.

I think mainly we are going to just have to careful still, washing hands, and not putting yourself in positions where you may come into contact with it. Saying that before all of this happened coughs and colds where always rife. Maybe by keeping distances and sanitising often does work.

I live in a small flat on the first floor of an apartment block in London and am finding it very difficult at present as I only leave the flat once a day to go for a walk or get some groceries. My family are all in Ireland and I have to rely on phone calls to check on their well being which adds to my anxiety and stress levels.

I feel better about the situation as a whole as the vaccinations are ramping up and soon normality will be slowly resumed. I am grateful that I have been able to continue to work through this time and am lucky that my life hasn't been too affected.

I don't really fear the virus as I have been vaccinated and I am in good health but I appreciate not everyone is in the same situation. However, if we don't start removing all restrictions soon, then when?
I have started socialising as normal and visiting places without a mask etc. Certain requirements to enter places such as covid passport feel arbitrary at this time.

text_long_wave1:

In general I'm not all too affected due to being an introverted homebody, but am shocked at the sheer level of contagiousness of the virus and in the longer term really hope it shows those in charge how important the NHS is. I really hope that people can pull together and don't drag this out longer than it needs to, although the pessimist in me isn't expecting that much.

Also, although I feel a little bad for it there's a certain amount of schadenfreude gained from knowing the Prime Minister is now ill with coronavirus after his being so weak-willed for so long when the dangers first started appearing.
text_short_wave1: We need to pull together, listen to the experts and do everything we can to curb this virus. Breaking social distancing is only going to add to how long it stays in place for!

I'm still concerned that we're opening up too quickly, our government seems to fold every time the business sector even mildly leans on them and it just gets us in a cycle of lockdown, then reopening, then infection rates predictably soaring, then lockdown again. We would probably be in a much better place if restrictions had stayed somewhat strict until vaccines were ready and at least partially rolled out.

Other than that I'm not especially looking forward to finding work again and feel rather down on myself for not making better use of my free time.
text_short_wave2: Everyone getting caught up in 'yay great vaccine rollout' needs to not forget how badly handled the whole covid situation has been by our government prior to this, nor let them hide behind it as a shield for their numerous other failings.

As much as I appreciate some things like normalising wearing masks when you're ill/concerned about getting ill and the obvious increase in remote working, it's nice to at least come to some form of normality.

That said there are still some things I'd be too cautious to do, for now I'm still staying away from concerts as much as I used to like going to them!

I’m in a loving relationship so don’t have the worry of being abuse in my own home, I don’t have children to worry about nor to think about homeschooling, I have time to cook a healthy meal, I have money to do so, I have times and wifi for exercise, getting in touch with family and friends online. So I’m really grateful and privileged, how about poorer parts of the country and the world where there’s no space like shanty towns and favelas? This worries me a lot. 

But also hopeful and happy that perhaps this will bring about a new normal - where the rat race isn’t going to be so overrated as it was. So I’m always thinking about the both sides of the coin which makes me anxious and helpless. My main question is - how to help others in this situation?

but on the other hand staying at home with my family and not rushing around to school drop off, commuting and working full time is is good  
i feel relaxed when i am with my family but then you open the front door and the realisation hits you of what is happening
text_short_wave1: Everyone please stay at home, for the safety of yourself, your family, your friends. and for those who are working at the NHS and frontline services
text_long_wave2:
I currently feel excited by idea of next lot of restrictions being lifted to begin to see friends and family again. I am also looking forward to opening up of services such as restaurants and other hospitality sectors to be able to have more freedom. Particularly with spring and summer on way.
I am concerned about the economy with maybe even a recession looming  and especially the affect the closure of schools has had on children 
 however I worry for the long term particularly if everyone rushes to go on holiday again then we may be back in another lockdown come autumn
text_short_wave2: Please keep listening to government guidelines and follow their instructions. Don’t rush to book anything otherwise we will be in another lockdown come autumn summer hols can wait!
text_long_wave3:
I am worried about the current situation in terms of infection rates increasing however I appreciate we have to learn to live with this virus - the attention has now rightfully in the media turned to the awful war in Ukraine but this means as it is the way with the media that covid is not beeen reported on

text_long_wave1:
I'm concerned about the effect it could have on my family and friends, apprehensive about the potential effects on the economy and sad that it has prevented me from seeing people.  It's also been very frustrating the way that many people have reacted, by either panic buying or ignoring the advice and continuing to mix with others.
However, I'm relieved that my job is (for the time being) safe, and that no-one I know has suffered any major effects.  The reduction in pollution has been a positive side effect, and it may result in some positive changes to the way we live and work (such as more remote working).
text_short_wave1: Trying to focus on the positive consequences of the virus - remote working, less pollution and a chance to catch up with projects at home!  If only we could achieve something like this without the anguish and loss of life
text_long_wave2: I'm feeling positive that the vaccine seems to be making a big difference to the number of infections, and that it doesn't look to be too long now before we can really start to relax the current restrictions.  This last year has been hard, although I do feel it has had some benefits, such as the opportunity to work from home more often even once the offices have reopened.  I've also been able to take up a home exercise routine using youtube videos, which has helped me to become fitter and start losing weight - I'm planning to keep going with this in the future.
text_short_wave2: Very glad we can see the light at the end of the tunnel, we just need to keep going a little longer and finally we'll be able to go back to """"""""normal life""""""""
text_long_wave3:
I'm glad that we do seem to be getting through to the """"""""other side"""""""" of the situation, although I do feel that restrictions were ended a little too early - the government's statistics show a significant increase in cases and hospitalisations that began at the same time the mandatory self isolation policies ended.  This puts a lot of pressure on people who can't afford to miss work but are infected, which results in an increase in further infections.
I'm still a little worried for people who are vulnerable, even with the vaccinations people can still get seriously ill or die from the virus.
text_short_wave3: Happy that we can start resuming normal life again, but despite the positive news the virus hasn't gone away yet.
life_event_descr: My father passed away. He caught covid whilst in hospital for something else. The NHS staff and carers were very unprofessional and poorly trained.
life_event_descr_2: One of my best friends passed away. This was not from Covid, but it was during the first lockdown and we could only attend her funeral online.

text_long_wave1: I am worried about losing my job. My emotions and those of my family are all over the place. We are all scared and worried about the future. The future looks quite bleak and where we go from here, I do not know. If we had a deadline or an end in sight, I think this would help a lot of people although I understand that this is a difficult thing to predict and communicate.
text_short_wave1: Fear, terror, concern, worry and disbelief. Coronavirus is no joke and unless we work together, it will not improve
text_long_wave2: Happy that things are starting to improve. I am ok eased that so many are getting their vaccination and that the rollout happened quickly. They think the vaccinations  will protect them no matter what and a lot of people seem to be flouting the rules because of this. I feel like people in general have given up their respect for the guidelines and are approaching this with a selfish attitude.

text_long_wave3:
We are still shielding as my wife is immuno suppressed, and high risk. Not sure what the future holds, or when we will be able to return to something approaching normal, having hardly left the house in the last two years, apart from for hospital appointments.

Angry at the government for removing restrictions too soon - our area currently has one of the highest rates of covid infection in the country.

Apart from a couple of trusted friends in a similar situation, our social interaction has been restricted to zoom meetings. We have two grandchildren (the youngest is 2) we have yet to meet, as they live over 300 miles away and we have huge logistical problems to overcome if we are to see them safely - my daughters and their husbands have all been infected within the last 6 months.

text_long_wave1: I feel that there is an underlying problem with the whole situation. Bill Gates had been warning of this on TED 15 years ago and we have had various contagions around the world. It seems that no country in the world was really ready for this, nor did they have any plans. It is as though it was never expected to happen. The testing in the UK for antigens is not working and a lot of taxpayers money has been spent on this. Emergency services are grossly overstretched and people are being badly informed. The only useful strategies have been hand washing, distancing from others and not going out unless necessary. Masks and gloves being worn day after day by the public may even accumulate the pathogen but no advice on this has been given.
text_short_wave1: Stay calm, keep your distance from others, keep clean and remain at home unless you need to work, shop for essentials or obtain medical help. Keep in touch with friends and family by 'phone, email, skype and other means. This will all pass. Stay safe and protect one another!

text_long_wave2:
I am sad that Covid-19 is so relentless. Perhaps it will be like the Spanish 'Flu of 1918-20 or the Russian 'Flu of 1889-90 (which could have been a coronavirus) and just drift away. However, the economy, education of our children, businesses and jobs have all suffered due to the pandemic. I am surprised that this was allowed to happen despite the warnings of the Bill Gates TED talk of 2015 and Event 21 of 2019. I was also very surprised at the transmission rate.
It seems that economic constraints have now been placed on the UK for many years to come and there is still uncertainty as to the efficacy of vaccination. I am also concerned that masks and social distancing will weaken the population's immunity to other illnesses.

It feels like a never ending situation that I would like the world to collectively come out of, as if exiting a bad dream.
text_short_wave1: Looking forward to 2021!

text_long_wave1: I am anxious, mainly because I am responsible for a multi-generational household - myself, my 15 year old son (who would have been taking his GCSEs) and my 87 year old father, who has vascular dementia and is very frail. We have carers coming in and out of the house 4 times a day to do Dad's personal care, and I live in fear of one of them inadvertantly (and they do do their best to be careful) bringing the virus in, as I realise it would likely mean a distressing and horrible death for Dad. I'm also worried about the effect of all this on my son, who now cannot improve on his schoolwork in order to get the grades he needs (he was unwell eariler in the year). I'm also worried about income, as I'm self employed and quite affected by the crisis in that regard. On the plus side, it's like someone has pressed the 'pause' button on life, it's peaceful, we are lucky enough to be in a reasonable sized house with a garden, and when I'm not worrying, I'm actually very relaxed, with the lack of rushing here and there.

Usually I have respite breaks where my dad goes into a care home for a week or so and I and my son can have a break from the situation. This has obviously not been possible due to the virus being so prevalent in care homes (my elderly cousin died of Covid in one in January) - it has been too risky to take the chance Also, if there was an outbreak while dad was in one, we would not be allowed to get him back out. So we have just had to cope. I'm so relieved, however, that we seem to be coming towards the end of this - dad has had his vaccine, and I have just been offered it. text_long_wave1:
Perversely it's created a shared spirit, albeit an anxious one. 
It's like a reset switch, but more bad than good is going to come out of it. Sudden hardship will cause large problems and there needs to be full empathy from large organisations to reduce those problems. 
There's not really a 'win ' situation here, it's a damage limitation exercise.
Large corporations (especially banks) need to be sympathetic rather than looking at opportunities to boost their public relations and marketing,
Most people I am aware of are keeping to the rules laid out by the government. i.e. keeping 2 metres apart, staying in the house, etc. But exercise is important, especially for those people in small houses with no garden, and I do not believe in demonising people who go to parks to get fresh air. If 20 odd people are hanging out together, that's something altogether different

text_long_wave1: I would not usually be at home during the day as it negatively affects my mood. My house is small and I have young children. It is difficult to keep them entertained in one room all day. I went to town for the first time on Sunday to buy cat food and found it very scary. There seemed to be more people with mental issues in the streets and much fewer other people to ask for help if there were problems. Most of the shops are shut and there’s no access to public toilets. People who are out do not respect the 2m rule and others and abuse the staff who are trying to enforce them. I am scared to go into town where usually we would spend most of the day there before. When I got home my anxiety and fear was so bad I felt I couldn’t breathe or think and I don’t usually suffer with anxiety. Now we go for exercise before 6am because we don’t trust people and if we have to shop we try to be home by 8:30am and we go to local shops and not the supermarkets. The queuing system is terrifying and full of people coughing and smoking and grouching about the stupid rules. I do not want to queue to potentially catch something that kills me or my family. Shops say one family member only and forget that we can’t leave our children outside alone, and that to buy a weeks shopping is often not possible. We have four cats, three children and no car. The cat food weighs 10kg for a week. The litter weighs 3kg. Milk for all of us is 30litres. I’m pushing a double buggy with 20kg of children in already, how do I carry everything? We can’t get home delivery, there are no slots and we’re not vulnerable. Shopping every second day is the least we can get away with at the moment. That means we have a higher chance of meeting the virus.

It feels like people think that it's finished....except that I currently have it, my wife has it, two of my children have it, and more people I know currently have it than at any time during the pandemic. I appreciate that fewer people are dying from it at present, but I think that too many people, particularly those in charge, would rather we forgot all about it.
I do not feel that our Government's reposne to the pandemic was in any way adequate. Too much money has been wasted on pointless initiatives within the economy, not enough money was provided to keep health and care home workers (and residents) safe, and we are now being encouraged to overlook the Government's constant partying and rule-breaking in order to look forwards. 
There seems to be no willingness to take responsibility for wrong decisions, poor behaviour, reckless spending of public money and there is an attitude of indifference towards those that have lost loved one during the pandemic ,both to Covid and to other causes of death.
I would applaud anyone in a position of responsibility to stand up and admit errors and to actually take responsibility but the country seems to be locked in a downward spiral of wanting power and reward but not to take the responsibility that comes with those priviledges.

Frustrated that certain members of the public are not taking the threat seriously. 
Generally the issues with getting essential food from the supermarkets is a little bit time consuming but safety matters to everyone and social distancing is there to help prevent the spread of the viral infection is a necessity.
Working from home if available does offer additional security when it comes to self isolation. 
However some companies appear to be chasing their revenue streams rather than thinking of their staffs welfare. It appears as if staff are expected to be very flexible with their work schedules to avoid companies cease trading (Taking annual leave forced shutdowns). However whenever we get back to some form of normality I expect companies won't remember what their staff did for them.

I am optimistic that with the Vaccination roll out that is currently being implemented will give us release from lock down and get back to a new normal. We will however still need to be cautious as to distancing and wear masks when in crowded spaces.
The economy will take a very long time to recover and a lot of independent retailers on the high street will take a long time to get back to their financial position pre pandemic with the outlook for some businesses quite poor and may well go out of business. Cash as a mainstay of payment now is not the normal and banking on the high street will be more difficult as banks take the decision to go online and reduce their face to face contact possibilities. Working from home an option for several types of business leading to no need to have a main/head office and use rented conference facilities when the need for large events is required leading to reduced costs.

I worry about how we can begin to resume life and about the people for which it will never be the same.

Covid still concerns me. On both public and personal levels. 

Pubically I feel we have become far too blaze about the whole situation, acting like it no longer exists, or is a threat now that restrictions have been lifted. Yet still, it remains. And still, it appears to affect families and can still hospitalise some individuals. Just more quietly. 

On a personal level, I have a lot of fears. Two members of my immediate family (one clinically vulnerable) continue to refuse any of the vaccines on offer, including boosters. They remain defiant and ignorant of the situation. In fact, it really is an elephant in the room. We do not speak about it how it will affect our plans in the future. They appear to feel that if they stay indoors, away from family members it will simply go away. Of course, it may well do so. But, I feel it is here to stay for a whole lot longer yet.

text_long_wave2: I feel like this third lockdown has been the toughest. Four weeks for the second was quite hard to get my head around, especially at the beginning. text_long_wave3:
To be honest, I feel I've really lost track of the Corona situation. A large part of this, I think, is due to the war in Ukraine, which has of course taken precedence and there's less said in the media about COVID. I'm a PhD student, and I live quite an isolated existence -- there's been few occasions in the last few months where I've been part of a large group, so I don't have too many worries about COVID right now. 

  I would say though that I still wear a mask whenever I'm shopping for food or going for a coffee. Part of this is just what I've become accustomed to I think, it almost feels natural now to slip on a mask before I enter a building, and perhaps there's a slightly irrational fear of catching the virus. I sometimes think this, particularly as I've noticed in the last few days how few people are wearing masks -- it's a rarity now. I know that's to do with government slacking of rules of course, but I still feel a slight urge to wear one, and feel exposed when I don't. The pressure seems to be changing towards not wearing one. 

It's been a while too since I had my double vaccines. This should perhaps now be a slight cause for concern, and I have noted on the BBC website in recent weeks that the case rates are rising, particularly in Scotland. One of my biggest worries is long COVID. I've heard bad things about it, particularly that the brain shrinks. If mine shrinks any more I think I will be in trouble.

Finally, I sometimes go to my parents, who are over 70. That's where I'd be worried about COVID. Did I have it and would I pass it on unwillingly? Should I always wear a mask with them? It's the times when I see them that I feel the greatest concern.
text_short_wave3: Keep cautious. Don't let your guard down. There's other important things going on at the moment, but Corona is still here, and rising. Get the vaccine, wear masks and protection, not only for yourself but for others too: we're in this together.

text_long_wave1:
I am mostly concerned for those people who are particularly vulnerable to this virus. I live with two people who fall into this category, so have been rather aware of the need to try and prevent unnecessary spread.

I am also somewhat angry with the people who do not seem to be able to grasp the potential seriousness of the situation, and who feel that because they aren't particularly at risk of serious illness from it they don't need to worry about spreading it. Fortunately those people appear to be in the minority.
text_short_wave1: I feel that the situation is serious, but manageable if people are sensible. I am hopeful that this will be eventually contained, but concerned about the long term impact on the economy and the possibility of a second outbreak.
text_long_wave2: I feel happy that the the peak of the latest outbreak appears to be past, and am hopeful that that the vaccination program is going well should eventually result in an end to widespread outbreaks. I am angry and frustrated at how poorly the pandemic has been managed by the government however. They were slow to respond to the changing situation throughout. Lockdowns were enacted too late, and lifted too early, which has resulted in a much higher number of deaths than might otherwise have happened.
text_short_wave2: I am very happy to see the number of people seriously ill falling rapidly, and that vaccinations should help to prevent another serious outbreak.
text_long_wave3:
I feel like the situation has improved a lot with the wide availability of vaccines. What concerns me now though is that the government appear to have disregarded ongoing risk and removed all restrictions including the need to self isolate for purely political reasons.

This concerns me because the current number of cases and hospitalisation is rising quickly again which has the potential to put unnecessary stress on healthcare services.

Although I feel like the risk to me personally has been reduced significantly, there is still the potential for serious problems in vulnerable people with the widespread unchecked infections.
