I think the pandemic has opened a lot of doors on where society will move next and exposed vulnerability that need to be addressed. One example of  things improving is remote working. One vulnerability is that many people can be misinformed about situations and don't listen to reason such as people not believing that coronavirus is real.

Ultimately, I feel that while there was a lot of incorrect steps that the government made during this whole ordeal now that the vaccine is done, there may be a new beginning.
text_short_wave2: Finally see light at the end of the tunnel of the pandemic
text_long_wave3:
I feel that the covid situation is being slowly forgotten about. This makes me worried as it makes people negligent and will cause further problems. I'm also worried by the number of people who don't want to take the covid vaccines as they don't understand how it works.

Since society is slowly adapting to pre-covid, shops and entertainment places have been opening up again which is good since you can enjoy yourself. Work life balance have also improved as more people are now remote working which I think is good as well.
text_short_wave3: Seems covid is being forgotten about these days. Hope people don't underestimate it as it is a deadly virus.
life_event_descr: I caught it and was hospitalised for a week

text_long_wave1: I’m very anxious about the current situation. I want to see if the lockdown has had any effect in reducing the number of cases and deaths, but don’t want to get my hopes up yet. It isn’t clear if the day on day reductions will lead to any actual trend, and I’m not sure when we would expect to know if the measures have worked. I think that people are getting fed up with the lockdown and there will be increasing civil disorder if the situation doesn’t seem to be improving. On the other hand, I’m truly horrified by the authoritarian streak that has been revealed in many people, and am disgusted at the way that rather than promoting community understanding some individuals are calling for people to be shot in the street for going for a walk. I’m looking forward to when I don’t have to work from home any more and I can do normal things like see my sister and my mum, and my friends.
text_short_wave1: Seriously anxious and fed up with the current situation. Really hoping the situation will start to improve soon or I fear the social consequences will be severe.
text_long_wave2: I’m totally fed up with the restrictions and really bored. I’m less anxious now that my mum and my in laws have had their vaccines and I’m hoping to get my vaccine soon-ish even though I’m scared of needles. I am a bit worried about the emergence of new variants especially if they have a higher death rate and escape the vaccine, but the whole thing seems like painting the forth bridge- no sooner have we vaccinated everyone then we have to start again! This whole year has felt like stasis, and I’m keen for stuff to start happening again!
text_short_wave2: I’m totally over the whole covid thing now, looking forward to getting back to some semblance of normal!
text_long_wave3: I am feeling much less worried about covid on the one hand, as I have had 3 doses of the vaccine so reckon I’m less likely to be I’ll with it, and life has to go a bit more back to normal. I’m enthusiastic about getting back to doing things like going on holiday or going to gigs, and have started to go back to working in the office one day a week. I am keen to see the back of masks and distancing. However, cases are so high now that loads of people have covid and I’m resigned to the fact I will likely catch it. That feels worrying as most people I know who have had it have been under the weather.
text_short_wave3: Feels weird that things are almost back to normal yet seemingly everyone has covid! Is this living with covid?
life_event_descr_wave3: I got married.

text_long_wave1: I am nervous about the impact of the virus on my family and friends, but I'm also highly frustrated by the restrictions put in place. It has made my job very challenging through working at home, and has added a greater number of obstacles. I fully support the restrictions, but I fear it will damage the relationship my baby daughter has with family members and hinder her development. In terms of my own risk of infection, and any subsequent complications, I am fairly secure in my ability to fight it off, even if I'm unlucky enough to contract it. I have no underlying health issues and generally respond well to illness. My main concerns centre around my parents and their ability to survive should they contract it.
text_short_wave1: This Corona virus is a scary thing. It'd help if people would follow instructions, then we'd have a chance of some kind of normal life again. Never thought I'd be chomping at the bit to get back to work!
text_long_wave2: Given the current situation with the vaccine provision to vulnerable people, I just want to be able to get on with normal life. I feel like I've aged a year and my life is no richer for it. I want my family to meet our new baby, eat out, go to the cinema, etc. I also want to be able to plan to visit parts of the world that excite me without fear of lost money due to cancellations. There's also the concern that even when these options are available again, if restrictions aren't eased they still won't be enjoyable. I just want to get vaccinated and get on with life.
text_short_wave2: Covid is killing my zest for life. The family still haven't met our new baby, and at this rate he'll be leaving school before he gets to do normal things like grab a bite to eat in town, or go to the cinema. Come on everyone, let's beat this!!!
text_long_wave3: Since the vaccinations and the boosters, I'm increasingly of the opinion that we just need to embrace the life changes and get on with what we want to do. I had covid quite badly before Christmas, and that derailed my thought process a bit but overall I want to have life experiences again. I think we've reached a point with it where we can't continue to hide away, otherwise there's no point surviving it in the first place. In hindsight the first lockdown was a lovely piece of uninterrupted family time, but it can't continue.
text_short_wave3: Come on everyone, let's get out there and go to the beach, town, cinema, festival and have an amazing time. At the end of the day that's why we had these jabs and boosters isn't it?!
life_event_descr_wave3: I lose my nan without being able to say goodbye due to the first lockdown. As a result we've become a bit closer as a family and we make sure people feel loved.

text_long_wave1: There's a slight sense of worry since there's a suspicion that this might not be a one time thing. The virus could mutate and come back even worse on a seasonal basis. Overall though I think it's likely there will be a vaccine within a year or so. It will be interesting to see how all of this social distancing influences behaviour once it is all over, and how easy it will be to return to normal. It might also be interesting to see how long this will take. I can't imagine a world where everything is back to normal any time soon. Some unsavoury characters might even tryo to take advantage of the situation.
text_short_wave1: Slightly worried but optimisitic.
text_long_wave2: I feel a bit bored, like everybody. I'm lucky to have a job where I know I'm safe to go back. I feel quite relaxed about things generally, although there's bound to be an economic hit down the line for the country. I don't know anyone who has been affected with coronavirus so in that sense it might not have hit home as much for me as it has for others. I have also not had to see how this can affect hospitals etc. I can see why some people feel as if it's exaggerrated, but then I epxect they wouldn't think that if it was affecting them as it has others.
text_short_wave2: Another day in paradise
text_long_wave3:
I feel as if life is pretty normal right now. People wearing masks are rare these days. Apparently the risk can;t be that bad if we are now happily taking hundreds of thousands of people from other countries to normal homes, unlike a few months ago when it was allegedly dangerous to even meet family members.

I think all of this goes to show that real problems highlight the fact that there never was that much danger to begin with, which rather begs the question of what this was really all about.  Overall, in my mind, the whole risk was and is massively overblown, and I hope less people fall for it next time.
text_short_wave3: It's over, if it ever began.
life_event_descr: became a father

text_long_wave1: I feel quite anxious about the situation as the future is so uncertain. I am worried about how coronavirus will impact all areas of my own life (social, economic, career, family) alongside society in general and the economy. I don’t see an end in sight which worries me even more. I am concerned that the government is hiding aspects of the epidemic from the public. I am concerned that China has been untruthful with the world and that their death toll is much higher. I am worried that there may be a second wave of the virus which will destroy all of our progress
text_short_wave1: I am worried about what coronavirus means for both myself and the country as a whole. I think the impact will be devastating on all aspects of life. I think the government is hiding the worst from us just like the Chinese government did
text_long_wave2: I still feel anxious as I don’t believe the end is in sight yet. I am reluctant to place too much belief in the vaccines helping us return to normal. There is a lot of different information out there regarding them and it’s difficult to know what to believe. I worry about the new variants and the problems they could cause. I am also worried about the social and economic consequences of the pandemic. Overall I feel too cautious to feel happy or look forward to the future, especially as even if the pandemic is almost over there are the economic and social consequences to deal with. Finally, I feel disappointed in the way that the U.K. government have handled this whole situation
text_short_wave2: This situation is not over yet. We still have to face the consequences of the pandemic
text_long_wave3: I feel worried because the situation seems to be worsening yet is being ignored by the U.K. government and media. I feel disappointed by the way the government has handled the whole pandemic and disgusted by the type of news stories that have come out since the beginning. I am concerned what will happen if this continues. I worry that the situation will never truly be over and we will have to “live” with this forever. It feels like mine and everyone else’s lives have been put on hold indefinitely.
text_short_wave3: I hate how everyone is pretending coronavirus is over when it is still a huge danger to us. The government need to finally do the right thing and address the situation before even more lives are unnecessarily lost.

text_long_wave1: The COVID-19 pandemic is currently making me feel extremely anxious and nervous about leaving the house. I see people who have taken it upon them selves to go to friends houses, go to the park and up my rural road for walks, not following the doll I’ll distancing guidelines. It’s extremely frustrating as someone who suffers with anxiety and depression because I feel like I do not have control, not over people as they can make their own choices but over my mental health as I’m forced to stay in where I won’t see my friends etc and it’s difficult. However, this can also be a blessing in disguise to me. I study French language and have been able to focus more on my studies now that I’m stuck at home. I feel on top of things for once and feel like I can catch up and keep up on all of my work as I’m doing it in my own time while also to deadlines. It’s a very contradictory time for my emotional and mental state but for everything else it is frustrating as I love being outside. However, it is selfish of others to go out when realistically that’s what’s making COVID-19 and it’s spread worse. The quicker we all stay inside and self isolate, the quicker this will all be over and we can be vaccinated etc.
text_short_wave1: Everyone stay at home. The faster you all stop being selfish and self isolate, the faster we can all enjoy the summer again. STAY AT HOME.
text_long_wave2: I am prepared to live with corona as long as we all get our vaccines. The government has handled this terribly and the blame on young people at university especially is disgusting. I just want to see my friends and family without fear of being reported etc but I also understand the importance of distancing for safety. It’s all very frustrating, I got a partner during this pandemic and although it’s going really well, we haven’t had a sleepover or some normal things couples would do because we literally can’t and that’s weird.
text_short_wave2: Torys have handled the corona situation terribly and I’m disappointed in everyone who’s made this worse. Look at other countries who’ve got past this now like New Zealand, could’ve been us but Boris is shit
text_long_wave3: At the moment I feel pretty okay and calm about it all. I was very worried at one point but I’ve had both my vaccines and my booster, and I still got it. So after having it and feeling fine I feel a bit better actually. Obviously there’s little rule about it now since the government is just kind of ignoring it again but realistically we were going to have to live with it at some point so I don’t mind so much. Things have changed for me, I have a job because of the pandemic, my grandmother got help with her dementia which lifted my stress levels and I met my boyfriend who I’ve been with for over a year and we’ve all made it through. Having all these people around me helps calm the anxieties I had towards the pandemic. Although I do still wear a mask at work (I work in a busy shop) as I still don’t trust that part, people are kind of dirty. Not in an impolite way, just the amount of people who I encounter closely as part of my job is great, and so I don’t need people coughing and sneezing on me without protection.
text_short_wave3: Covid really came and went as news didn’t It. Glad that’s over
life_event_descr_wave3: My grandmother becoming I’ll and then getting help, meeting my boyfriend early in the pandemic, having covid myself
life_event_descr: I became pregnant

text_long_wave1: I feel that countries are trying to work together and watch how each other responds to the situation and what we can learn from each other. But I feel sad that so  many people have died and in particular that nursing staff have lost their lives when they have helped so many people. I also feel scared about how we will exit the virus and what the economy will be like afterwards. I am worried for my job and that of my husband, who is self employed. I also feel sad that the weather is so nice but no one can be out there to enjoy it.
text_short_wave1: sad at the situation we're in but hope for the future thanks to our wonderful NHS.
text_long_wave2: I feel that this has been a very hard year and the lockdown that took place over the last few months was the hardest of the three because of lockdown fatigue and the cold weather. But now I feel grateful and hopefully because I've had my Covid-19 vaccine and have been lucky enough not to lose any friends or relatives to the virus. I am looking forward to seeing friends and family again but I still feel scared that I could lose my job if the economy doesn't pick up again and I also feel scared that another virus might come along.
text_short_wave2: Tired but ready to move on. Feeling grateful, hopeful and tired.
text_long_wave3: I feel that the pandemic has been overshadowed by what is happening in Ukraine which is completely understandable. However I think Covid 19 is far from over and will come back again in other waves during the summer and autumn. People must still listen to advice, act upon it and continue to be vaccinated and boosted when this is offered. International travel over the spring and summer is also a worry in that it could cause new variants to emerge. Governments will also need to plan for the coming winter with a programme of booster jabs and perhaps new restrictions.
text_short_wave3: covid19 has not left us, please stay aware and protect yourself and others.
life_event_descr: My baby daughter was born and she had a difficult time at birth due to breathing difficulties leading to a prolonged stay in ICU.

text_long_wave1: I'm mostly just worried about the whole thing. I don't want to get poorly so i am afraid about that and even more afraid of my family getting unwell. Im also anxious about what the future holds for not only me but the country in general as i fear its going to be a long time until things are ok again. And im upset as i am struggling to be stuck in the house and i dont know if theres going to be any food shortage so its a constant state of stress and worry.  im not sure what else to put as ive explained really.
text_short_wave1: Please, everyone stay inside. The longer you don't listen to the goverment rules the longer we are all in trouble for.
text_long_wave2: I very much feel Hopeless that things are going to ever change and get better. That anyone will be able to leave the house and live a normal-ish life. Fearful of getting sick and even worse dying which i know is a risk every time that i go out. Worried about my family getting sick and sad because it's been so long since i have seen anyone i love and i feel like life is slowing withering away. Just really sad, and anxious over all i hope things get better soon. i dont really think that there is much more to express than that.
text_short_wave2: Lockdown and Covid-19 sucks, all i want is to be healthy and see the ones i love the most.
text_long_wave3:
In still very worried about catching it and this is stopping me enjoying things or going about my daily life.
I'm also worried about getting very sick if I catch it but more so I'm worried and scared that I might loose my family if they catch it so we are all trying to keep as safe as we can. I am just hoping things are better soon as I feel like we are all missing out alot of life and it makes things so much harder when you're wanting to live life but you're afraid of getting seriously sick and dying
text_short_wave3: Still trying to keep safe and alive.
life_event_descr: Changing jobs 3 weeks before lockdown - meant I was in a lot less stressful environment so I could redirect that stress and anxiety to dealing with the pandemic

text_long_wave1:
Feel that the threat is still coming. Feel very lonely because I live alone. Feeling I’ve eaten too much chocolate because I’m just a bit fed up and all Easter eggs on offer at the moment!
I’m more concerned for the older people I know such as my parents and someone I’m keeping an eye on in assisted-living. 
Do you feel I need to keep reminding myself how lucky I am. I live in a nice area with easy access to open spaces and I have supermarkets in walking distance. Most of the world doesn’t have this luxury.
text_short_wave1: Feeling lonely but also feeling thankful that I live in a country where is one of the best healthcare systems. We need to look at places like India and sub-Saharan Africa. Those of the places where individuals don’t have the luxury we have.
text_long_wave2:
More hopeful than previously. Just hope I get the vaccine before I get the virus. But it’s also the least of my worries at the moment. Too many other things going on in my life.
This phase has been more real. It’s hit the north more. More people have died and more people have have the virus that I know. I’m relieved that my parents have both had the vaccine though. Hopefully I will be soon as I’m 52.
But it’s good that we are finally turning the corner. Just hope there isn’t a new variance that the virus vaccine cannot deal with.
text_short_wave2: The only way is up
text_long_wave3:
It’s dangerous. It’s increasing. I’ve had it and I’m still coughing four weeks later. I wouldn’t like to get it again.
But it is part of the government plan that everyone gets it, the week get killed off, and the rest of us have some immunity. That’s how it feels.
Put on the other and what can we do. We can’t carry on forever like this.
I guess there are fewer people in hospital than with the initial variance,
It’s a big worry that my parents, who haven’t had Covid and don’t seem to take the same precautions that I do, will get it. I’m a relatively fit 53-year-old man and was knocked sideways with it. So it’s a worry that they will get it and be very poorly.
text_short_wave3: The government plan is that everyone gets Covid to build some immunity. Someone will die through this policy, but what else can we do.

text_long_wave1: I feel anxious about the actual virus - I work in a retail bakery and on shopfloor, so it's quite a worrying time for people like us! Especially seeing many, many people coming into the store for items that are not essential. I also feel sad because all my plans are on hold, even short trips planned. I also feel sad as I can't see my boyfriend at all. The only time I see him is if he comes shopping at my store! And yet we've been together 12 years. I know it's for the best but it's a sad time.  Alongside this, I feel proud to be doing what I can to help contain this virus, by working and providing essentials to people, and by staying at home on my days off.
text_short_wave1: A terrible time for our generation, tinged with sadness and anxiety, but a time to be proud to be united!
text_long_wave2: I feel hopeful that the situation is going in the right direction, but I also feel very anxious about what will happen once restrictions are lifted. I do not want people to simply throw away what we have achieved thus far. We have come too far to just remove all restrictions and potentially go back to Square 1. I feel a bit sad because I feel as though life is passing me by, but I understand that it is the right thing to do for the good of humanity, and that I have many other things to be thankful for, such as my health.
text_short_wave2: Feeling hopeful but anxious about Covid - hopeful that there's a return to some sort of 'normal' but anxious that removal of restrictions will take us back to Square 1!
text_long_wave3: I feel less anxious about the situation but I'm aware that it is still something that should be monitored and that people should still be careful. I am still taking all precautions necessary to avoid infection, regardless of the government's rule relaxation. I feel some people think that COVID has gone and are forgetting about it, which may cause undue spread again. It is still in circulation and we must do all we can to avoid transmission. In my opinion, wearing a mask and regular handwashing is a minor inconvenience to enable the safeguarding of others.
text_short_wave3: Wearing a mask and regular handwashing is a minor inconvenience to ensure safeguarding of others.
life_event_descr: I had met a high rate of people in my life. 2 family members, 2 friends overdosed, 3 suicides, and some other things. This had been a negative experience overall for me.
life_event_descr_2: The groups of friends I felt close by had moved away during the pandemic, in the country I had been living in for 3 years.

text_long_wave1:
On a personal level, even though my job seems to be secure for now I feel general anxiety. I can work from home but the whole company needs some time to get used to this new situation. Hearing about how others are trying to cope and talking about it makes things easier.

I have mixed feelings about the global situation. Eventually, we will get through this, but it seems like some governments are only concerned about bailing out companies from this and leaving individuals in a dire situation. The economy will be fine, eventually, but people, families might not be. And that makes me anxious.
text_short_wave1: Social distancing is important, please stay at home, but it is the right time that we come closer to each other. I'm hoping that we will get through this together.
text_long_wave2: In the past year I got used to the situation. I don't have any strong feelings about it anymore. Given that we have a number of vaccinations available makes me optimistic that this will soon be over. I'm looking forward to pick up my jab as well. My work situation is still the same, I work from home most days, but I spend time at my workplace as well, where I can interact with people in person. Am also a bit worried as I have family in another country where things are not going as well as here in the UK.
text_short_wave2: Looking forward to get my vaccination. This soon will be over.
text_long_wave3:
I know that it is still around, but after two years I am tired of keeping up with all the news about it. I am vaccinated so getting infected is less of a concern, even if it happens I expect mild symptoms. 
I think the situation is not as critical now as it was last year, due to the vaccination programme, and the healthcare system can cope better now.

My work situation hasn't changed, though I interact with more people in person now that the office is open. I am not really concerned about this. 
Covid just became a thing that is here to stay and will be part of our lives now.
text_short_wave3: Covid's here to stay. Whatever.
life_event_descr_wave3: We had multiple events as we lost all of our pets during these 2 years. We are still at home on most days not going out which has a negative effect on us.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: My partner was having trouble at their workplace. Overworked and underappreciated. Eventually ended up leaving that position and also left that field of work also.

text_long_wave1: I am very worried that I might contract Coronavirus I have to care for my elderly father and I worry I might pass it into him I’m also worried about job security and paying my bills I am also very scared when I go and do the basic things like shopping for groceries and I will put this off until the last minute. I am also very angry that some people are just ignoring the social distancing and not following the rules that the government have laid out. I am also concerned that our leader Boris Johnson has been admitted into hospital with Coronavirus symptoms and I hope for a speedy recovery as he was doing such a great job and I worry that his replacement will do such a good job the nation needs him
text_short_wave1: I am very scared and worried about contracting the virus and becoming unwell
text_long_wave2: I am really worried for the future I’m scared of losing my job and how I will pay my mortgage I’m worried about my health and the health of my loved ones friends and family I don’t think we will ever fully go back to how we used to live I miss going to the theatre and the cinema and meeting up with my friends I have stayed focus on eating healthy and keeping fit by exercising  to improve my mental health and try to stay as active as I possibly can. I’m trying to support my friends who are struggling with isolation and I am currently working from home and would like to continue to work from home post pandemic as I feel this would help with self motivation
text_short_wave2: We all need to get the vaccine to support the U.K. with the pandemic to help save lives and protect the NHS
text_long_wave3: I’m worried I will contract coronavirus and become poorly and not be able to work or go out to buy essentials I am also fearful of spreading the virus and making my loved ones poorly. I feel the situation is getting better but it’s still worrying and I believe this is something we have to live with I want to do everything I can to make sure I am social distancing and protecting my loved ones from becoming ill there are still many people catching coronavirus and lockdowns stops in for a short period but when lockdowns lift the virus spreads and mutates again
text_short_wave3: Coronavirus isn’t going away this is something we have to live with do what you can to protect yourself and your loved ones
life_event_descr_wave3: I’m much more careful with Money
life_event_descr: I got a new job which deals with people daily

text_long_wave1: I feel lots of worry about loved ones, what will happen if they get the illness. Also feeling anxious about what is going to happen, how long this will last for and long term effect it might have. Anxiety is mostly driven by unknown things, living like this is doable but harder with not knowing all of these things, Relieved that me and husband have secure jobs, mine being In key worker sector (education). We are feeling proud of key workers in NHS and supermarkets etc who are supporting at possible expense of their own health.
text_short_wave1: Feeling anxious about how long this will go on for, but incredibly proud of all key workers! We can get through this.
text_long_wave2: I am looking forward to things being relaxed and being able to do more things. I have been fortunate during the pandemic that my financial situation hasn’t changed but am fed up of going to work (as a key worker) but that is the only thing I am really allowed to do. It is not good for mental health to only be allowed to work and exercise locally, it has been difficult. I also am not happy with the portrayal of education workers during the pandemic as the media and government have suggested they refuse to play their part, even though they have mostly been working just as hard as regular times.
text_short_wave2: Fed up of lockdown, can’t wait for restrictions to be eased.
text_long_wave3:
Slightly worried as cases are rising. I have been fully vaccinated but got COVID for the first time about 3 weeks ago and I felt pretty ill. I did isolate but felt difficult as legally I was allowed to go to work, fortunately my boss made me get 2 negative tests before returning.

I think there should still be some restrictions such as masks and mass indoor events legally enforceable. I am anxious that older relatives might get it, even if they are fully vaccinated after my and my husband’s recent experience as fully vaccinated younger people.
text_short_wave3: Why are we ignoring the rates?
life_event_descr: Starting my small business

text_long_wave1:
The government made an absolute mess. We had time to prepare and learn from other countries. instead they wasted time with the idea of herd immunity. Now we are royally screwed.
Mr Charles Windsor trip to Scotland is the umpteenth proof of the contempt we are hold, it is disgusting and he should pay for the care of the entire village he infected.
Scotland is trying to resolve this matter using devolved powers as much as possible but the Westminster government should do more, or nothing at all and leave devolved administration free rein and funding. Either they give the money or give instructions, can't do neither of them.
Mr Johnson illness, while we all wish him a speedy recovery, is just a proof that this virus is a serious matter.
text_short_wave1: This government is a shamble and their response to COVID-19 is ludicrous
text_long_wave2:
The long lockdown with no end in sight is hampering my mood. The isolationa and lack of social activities make every day the same. A boring hamster wheel.
I am glad that I still have a job, many lost theirs and they were hit hard. Economically I'm in a better place, but the mental health is deteriorating.
I hope that with vaccine passports we'll be able to get out, albeit with limitations.
I still manage to get in touch with friend and family but it's awful.
I am sad because working from home makes every hour the same. I work and live in the same place, there's no solution of continuity.
text_short_wave2: When the f*uck can we have a pint?
text_long_wave3: In wk 16, what strikes me the most is the fact that a purpose can provide leadership. People can follow an idea, not necessarily a person. And the broader and vaguer it is, the more powerful it will be. Issues may arise when turning into reality, I suppose. Restrictions have been lifted almost everywhere, so businesses can stop complaining and move on. If they aren't making money, maybe their business model is too 2019 and they have to change it. Not my problem. I don't want to hear their complaints anymore.
text_short_wave3: I had my jabs and still I want you all to stay away from me. Don't @ me.

text_long_wave1: I a fairly relaxed. At the end of the day, if you are able to follow the guidelines and reduce human contact to as low as possible, then you ought to be ok. I have to go out to shot but try to get out early when it is quite and with the new procedures supermarkets are enforcing, I feel fine. In addition, if you are meant to catch the virus, then you probably will. I had a cardiac arrest lasting 72 minutes last year ad survived without issue, so it kind of makes me more relaxed. 500 characters for 50P that's a canny rate of return!
text_short_wave1: Follow the rules....stay safe, live long!
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2: I think we have reached the position that we have, through good government control along with more folks obeying the rules than the idiots who have not. This is clearly reflected in current infection figures, along with vaccination levels. To say that we are the enemy of Europe is putting it mildly. The kids are going back to school on Monday, but numbers aren't as low as they were last September. I'm resigned to it, but I wish we could've had lower numbers first. I think numbers are going to climb - the lateral flow tests feel like making our kids do something unpleasant to themselves twice a week for not that much diagnostic help. Primary kids are unmasked and classes are packed and not particularly ventilated. At least the local university isn't going fully back before Easter, so perhaps our local numbers won't spike - but TBH I keep a close eye on daily covid data, I'm not sure if that's good or bad for my mental health, but I like to draw graphs. Our local numbers aren't falling for the last 3 weeks while we've been 'in lockdown' and we now know kids can catch and transmit covid, often symptom free themselves... so schools going in fully feels dodgy. In January - with numbers really high, and schools looking like they were going in I had resigned myself to catching it and hoping I got lucky (3 of my friends have had it badly, but nobody I'm close to has died). Now, with my age group maybe getting the vaccine before the summer it's going to annoy me if I get it now.

I'm convinced this government makes consistently bad decisions and makes things worse. The people who are being convinced that we have a clear timeline to 'back to normal' make me feel a bit sad, a bit angry at the state of the PM, all that.

text_long_wave3:
I feel like I have done everything I can to protect me and my family. My husband and I are vaccinated with boosters, and when my husband contracted COVID he isolated in our cellar. I was hoping a vaccination was on the horizon for our toddler, but it seems it isn't. 

At this point, I'm living my life. I cannot do more to protect myself, and so at this point I see going back to normal as the sensible option. Carrying on with how we've approached COVID (isolations) cannot be a long-term strategy -- people need friends, family, socialising, and, quite frankly, we can't add endlessly to economic debt. But I do think it's sensible to work more from home and wear masks, as these things don't take away anything from our lives.

My views are coloured by the fact that, last year, in Feb, my best friend from childhood overdosed and died (I found out in April, after this survey I think). She had had severe mental health/drug issues till the last three years of her life, where she found coping mechanisms -- seeing friends, going out dancing, etc. She relapsed six months into the pandemic and overdosed five months later. The pandemic kills in more than one way. She is dead because she was forced to isolate. Mental health isn't an endless resource.

I find it exceptionally frustrating that my parents won't fly to meet their now 2.5yr old grandson because they're scared of COVID. They have sacrificed what's essential in life for less risk (risk which will never go away and which they can't mitigate any further). I try to say they are going at their own pace. I read an article by Quentin Janes from CBC about how he had the same issue with his sister and it helped me.
text_short_wave3: Time to go forward. Let's mitigate risk where we can. Let's give mental health the same consideration we've been giving physical health for the past two years. #MissyouMel #HereComesTheSun

text_long_wave1:
The current Corona situation is completely consuming - my 8-year-old daughter is required to shield due to her health issues and as a single parent, it means I'm with her at home alone. I feel engulfed with so many emotions; relieved that we're not ill at the moment, petrified if my daughter does become ill, lonely beyond imagination yet guilty for feeling any of this when we're at home where it's safest to be at the moment. 
I feel helpless and dependent on the kindness on the others to ensure we have food and essential supplies.
Ultimately I feel scared for the first time in my life as a parent that I can't absolutely guarantee my daughter's health.
text_short_wave1: Grateful to everyone on the front line allowing us to Stay Home. Protect the NHS. Save Lives. Scared but determined to find happiness, love and hope in the everyday
text_long_wave2:
We’re approaching a year - and yet I still feel a range of emotions daily, almost as if I’m still trying to come to terms with the enormity of it all. 
I’m extremely analytical of science, data etc so whilst I can rationalise modelling, mutations etc ifs hard to balance that with how I feel. I feel guilty for still having what I deep down know are guilty individualistic desires when there are so many pressing public health pressures. I feel sadness that I haven’t been able to develop a relationship (especially physical) - yet happy that as a single mother I’ve gained such golden bonus time with my 9yo (albeit under the most strained of circumstances); it felt like the early baby days just us two all over again. 
I feel disgust/contempt for the woefully inept handling by the government, which has cost thousands of lives. 
And yet there’s a weird sense of calm - the pandemic is happening, I can’t change that, what I can do is find moments to reach for breathe from it all. 
I’m just grateful to feel, I glad I’m not numb.
text_short_wave2: My feelings about Covid-19 are varied and evolving every hour, never mind every day - I’ve come to learn that just feeling is good enough, the absence of numbness is achievement I’ve come to value.
text_long_wave3: 2 years on, and feelings are a paradox: so much has changed, yet there are so many conversations that are still the same. The fundamentals are unchanged - yet our approach to how we approach/live with Covid 19 has transformed. My life has changed so much. 2 years ago I was shielding with my daughter - since then, we've had a horrible period of poor health for her which brought with it immeasurable stress, worry and health anxiety for me. But now i'm in a new relationship; something I never planned, my daughter is stable and there is genuine happiness in my/our life. It's as if I can't allow Covid-19 to dominate the feelings I feel. I'm still very much aware of its prevalence but it's as if I choose to allocate small periods of emotional attention to it. Otherwise it will become overwhelming, like drowning. I'm not sure this is the best/right approach but it's what's working for us.
text_short_wave3: Still. Still worried, still engaged, still concerned at government's lack of cohesive strategy. But still smiling, still finding the good in abundance where it is - because there is so much - now more than ever.

text_long_wave1:
I feel quite philosophical about it. We have a member of our family who is very vulnerable health-wise, but we're used to being on that rollercoaster as a family, so perhaps we have a bit more perspective than other people. 
It has made work quite difficult - I work in a department that requires very fast turn around communication and also a lot of very hi-tech hardware, so this has all been a bit of a nightmare to get set up. We're getting there though with a good team and some very dark humour.
text_short_wave1: Could do without it, but thankful that we're not the Central African Republic. Three ventilators, five million people. We're pretty lucky.
text_long_wave2: I'm feeling quite positive about the situation, especially in the UK. Personally, my parents and brother have had their first vaccination, which was my own main concern. The weather is getting better, which means that it is easier to get outside, and I think the messages are clearer from the government - stick to the rules but we're on the way out of lockdown. I feel encouraged. I and my partner are still being very cautious; not seeing family or friends, only bubbling together, but it is not as difficult as it was. Having said that, I think lockdown fed my inner hermit a bit anyway. I'm a reader, he's a gamer, so between us we feel it could have been a lot worse.
text_short_wave2: Thankful for the NHS and a good community that supports one another. Grateful for the start of the good weather. Hoping the government does the right thing when it comes to poorer countries not being able to access vaccine when we have surplus.
text_long_wave3: In general, I feel quite at ease with the idea of Covid. I'm resigned to the fact that I will get it at some point, probably fairly soon, but I'm hopeful that it will be no worse than a bad cold. I'm grateful for the vaccinations I've had access to, and for my employer's attitude to being able to work from home and protection of staff. The only time I do start to feel more nervous about it is when, as this weekend, I am due to visit a particular family member who is extremely vulnerable health-wise. Consequently I've probably been a lot more careful in shops and public transport than I normally would these days.
text_short_wave3: Feeling more relaxed about the Covid situation than I have in a long time. The good weather probably helps. It does all come back a bit when visiting vulnerable family members though.
life_event_descr_wave3: Moved in with my partner in a different part of town.

After seeing coming off Facebook my anxiety is reduced and I become sad. I have found the best way for reducing my anxiety and sadness is staying off social media. text_long_wave2:
At this moment, I do not feel concerned about the corona situation for myself or my family, in terms of the virus as my father has been vaccinated who is the only person I have been concerned about contracting the virus. However, I am concerned for the general public, especially those who are at greater risk of life-threatening consequences. 

I feel quite lucky to be in the position I am in. I have felt anxious and nervous in the past but I have become accustomed to the situation, the idea of being able to go back to normal life makes me feel excited and nervous at the same time.
text_short_wave2: It continues to be a difficult time for all. We need to keep our hopes up and continue following the rules so we can see a light at the end of the tunnel without putting others at risk.
text_long_wave3: I do not have strong feelings towards the coronavirus situation at this moment. Personally, I am do not fear COVID as I had it in 2020 prior to the vaccinations and I am fortunate that my loved ones are not vulnerable. I do fear for the vulnerable getting COVID as this the severity of the virus is still present. It is something we, as a society, are going to have to learn to live with which I feel we are and still taking precautions where necessary, as it is not going to go away. It does sometimes hit home how I have lived through a historical moment and that is quite thought provoking.
text_short_wave3: I worry for others, particularly the vulnerable or at risk, however I feel more comfortable with the virus and I am fortunate enough that my loved ones are not in the categories mentioned. If I get covid, I would be more worried about long covid from my experience.
life_event_descr: Death of a family member. Didn’t die of covid but it impacted on our ability to visit them towards the end of their life.

text_long_wave1:
I feel pretty anxious about how things are going but I'm also hopeful that the measures undertaken by the public to slow the spread of corona are working. 

I worry about how long the current situation will continue. I'm also feeling rather frustrated by having to stay inside more (although I'm observing all the social distancing rules, regardless) and annoyed by people who aren't taking the social distancing rules seriously enough.

I'm also anxious about what the future holds once things start to get back to normal. Although my work hasn't been affected too much at the moment, I'm worried that work (I'm a freelancer) might be more scarce in the future.
text_short_wave1: STAY INSIDE
text_long_wave2: Although the vaccination rollout is underway, I'm still worried about the coronavirus situation - especially given the new variants of the virus that have emerged recently. I'm also disappointed with the way that the government has handled the pandemic, both in terms of containing the spread of the virus and in making sure British citizens have the economic resources to survive during these trying times - which doesn't fill me with hope as to how the government will likely act post-pandemic. That said, I am very excited to receive the coronavirus vaccination and I am beyond impressed with how the NHS has handled the pandemic.
text_short_wave2: Get vaccinated.
text_long_wave3: I'm currently in two minds about the COVID-19 situation. On one hand, it feels like Britain may be out of the worst of the pandemic thanks to widespread vaccination. On the other hand, however, it doesn't feel like life is completely back to normal - especially with infection rates on the rise. While I'm enjoying the fact that there are less restrictions in place currently, I’m always aware that another COVID variant could emerge and that another lockdown could happen. Overall, it still feels like normal life is on hold.
text_short_wave3: Please remember that the pandemic is ongoing. Exercise caution and please get vaccinated.

text_long_wave1: I am accepting that the coronavirus situation is what it is. I am more relaxed knowing my loved ones are now at home isolating. I am trying to make the best of a bad situation by appreciating things I can do because I am stuck at home, like spend quality time with my husband, and not have to commute to work. I am just trying to see the positives. I cannot change the situation rthat is going on, so I might as well just enjoy some of the things that have come about because of the situation. It is not a good situation that we are in, but right now there's nothing I can do to change that, It wou;ld be nice to be able to go out and do the normal things, especially when the weather is nice, but I am accepting that it is not currently possible to do so.
text_short_wave1: Can't change it. Might as well make the best of my situation.
text_long_wave2: I have gotten used to the Coronavirus situation. I've made the best of a bad situation. Hopefully it'll be less restrictive soon and we can all start relaxing and enjoying life a bit more, rather than just trying to get through it. I am nervous about being made to go back to working in an office. I prefer working from home - it's been one of the few good things to come out of  coronavirus and lockdown. I hope it stays around once lockdown has been lifted. It's been brought but I have made the best of the poor situation.
text_short_wave2: almost over now
text_long_wave3: I am worried about cases rising again while at the same time, mitigations are being removed. People are acting as if it's over when it isn't. I am still worried about catching the virus and having to take time away from work unpaid, or being left with long term complications. I feel as though the risk is greater now than it has been at any other time, and we are all being told by the government to pretend that it does not exist any more. We are being forced back in to office buildings which are poorly set up to deal with and mitigate against the coronavirus, and any concerns we have are being dismissed by our employers.
text_short_wave3: It's not over yet, stop acting like it is.
life_event_descr_wave3: New job

text_long_wave1: I find I'm very anxious about many things. Worried about my family and missing them very much. Worried about university and my final postgraduate MA classification because I have no access to the equipment, teaching and facilities required. I'm very anxious about the impact this (and the rest of the crisis) will have on my plans for further study (PhD). Also very concerned about income/finances and the very real prospect of being unable to pay rent/bills and student fees. I also feel that more needs to be done to support students and those just starting out as self-employed. Too many honest working people are falling through the support net and being left with nothing.
text_short_wave1: The world suddenly seems like an even more unsecure place
text_long_wave2: I feel quite pessimistic in all honesty. I just feel extremely worn down. My living situation and finances have suffered a lot due to the crisis and I have become increasingly depressed and anxious over the past few months. I feel quite hopeless about the future and my prospects, despite having graduated my MA and feel that there is very little to look forward to.  Coronavirus is not my only concern, but it seems to have negatively impacted every aspect of my life. Health, finances, employment, standard of living and future outlook. To be frank, I'm more concerned about my mental health and state of mind than catching the blasted virus at this point.
text_short_wave2: There is so little to look forward to. The future is very bleak.
text_long_wave3: I feel fairly anxious about it since there seem to be other variants emerging and most of the population seems to have stopped taking many precautions. I worry about my parents, who are getting older because I know the effect of the vaccine may be reduced soon. In general, I feel it is not over, and there will be more to worry about in the future, especially when winter comes. It seems to be inevitable that everyone is going to catch it eventually and I think there may be unknown long-term effects that emerge in the near future (beyond long covid) that we do not yet know about.
text_short_wave3: Don't stop living your life, but understand that the virus is still prevalent and you should still be careful. If not for yourself, then for others who are at risk. Be considerate of your own health and that of those around you.
life_event_descr_wave3: My levels of anxiety have skyrocketed, not just to do with the pandemic but generally. This has made it much more difficult to deal with everything.
life_event_descr: My partner got it and I know how I'll she is and how I want to be there to help her, but can't.

text_long_wave1:
In Answer to the previous question I expressed a level of anger and disgust. This was not to the disease or how how it is being addressed by national or local government or those responsible for treating individuals, the medical services etc. I am angry and disgusted with individuals who are using this situation to either profit from the misfortunes of others or who believe they have carte blanche to do whatever they want and everyone else can suffer. 
I have no direct fear of the virus itself or of the disease. Although I understand it is highly contagious and potentially very serious, all I can do is follow the guidelines for keeping myself and my family and friends safe.
text_short_wave1: Follow guidelines, social distance, wash your hands. Don't worry - it won't make things better!
text_long_wave2: I feel optimistic and positive about the progress being made in fighting the pandemic and I believe we can now see """"""""light at the end of the tunnel"""""""". I do not believe we will fully beat the virus for several years, if ever, but I think both as a nation and on a global basis that we will reach a point where outbreaks will be identified rapidly and controlled. Preventative measures, such as the vaccines will be improved. Treatment measures will reduce the severity of the disease for those infected.
text_short_wave2: Optimistic - it will take time but we will get to a point where Covid-19 is under control. The world will learn and we will be ready next time
text_long_wave3:
At the moment I am not too anxious about the Corona situation. I think the virus has now been accepted as something that will be with us for a long time but we have developed and will continue to develop coping strategies.
The most important of these is the vaccine and getting as many people as possible fully vaccinated. The vaccines should also be continually developed to improve their effectiveness and to maximise their ability to cope with the new variants that will arise.
Society will return to a level of normality but we will need to recognise that the virus will be part of our lives for a long time.
text_short_wave3: Back to normal as far as possible, get vaccinated, stay safe!
life_event_descr: My mental health

text_long_wave1: Currently, I feel anxious that the situation in the UK will not improve due to people flouting the lockdown rules. There is also a great sadness for the lives that have been already lost, especially health workers who are putting their lives on the line to help others survive. I hope that people, especially the government, will recognise this after the corona virus.

I have anxiety about the future of the situation, whether life will return to normal and whether any part of my degree will bear some semblance of normality. I also worry for my parents, although less so now they have had their first dose of the vaccine.

The stupidity of people is also a worry in not abiding by the very simple guidelines, and I find it disconcerting that even so called experts in the media seem unable to comprehend a simple message, without resorting to melodrama.

I would have expected a more optimistic response following the vaccinations, but again frustrated by the messages being sent out.  We have constantly had positive messages about the uptake of the vaccinations, but a rather negative reaction to wanting to open things up again.

so, frustration and wondering what the next fashion is going to be.....climate change? Possible.

text_long_wave1: I'm angry at the poor response from our government, and the attitudes of most people. It's extremely frustrating to see people wandering about every single day doing non-essential things (I work in a pet store so see this every day I go to work). The attitude of our government is reflected in the people. This won't go away if we bury our heads in the sand and pretend it's a holiday; people are dying, other people are suffering. It's not going to just wear itself out. This will only go away when EVERYBODY makes a commitment to isolating themselves.
text_short_wave1: I'm angry at our Government's poor response to this crisis, and not learning from or listening to other countries and epidemiologists, and not enforcing a stronger lockdown; people aren't listening to the """"""""advice""""""""!
text_long_wave2: Our government has done very badly at handling this, they have lied and swindled the people. They could have done so much better by caring about the people and not their pockets, by acting sooner, like other countries have done (e.g. China, New Zealand). It is extremely frustrating to see people who clearly and genuinely don't care, to be """"""""leading"""""""" this country, lying the whole time, openly and brazenly to our faces. The track and trace fiasco is a national disgrace, as is the """"""""pay rise"""""""" for NHS staff. They deserve so much better. Ghana increased their hospital staff wages by 50% over the pandemic - why can the UK, one of the richest countries in the world, not do the same.
text_short_wave2: Disgusted and furious at the actions of the Government over the last 12 months. They should be ashamed of their lack of empathy, and their gross fetishization of the contents of their pockets.

The government has recently removed all protections against coronavirus, including the most insane one - self isolation when you have the virus. you no longer have to isolate if you have a virus that can kill people. yes, the omicron version is less likely to - but for the people who it can kill, unsurprisingly this is a big deal. the government, and by extension the country, are  burying their heads in the sand and pretending this isn't happening and that it will simply go away if we don't talk about it. we have the highest infection rate yet, but the media aren't reporting on it, because covid is boring now.
i'm angry and disgusted at the inaction and inability of this government to protect its people. it just reveals what we knew already - they do not care.
text_short_wave3: im angry and disgusted at the non-response an inaction of this government towards protecting people from coronavirus. they are going with whatever they think will make people like them, instead of scientific advice to protect the vulnerable - they do not care about us.

text_long_wave1:
the corona situation is scary, but not just because of the virus itself. In fact thats the least scary part, although we are not 100% sure there are alot of facts that science can present to us about the virus, e.g; how it spread, symptoms, how people recover and feel afterwards. 

The main source of worry and anxiety and also anger is the government who are not doing enough in order to flatten the curve and keep as many people alive - e.g; under funding in nhs, not enough ppe. As well as that it is also the groups of people who either think that this is not an issue so still carry on with their normal lives going to work and meeting friends or believe it is some sort of conspiracy and so they also chose to ignore the governments advice.
text_short_wave1: we should not be angry at the corona virus but instead the responses of governments and the public who are not listening to the rules.
text_long_wave2: I think the word tired best describes it. I am tired of lockdown, tired of working at home, tired of being alone. I am a bit more hopeful though, given the vaccination programme and the current rate of slow opening and easing of lockdown. The fact it is much slower has in a way made me feel more hopeful and have more faith in the governments actions compared to last year. I get very frustrated easily and i think it is because almost everything feels out of your control at the minute. I've noticed that I get upset a lot more over little things and they feel like an even bigger deal.
text_short_wave2: I am so tired of this. I feel so powerless right now despite doing the one most important thing i can right now which is staying at home.
text_long_wave3: Currently I feel conflicted. I know that there is a huge risk of COVID becoming mutated enough that there is a new variant that does not respond to vaccines and so that concerns me. Additionally, I still haven't had covid, which concerns me as I feel like i'm due at any moment to get it. However, on the other hand, I am tired of living half my life, I was very strict with guidelines and recommendations throughout covid and lockdowns. But recently I see myself caring less and less. I still am very cautious whenever I get a slight cough or cold, and I ensure to stay at home and test myself. But besides from that, I'm tired of having to always make sure i'm being cautious and so I am now more likely to be around larger groups of people and in close proximity to them. I know that Covid is here to stay and due to many factors, this will not be the last pandemic in my lifetime. So because of that I am trying to get used to a new way of life, where I'm being as cautious and safe as possible, whilst also trying to live my life a bit more normally.
text_short_wave3: Though I am still aware of the risk covid has to many people, and could do for all in the future, I am tired of having to put my life on pause. So now I am being as cautious as possible for others whilst also living my life.

At the moment I have mixed emotions.

Anger at how the pandemic began. Anger at the people who are determined to carry on living as normal when the majority of us are sticking to the rules. My children want to see their grandparents and cousins and friends but they know they can't and the reason why they can't but it is difficult to explain when they see people continuing to play football etc.

I'm angry that my son has missed nearly half a year of school. That it took 2 months for y daughter to get into a routine for nursery and not scream every morning but we will have to start from square one.

I miss my work and my colleagues, I miss my friends and my parents and siblings. I'm upset that we have had to cancel our holiday.

I'm worried as my husband has to continue to work and risk bringing the virus home everyday for a low wage. I'm also worried that the lack of routine will have a negative impact on my mental health.

All my emotions do not matter when you think  of how many people have died worldwide  to this virus.
