text_short_wave3: Remember that covid didn’t go away just because we stopped talking about it.
life_event_descr_wave3: Promotions at work and the move to work more remotely.

text_long_wave1: I feel concerned, both that people around where I live (London) are not taking social distancing seriously, and that I or my family may contract COVID-19. I feel some anger at people I encounter on the pavements who do not make eye contact or attempt to move aside, or who give me odd looks when I move into the road to avoid them. I feel anxiety about having to perform my job remotely, as I do not feel equipped to do this well. I feel especial anxiety over the transmission of coronavirus, and the length of time it can potentially be active on surfaces. I worry it may be in the air, floating.
text_short_wave1: I wish everyone would just STAY INDOORS unless they are a key worker.
text_long_wave2:
I am very angry at China, illogical though it may be. I am also angry at international response to China, who I feel should be held to account for their practices and response which allowed the spread of Covid to be so swift at the outset. I don’t know exactly what I’m hoping for here, but possibly some international boycott of Chinese products and companies, unlikely through that is when their tendrils are creeping ever more steadily into African economies, and their commandeering of the South China seas continues unchecked.

I am worried about the new strains of the virus, and our ability to manage them. I am particularly concerned about what long term effects may gradually become apparent, both from Covid and from any vaccines (not that this will stop me having one when I get the invitation!). More a sense of resignation about these most of the time, but trepidation and anxiety if I let myself think too much about the myriad possibilities. Stoicism is still helping, though.

Some occasional feelings of optimism, probably more due to the signs of spring and my approaching sabbatical more than positive developments re Covid though, I think. Maybe it’ll be ok - most pandemics seem to have burned out within 2-3 years, after all. But I certainly feel more insular, happier to stay at home, in the UK, and fed up with tales of those travelling around still. I feel pessimistic about the chances of people/countries changing their practices in the future, and angry at the wasted opportunities to get control over climate change/scale down human expansion across the globe. Traffic on the road outside my bedroom window, London’s south circular, is back to even higher volumes than pre-Covid, I think. People are idiots - in the very literal Classical Greek sense :(
text_short_wave2: Why the fuck can’t people stop being selfish pricks?
text_long_wave3: I am fed up of the changing goalposts regarding behaviour, and the lack of united behaviour. I worry still a great deal about bringing Covid to my parents (in their 80s, one bedbound), though I've not yet had it myself. I am annoyed at still feeling morally obliged to wear a mask in shops, buses etc whilst others don't bother. The UK government and their partying during Covid while I was having to teach roomfuls of 25-30 kids through masks and in the cold pisses me right off. As I think about it, anxiety segues into rage, frankly. The lack of effort at halting the detrimental effects of international flights, travel, and industry on the environment angers me too: we had such a  great chance early on.
text_short_wave3: If we eliminated smallpox, we can eliminate Corona (less contagious, more fragile, I think), but it might actually take an effort from EVERYONE, ya know?

text_long_wave1: Nationally, I'm disappointed in the relatively few selfish idiots that continue to flout or ignore the UK lock-down restrictions, but I also realise that this is more on me to adjust my expectations of society as a whole to reflect reality rather than be upset by it. I'm also disappointed by the daily government briefings, the lack of useful information they contain and how they have quickly descended into a political defensiveness. Mistakes have clearly been made, and will likely continue to be made. No one is expecting a perfect response in such difficult times, but it's saddening to realise that even in a crises such as this, politicians will still more willing to put self and party above country and personal integrity.
text_short_wave1: The corona situation feels at once new and depressingly familiar. Politicians eager to claim credit and deflect blame, commentators eager to scaremonger, and trusted informative voices few and far between.
text_long_wave2: I have mixed feelings about the coronavirus situation overall. I was surprised and saddened to see the the general level of stupidity and selfishness was much higher than I believed, even if they represent a minority overall. I never thought I would see """"""""anti-lockdown"""""""" protests for example. I was also a little surprised to learn how much of a role political ideology factors in a countries overall pandemic response, both good and bad, and how unlikely it is that any real long term lessons will be learned to address any failings. At the same time, I'm heartened by the number of genuinely selfless and compassionate people, including medical and other critical workers, who have given so much with little thought to the their own risk.
text_short_wave2: The reason the UK got the approach right to Vaccines is also the same reason it got the response to lock down so badly wrong. Dogged one-sized fits all ideology will never deliver the best response compared to one adapted to the context. Precaution & innovation are both needed.
text_long_wave3:
I'm very concerned that the UK government is planning to relax all covid restrictions without any publicised plans for dealing with a serious new variant, entirely new pandemic, dealing seriously with long covid, or addressing how the most seriously vulnerable e.g. immune compromised, are expected to manage longer term. I have little faith that the current government is or will follow scientific and medial advice, especially when it conflicts with economic priorities and interests. 

I'm thankful for the vaccines and the booster program. I'm far more relaxed about the implications of catching covid than 12 months ago, as well as any impact on friends and family. However, I'm still very concerned about the state and underfunding of the NHS, number of covid patients, treatment backlogs, and difficulty in accessing basic services - now is not a good time to be seriously ill or involved in an accident requiring hospital treatment.
text_short_wave3: Glad to see early signs that covid may be on its way to becoming less serious, but still very concerned about attitude to long covid and the impact on the highly vulnerable by the UK government.
life_event_descr: My grandad died of the virus in April 2020

text_long_wave1:
I am worried for myself and my family, the UK as a whole - the impact of the virus will be huge. There will be a second pandemic - the aftermath. 
I just hope that everyone takes the guidance on board and takes it seriously, although I fear there is a majority that aren’t. 
I look forward to better days to come and the celebration after this but it feel strange not knowing when that will be. There is so much uncertainty. So many unknowns. 
Feeling ‘mixed up’ and mixed emotions is a fair way to describe how I feel.
text_short_wave1: I am so worried about the second pandemic that is coming - the corona virus aftermath. Will we simply be able to pick ourselves up and dust ourselves off? Domestic abuse, mental health, poverty, an exhausted nhs and vulnerable children missed. It’s coming. And I’m very worried.
text_long_wave2: I am hopeful that this is the last lockdown. It has been a really testing time for the family in lodown. I felt like it has got a bit monotonous and tedious now. I am feeling fed up and lockdown is a lot harder than it was at the start of the pandemic. I am feeling optimistic that the vaccine is the way out. It fills me with excitement that we can start making plans again: I am getting excited about planning my 30th birthday party celebrations. I am also getting excited for my best friends wedding again after it was clouded with doubt until the recent announcements of the roadmap out of lockdown
text_short_wave2: Looking forward to getting out of lockdown once and for all!
text_long_wave3:
I feel okay about it, I am glad we are all vaccinated and we can get back to normal life whilst being mindful of people that are vulnerable and taking precautions necessary to keep these people safe. 
It is good to be ablke to get back to normal life and go to shows and travel again, it was really missed and is good for our mental health to be able to get out and about again 
I do not believe enough was taken in to account to peoples mental health initially when we went in to lockdown, this should been considered more strongly. 

I feel quite safe as a young 30 something and now that I am vaccinated I do not feel vulnerable
text_short_wave3: feels good to be get out and about again now that we are vaccinated
life_event_descr_wave3: Giving Birth

text_long_wave1: As a healthcare worker I feel very anxious about the situation, mainly the risk of bringing the virus home to my family but also the lack of PPE and the uncertainty at this time. I am also embarrassed of our country that they are unable to stick to the rules of social distancing. This makes me angry and upset as I don’t think people understand the severity of the virus at all and think they are invincible. I am naturally worried about my family who I miss massively and am struggling from a social point of view. I do however feel that a lot of positives will come from this experience,
text_short_wave1: Stay at home. It isn’t difficult. Some of us have to leave our homes, you don’t! When this is all over, will you look back and think you did the right thing?!
text_long_wave2: I have started to feel optimistic at the plans moving forwards. Frustrated of how long it’s taking but understand it’s for the right reasons. I have been working from home for 6 weeks and it has been a long 6 weeks with minimal interaction. I am however grateful I haven’t been someone at home for the last year and was lucky enough as a nurse to still go out to work. We are due to have a little baby boy at the start of April and I am hoping we will be able to meet with family and friends whilst he is still little. I don’t want to lose out on those precious memories.
text_short_wave2: Optimistic for Covid plans moving forwards. Fingers crossed all goes to plan!
text_long_wave3:
Sad for all the loss over the last couple of years. Happy it’s beginning to come to an end, restrictions have lifted and normality is resuming.  Exhausted with all the news
And change in recent months. Proud of the collective achievements of everyone in the UK particularly that of the NHS - the nurses and doctors that have worked tirelessly over the last two years. Angry about the the situation with MPs and the sheer lack of trust anyone now has for them. I feel a real sense of achievement personally for working all throughout the pandemic as well as a real send of pride as a nation for developing the vaccine and the national roll out to ensure everyone is now protected against the virus.
text_short_wave3: So pleased COVID is coming to an end. Exhausted with it all to be honest.
life_event_descr_wave3: Job security and promotion increasing annual salary.
life_event_descr: A pay rise

text_long_wave1: I'm very anxious and restless at the moment. As of right now I feel very stuck in limbo, it's very hard to know what the future will be like right now and I am very worried about other family members. I don't think any of the governments around the world have handled the situation adequately and we'll all suffer even after this lockdown is over. Nobody can say what the repercussions will be so i think a lot of people must feel the same sort of fear and anxiety that I do about the Covid-19 outbreak.
text_short_wave1: Feeling very anxious and unsure about the future.
text_long_wave2: It's been literally a year now since I started my new job and was almost immediately put into covid lockdown, I've worked there about half as much time as I should have done by now and it feels strange. I don't feel socially isolated at home though, because I've always communicated with long distance friends over the internet through my teen years so I've not found myself that upset over the lack of socialising. Right now I am enjoying the lack of pressure that comes from being forced into activities just to keep friends at work and I'm a little apprehensive about that coming back soon.
text_short_wave2: I'd like to work from home a lot more.
text_long_wave3: I think I might possibly have COVID right now, but I'm waiting for test results. Which makes this really weird timing actually but hey. Actually having it doesn't feel great, my chest hurts a lot but I'll be alright, a lot of other people have not been so lucky. I hope people do not forget that the disease is still out here because it totally is but the world is just running how it used to before all this. It's a strange time I think right now because a lot of people have avoided COVID all this time just to get it now and bring the case numbers back up.
text_short_wave3: Kinda garbage tbh, wouldn't recommend it 0/10 don't forget that COVID is still here

text_long_wave1:
I am worried that it’ll effect my family. I am not that worried for me but for my older family members. I like how it has bought the country together and bought out the good in each other. 
I work in the NHS but I am still happy to go into work. Everyone is very supportive and helpful both at work and at home in the community. Staying home is hard but it is the right thing to do and shouldn’t be for too long hopefully. I am thankful for the hour exercise a day to get my 18 month son out of our flat.
text_short_wave1: Scared and worried about Covid-19 but  we will get through this together.
text_long_wave2: I am utterly fed up of it. I have been quite positive and happy throughout but it has taken a toll and I am done. My son was 1.5 years when this started and now he’s 2.5 years old. He had changed dramatically in that time and my friends and family have missed that, plus his lack of interaction with children his own age, affecting his development, is heartbreaking. I think the roadmap is unrealistic and find it hard to believe that we will be all done with everything by June 21st. We have been given false expectations plenty of times so far so why should this one be any different.
text_short_wave2: I am done.
text_long_wave3:
I feel ok about the situation. I am not worried like I was two years ago. I have recently had Covid and I felt ok with it. I am boosted, as is all my friends and family and so that helps.
I do not know what else to say in relation to it. 500 characters is a lot when you only ask for a few sentences. I feel ok about the situation and am not worried like i was two years ago. I have recently had Covid and i felt ok with it. I am boosted, as is all my friends and family. and so that has helped me feel at ease knowing the booster helps the symptoms not be too bad.
text_short_wave3: Coronavirus is still very much around but seems mostly to be coldlike symptoms.

text_long_wave1: I feel anxious about when the coronavirus will end as I’m due to give birth in 11 weeks so want things to be better by then so my newborn baby can be introduced to friends and family and I’m nervous about giving birth alone. I live by myself so I want to see friends and family as I feel lonely but my dog keeps me company. I’m also worried about money as I’m self employed and rent a flat so don’t know how I will pay my bills especially as I have a baby coming along. It annoys me when people are still out seeing friends and family and not sticking to the social distancing rules
text_short_wave1: When will this end!
text_long_wave2: I feel slightly anxious about things going back to normal and going back to the real world again as Iv adapted to this change but I’m also fed up of lockdown so i want things to go back to normal and see all of my friends and go out and about and doing the things I used to enjoy like going to the pub. However I’m on maternity leave at the moment and I’m due to go back to work next month so I feel upset I haven’t had a proper maternity leave and anxious about starting work again after such a long time off and in new conditions. I have to put my baby into nursery so also anxious about them catching Covid there
text_short_wave2: Anxious about lockdown ending and going back into the real world
text_long_wave3: I feel that life needs to go back to normal. I’m not scared to get the virus as I believe It won’t affect me hugely. I understand others are vulnerable but I don’t agree with anymore lockdowns or restrictions espeically now we have the vaccinations. I feel like the media made it out to be worse than it is and that we just need to get on with it now. I am happy to wear face masks in hospital settings but anywhere else I do not feel the need to. I have only had 2 vaccines and don’t want to have anymore
text_short_wave3: Can we all just go back to normal already? #covid
life_event_descr_wave3: Had a baby

text_long_wave1: A little worried about how long this situation will go on for, wanting to get back to normality, hoping that the numbers of people dying each day will start to go down soon, and hoping that people will listen to the advice and stay inside as much as possible. I feel grateful that my family is safe and healthy and proud of the NHS in this country. I’m trying not to watch the news too much or spend too long on social media as there is too much incorrect information and conspiracy theories which don’t help my mindset.
text_short_wave1: If we all stay inside this will be over sooner and we can enjoy our summer with friends and family. Please #stayhome 🙏🏻
text_long_wave2: I feel optimistic that life will return to ‘normal’ soon. I think that the worst is over and numbers of cases and deaths will continue to fall so that lockdown can be lifted and things can open back up again. I feel that the vaccine program is going well and making a huge difference, and will continue to do so. I don’t feel worried about going shopping and I can’t wait to be able to go without a mask on. I am looking forward to things and I see the light at the end of the tunnel better now, rather than feeling like this pandemic will never be over. I just hope that it al goes to plan.
text_short_wave2: Feeling great about the future right now, can’t wait for summer ☀️
text_long_wave3: I feel that the corona situation is not as worrying now due to the omicron being so much milder than other variants. The media coverage has also been less scary. I don’t feel worried to go to work and be around people, and I feel that the vaccines have done a good job at protecting those at most risk of becoming seriously ill from covid. I’m glad that we have got to the stage where we are living with covid, rather than hiding from it and being scared to live our lives. I feel that some practices, like wearing a mask if you’re not feeling 100% and are going to be around other people, should stay.
text_short_wave3: Happy to be able to live freely with friends and family again.

text_long_wave1: I ‎‎‎feel ‎‎‎that ‎‎‎the ‎‎‎situation ‎‎‎has ‎‎‎been ‎‎‎handled ‎‎‎terribly ‎‎‎by ‎‎‎the ‎‎‎world's ‎‎‎governments, ‎‎‎putting ‎‎‎measures ‎‎‎into ‎‎‎place ‎‎‎far ‎‎‎too ‎‎‎late ‎‎‎to ‎‎‎be ‎‎‎useful. ‎‎‎The ‎‎‎United ‎‎‎Kingdom ‎‎‎government ‎‎‎has ‎‎‎been ‎‎‎especially ‎‎‎guilty ‎‎‎of ‎‎‎this, ‎‎‎as ‎‎‎well ‎‎‎as ‎‎‎our ‎‎‎prime ‎‎‎minister ‎‎‎Boris ‎‎‎Johnson ‎‎‎making ‎‎‎stupid ‎‎‎decisions ‎‎‎(such ‎‎‎as ‎‎‎shaking ‎‎‎hands ‎‎‎with ‎‎‎KNOWN ‎‎‎coronavirus ‎‎‎patients) ‎‎‎and ‎‎‎ending ‎‎‎up ‎‎‎contracting ‎‎‎the ‎‎‎coronavirus ‎‎‎himself.
text_short_wave1: Disappointed with the UK govt.'s handling of the entire coronavirus situation. The word """"""""fiasco"""""""" doesn't even begin to cut it.
text_long_wave2: I feel like throughout this whole thing the government have consistently made the wrong decisions like keeping schools open, starting lockdowns too late, ending lockdowns too early, etc. I think for the most part people are fairly used to living in lockdown now, although I think some people are almost *too* used to it, and will have trouble readjusting once normality resumes. The people who do not follow the guidance (ignoring social distancing, hand washing, mask wearing, etc) along with people opposing the vaccines are fools.
text_short_wave2: With the vaccine rollouts in full swing it looks like we're finally on the path back to normality.
text_long_wave3: I don't think it's so bad at the moment - it feels like most people have made reasonable adjustments to living with covid present; getting vaccinated, wearing masks in enclosed spaces, etc. People are washing their hands/using hand sanitiser more often which is just good for hygiene in general, which is nice. I feel that the government lifting restrictions entirely happened way too early, and while many people have adjusted and just made those restrictions part of their everyday lifestyle - a not-insignificant contingent stopped doing all those things at the earliest available point (that is, assuming they were even doing them in the first place)
text_short_wave3: I feel like things are alright at the moment, most people are being responsible but obviously there was a bunch who stopped doing what they should as soon as the restrictions were lifted.
life_event_descr_wave3: Got a new job which required commuting to the office one day a week.

text_long_wave1: I feel frightened about the effect that the virus is having and am worried about how this will impact people over the long-term. I am currently a full-time student and have been moved to remote learning so I am concerned that my academic performance may be affected. I am also concerned for the health and well being of family members and levels of access to essential services. I have a close relative who is awaiting an operation and it looks unlikely that they will be able to get this anytime soon with the current strain on the National Health Service.
text_short_wave1: Worried about the future
text_long_wave2: I feel quite relaxed about the Corona situation at the moment as numbers of positive cases in my local area are relatively low, I also feel relaxed and hopeful for the future due to the rollout of the vaccine, everyone I know in the vulnerable category has received their first dose now which makes me less worried about infecting them. Although the new variants are somewhat concerning, I believe we have experienced the peak of the virus and that things should stabilise in terms of infection rates as more people are vaccinated.
text_short_wave2: Looking forward to getting my Covid vaccine so that I can get on with my life
text_long_wave3: At the moment, I don't feel overly concerned about the Corona situation even though cases have recently risen somewhat in my area. The reason that I am not too worried are that the situation seems to be being relatively well managed compared to when the pandemic started. We now have a much better understanding of the virus which has allowed for the development of effective vaccines and treatments, I believe that as time goes on this will only get better and even if we still need additional booster shots I think they will have greater efficacy over a longer period of time. Most people that I know have now had Corona at least once and have made a full recovery which has helped to allay my fears around the virus, although I still do feel sad that some people are not taking it seriously and that so many lives were lost at the height of the pandemic.
text_short_wave3: I feel that we are over the worst of the Corona situation and will have better, more effective vaccines and treatments for it going forward which makes me feel positive.
life_event_descr_wave3: Losing a loved one to cancer.
life_event_descr: Mother in law has a progressive health. Catching covid could be fatal for her.
life_event_descr_2: Both eldest children changed from home education to college to prepare for exams.

text_long_wave1: I am very anxious for my children and relatives. I want normality back again for my children. I just want to do simple things like walk in the forest and 'pop' out to the shop. I just want the world to heal and this be behind us. I wish for freedom again and safety for the people who are risking so much. These people are going beyond the role that they are paid for. I hope after this that the government will realise they should be funding the NHS in a better way. I hope that our Prime Minister sees that things need to change.
text_short_wave1: What a day! I hope everyone is safe and well
text_long_wave2: I feel sad that my children have missed out on so much school. I feel sad that I have lost my business because of the situation. I feel anger that the government have not listened to experts and that perpetrate fear and have made people scared of people. I don't like seeing covered up faces and I worry about the impact on peoples mental health. I do not want an injection and fear that it will be impossible to live again as we once did. I worry my children will not have the school and university life that I had. I wish this had all never happened. I know more people that have dies from mental health issues during this time than covid. I live in a large town and I don't know anyone who has had covid, yet the fear surrounds us everywhere we turn.
text_short_wave2: Back to school Monday. No masks. No testing. Let kids be kids
text_long_wave3:
I feel happy that some of the things the government have hidden from the public are starting to be reported on in the press. I feel pleased that schools and businesses have been able to return to their usual operational capacity.
I feel sadness when I see people in face masks, who have probably had all their vaccines.
I feelsad that my grandmother and father have both deteriorated in health as they were too fearful to leave their homes. They have lost their support and social networks.
I do not like how the government are still spreading the message that vaccines stop people getting ill from covid. People I know who have not been vacinated have had no symptoms when they have been positive. People who I know have had vaccines and boosters have been incredibly unwell and hospitalised. I feel anger with the government for spreading untruthful propaganda in schools about covid.
text_short_wave3: Covid ... that was forgotten about quickly?
life_event_descr: Failed fertility treatment, miscarriage and ectopic pregnancy
life_event_descr_2: Fertility treatment ending

text_long_wave1:
I feel anxious about the situation, normal life has been completely disrupted, finances are up in the air and no one knows if and when things will return to normal. 

Added to this people, of all ages are dying suddenly from such a horrible virus. The virus doesn't discriminate or care and there is very little, it seems, we can do to prevent or recover from this illness.

I feel nervous about how long this will go on for, what the future will be like and how both mine and my partner's professions will recover following this. I am also nervous about my health and the health of my friends, families and colleagues.
text_short_wave1: Disruptive, deadly and dire - the coronavirus situation currently. Hoping people stay safe and healthy during this strange time.
text_long_wave2:
I am tired and anxious in general. I am angry and upset that due to the situation I was unable to see my nan and then she died unexpectedly.
I would like to see people and experience life once more but I understand the reasons for not seeing people at the moment. 
I am generally trying to remain healthy, active and positive that hopefully soon life will become a bit more normal and we will have a bit more freedom again.
I am anxious about all children returning to classrooms in one go on the 8th March, I am a teacher and as much as I am looking forward to seeing my whole class again I do have concerns about what will happen if the infection rate goes up again.
text_short_wave2: I am looking forward to the day when I can see friends and family again and hug them without concerns of making them ill.
text_long_wave3:
I feel it is being brushed under the carpet. Coronavirus is still very much around in large numbers and people are becoming very ill. It is concerning that the government have removed all of the measures to try and protect individuals. I don't think people will pay for Lateral Flow tests especially with the constant price rises and the extortionate costs of them. 
I am very concerned about what the country will face in the next 6 months to one year and feel that not enough is being done in the face of a continual very real threat.
text_short_wave3: I feel despair over the current situation. I feel that the situation is being brushed under the carpet. I am unsure what the future of coronavirus looks like.

text_long_wave1: It is hard to relax at the moment with everything on the news and so much disruption to basic living.  I feel frustrated at not being able to pop out to the shops to get food, without feeling like I could be in serious danger!  It has meant I have had to order things from various websites other than the supermarkets (who are completely booked up and unavailable) which is a hassle and doesn't include fresh produce.  But it is better than nothing and at least I feel safer with an older family member here so we are not risking ourselves by going out.  Just have to hang in there and hope this too shall pass!
text_short_wave1: However tempted we are to go out, it just isn't worth the risk atm! There are lots of online shops for food items other than the supermarkets so we are using them for now (for tins, biscuits, fruit puree etc.), at least it's safer.  And I exercise in the garden! Stay safe people!
text_long_wave2: I'm feeling just a bit depressed at the never-ending saga of the lockdown, and the frustrating feeling of restriction and helplessness.  Also weariness and mental tiredness of doing similar things every day and not wanting to go out anywhere to avoid people and awkward situations.  But also this is tempered with a glimmer of hope with the vaccines and possible improvement to come.  (Assuming the vaccines aren't a plot to kill us as well lol)!  This feels like I am being tested to the limits of my mental endurance but I realise it could be much worse if I actually had the virus and was in hospital.
text_short_wave2: Feels like I've been in hibernation for the winter!  Looking forward to some spring sunshine and being freed from these lockdown shackles lol!
text_long_wave3: I think it seems to be receding into the background slowly.  People I know are taking a more blase view of it, as many have had it with only mild cold-like symptoms.  But they have had the vaccines so are probably more protected.  Those who haven't may still suffer worse problems if they catch it.  And there is a new variant called Deltacron which may cause problems in the future.  This apparently has the higher transmission of Omicron with the severity of Delta (as Omicron is supposed to be milder), so I hope this doesn't start becoming the standard!
text_short_wave3: Well seems like everyone and their dog has had Covid by now!  Anyone left?  (Whoops, excluding me lol!)

text_long_wave1: I feel anxious all the time to varying degrees, sometimes becoming fearful particularly when the news deteriorates. I am worried about my family, the country and what is going to happen. I am finding it difficult to sleep. I am trying not to watch too much news on TV or on my phone, as a means of trying to control my anxiety, however I am still very worried. I desperately hope that a vaccine can be found as I think this would be the most likely way out of the situation.  I am washing my hands a lot and am worried that the virus could be transmitted by packaging or via the post.
text_short_wave1: Constant anxiety that varies in degrees, but is with me all the time, and sometimes becomes fear. Tense and finding it difficult to relax.
text_long_wave2: I think the situation is improving and itseems as though the vaccination program will give us a way out. However I still feel anxious about going outside and worried that people will not respect the rules once they've been vaccinated or the government will relax the lock down too quickly. I also am unsure how much personal protection the vaccine will give and will carry on with wearing a mask and social distancing. I would like to know more about how long covid can live on surfaces as this is a concern for me.

I am worried about the whole situation getting worse again. I don't trust the Government's road map or the Government in general. People around me are making plans for the opening up already but I feel it's too soon to know anything. I feel some hope and optimism but that Hooe is tempered by all my negative feelings.
I'm more worried me or my husband catching the virus now than I was at the start because of long covid and the unpredictability of it all. Previously I was more focused on my parents and in-laws but they have been vaccinated now. I'm also worried about the new variants that keep popping up and the possibility that we'll have to start all over again with the vaccine. 
I'm bored and frustrated by working at home and feel ineffective because of it. 

I miss my friends and feel my life chances have been significantly impacted - my husband lost his job in August and now had a temporary one which has prevented us from getting a mortgage. I feel like my chances of having a child have also been affected as I am taking medication for my mental health and haven't been able to access the support I need to start to come off it. The medication would potentially hurt the foetus and I can't add that to the other risks of having a child at my age would bring.
Overall I know we are a lot better off than lots of other people but it's been a slog. We've been locked down since November in our area and I haven't seen my parents or my friends in my home town since September.

text_long_wave2:
I am fearful, working in education without being prioritised for a vaccine. 

I am angry that I had my first baby in April 2020 and my experience as a first time mum has been hugely impacted by COVID 19. I had to labour on my own in hospital, I had to stay for three nights without my partner being allowed to visit. Our after care has been impacted by the lack of services available. I have not seen my family due to restrictions as much as I would like. I last saw them in October, they have missed out on my daughter and I have missed out on support. Current restrictions in place mean I can’t even have any celebrations for her first birthday with my family. I appreciate thousands have died, however this is how covid has impacted my life personally. 

I am so angry about this, and have now returned to work. My maternity leave is over and I have to leave my daughter in nursery care. I can’t kiss her when I drop her off as I have to wear a mask. She cannot see the smiles of her nursery workers as they are in full PPE. I cannot step foot inside the nursery to see where my daughter spends her days. 

She is an IVF baby and so longed for. This experience is not what I wanted for her or for my family. We deserve more.

text_long_wave1:
I think the best words to describe how I feel are busy and overwhelmed.  I am busier then usual because I now have 5 homeschool children at home, whereas I am used to them being at school during the day.  I am feeling overwhelmed because suddenly far more people want to interact, video chat, call, text, e-mail, etc.  I am an introvert and I find the amount of social check-ins that are suddenly expected to be very overwhelming, time-comsuming and exhausting!  I feel like between 5 busy children at home and outside people constantly demanding my attention via video call, mobile phone, text, etc, that I am overwhelmed with expectations.  
I don't feel fear, worried or anxious because I don't have time to feel those things.  I don't have time to dwell on the situation we are in.
text_short_wave1: Our children are the leaders of tomorrow -- but only if we keep them safe at home today.  You may choose to risk your life, but they don't have a choice.  Keep them at home.  Keep tomorrow's leaders safe in order to keep our country's future safe.  It's all for the kids.
text_long_wave2: I took a job as an essential worker 6 months ago.  When I took it I was a bit more anxious about catching or spreading the virus.  Six months later and that fear and anxiety has dwindled.   I think I have accepted the fact that I might get it, but I am doing everything I can to protect myself and my family.  I wash my hands constantly and expect my children to do the same, especially after coming in from outside.  We use hand sanitizer regularly.  I wear a protective gown, gloves and protective glasses at work, and dispose of my PPE carefully and properly.  I am not going to live in fear, but I am going to live with caution.
text_short_wave2: Catch the virus or not - it's not in my control, but God's.  I am simply responsible to be vigilant and careful.  Nothing else is within my control
text_long_wave3:
I am saddened by the corona situation.  I am sad for my children who have missed so much because of Corona - they have missed out or lost more than most other children I know, and I hurt for them.

I am sad for my parents who desperately needed help during this time, but were cut off, isolated, and left alone when they needed support.  

I am sad for the seniors I work with every day.  Some of them have gone over two years without seeing family.  The depression and heartache they experience does not make them feel like they were better off in isolation.  Most of them say they would rather have had six months with their family and then contract Covid symptoms and die than experience trying to manage the long days and crushing loneliness that Covid isolation has brought.  

Not to mention that the government keeps making promises and not fulfilling... I feel like I cannot trust my government to make decisions that are in the best interest of the common people.  I feel like I have no control over the future of my family.

So, all in all, it makes me sad.  Not angry, but sad - and a little wistful.  I pray the coming year is better for us all.
text_short_wave3: Corona isolation has stolen more lives than the virus - it has destroyed relationships, ripped away opportunities, financially decimated families, shattered dreams, and obliterated HOPE.  Was the """"""""cure"""""""" worth the sacrifice?  Many will never recover from the effects of the remedy.
life_event_descr_wave3: My father was hit by a truck and spent 6 weeks in a coma.  My family moved countries to be able to support my mother and offer him the support he'd need if he lived - new city, new country in covid.
life_event_descr: Parent reduced work hours to allow me to have a better work/life balance

text_long_wave1: I feel at this point that we've settled into our lives in this new routine. I'm not struggling with any of the measures put in place and it's been great for my partner to get to work from home. Although I of course hope the situation improves quickly from a public health perspective, I could personally maintain this life in lockdown for a few months quite happily assuming my personal situation doesn't change much. Some positives have been more time for exercise (using fitness videogames) and leisure activities, and discovering new ways to interact with friends and family while apart.
text_short_wave1: Hoping for the situation to resolve soon for all those negatively affected, but for now, I'm just following the guidance and making the most of the new normal. There are so many wonderful resources to enjoy if you've found yourself with more time, there's no excuse for boredom.
text_long_wave2: We are very much settled in the way things are right now, and the weekly shop is pretty much the only thing that causes some COVID-19 anxiety. It wasn't long ago that the proposed roadmap for coming out of lockdown was announced, and I think the full lifting of restrictions is too soon. The date is also right before my birthday, so I'm hoping others won't try to pressure me to do something sociable, because I'm not comfortable with going back to normal until I've had both of my vaccine doses. It's still long enough away that I'm not giving it too much thought right now though as things could easily change.
text_short_wave2: Much love to everyone behaving appropriately right now, and to those who will respect others' boundaries and comfort levels as restrictions begin to be lifted. If that's not you, please reassess your life choices.
text_long_wave3: It feels strange now, because infection rates are higher than I think they've ever been, and it's only within the last few months that a number of family members have become infected, yet we're almost living life entirely as before the pandemic. My partner and I had continued to wear masks in supermarkets and on public transport, but last weekend we took a trip to London and Lee-on-the-Solent, and so few people were wearing masks that we only did so when shops had signs requesting it or we felt they were particularly cramped. This is strange because we've been so cautious throughout the whole thing, and this weekend away was probably the greatest risk we've taken so far in terms of likelihood of catching it, and yet we weren't terribly cautious. We've had both vaccine doses and a booster, and I suppose many people now just feel there's not much more we can do but return to normal life.
text_short_wave3: So... I guess it's a return to life as we knew it before 2020, and COVID-19 is just a risk we live with now. Is there anything more I haven't considered in feeling this way?

500 characters isn't a few sentences! Few is two to three, so please make sure your questions are clear. This is really really annoying and means I've had to pad out this answer.

Living with Covid is like flying without dials. So reckless. We should carry on testing.

If tests aren't free there should be information where to buy them

text_long_wave1:
i am very sad and worry about whats going on in the country, unable to leave the house and starting to feel depressed being trapped in and away from friends and family. Worried things will not go back to normal for at least half a year.
I worry that this could lead to depression for a lot of people if we can't go back to normal. Restaurants and bars have been closed for long time, lot of business will be forced to close down and people will lose their jobs.
I worry that my parents will get corona virus as they are at that age of over 70. Some of my friends have bene forced to take furlough from work.
text_short_wave1: At times like these we have to stay strong, emotionally, mentally, stay in doors..Stay safe
text_long_wave2:
I am very nervous that it is still going on, I miss going out and seeing my friends and going to restaurants.
I want lockdown to be over, I really need a holiday and a break from work. Work has been so hectic at the moment can't even leave the house. 
The vaccine needs to work so we can go back to our normal life's, been nearly one year since we went into lockdown.
Since we went into lockdown last year I have been working from home on a daily basis and not hair a hair cut in 4 months now.
Government is going too slow on opening shops and restaurants
text_short_wave2: Corona virus can go to hell, made my life a nightmare, i want my social life back
text_long_wave3:
i feel more relaxed and happier that the rules have changed and shops and bars are now opening up more. No more isolation and slowly getting back to the normal life.
I now get to see my family more often. It's also nice to go out to cinema and watch a film.
Don't feel so trapped at home now at the moment. Also soon be able to travel again on holiday. The more people that have the booster jab vaccine the less likely Covid will get spread around and infect other people.
Being able to spend time around my family and friends is good for my mental health instead of being alone on my own.
text_short_wave3: Glad Covid is over. Summer coming, shops opening, no more isolation, time to enjoy life again

I believe we should be in a full and proper lockdown like other countries. I fear for my children and their futures. My son is 4 and just about understands school is closed and we aren't allowed out and we cant see family and friends. My husband has been furloughed and that worries me as we're not in control of things. I hate going to the supermarket because there's always a minority of people who wont or dont socially distance themselves.
text_short_wave1: Nervous AF. Stay At Home!!! Fearful for the kids future and so bloody scared RN.

text_long_wave2:
I am very anxious as the schools have literally just re opened and my son is back to school, i am anxious for him about how much time he has missed and how much he has missed his routine and his friends. I am sad because I miss everyone so close to me, i havent seen grandparents for months and my youngest child hasn't seen family in nearly a year and that is half her life wasted and gone from meeting everyone. 
I am annoyed and disgusted with the government for taking so long at trying to handle this situation, I am annoyed they are forgetting close friends of mine because they are newly self employed. I am annoyed at managers and business owners whop think the rules do not apply to them. My husband is NOT a key o9r essential worker, so why has he been working this entire time INSIDE peoples houses?! And not having the opportunity to be tested weekly etc.
text_short_wave2: Angry, anxious and dismayed at the current pandemic....#gonnabeoversoon
employment status_wave2: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave3: I feel the restrictions lifting was very bad timing and in no way indicative of corona going away. I feel it is coming back with a vengeance because people are no longer willing to comply with mask wearing or even social distancing. It worries me how rife the virus is within schools, however with tests now costing people money, some just wouldn't be able to afford to purchase them and so therefore they won't be testing as frequently as before. This is a concern especially for those who are vulnerable and those who are at higher risk of catching the virus. I do believe a lot of people, especially those aged 30-50 believe that they wouldn't have had the 1st booster job had they of realised how quickly the restrictions were going to be lifted. I also know a few of those aged groups refusing to get any additional boosters required.

text_long_wave1:
Primarily, I am extremely anxious about the whole situation. I am worried about the health of my family and friends, myself and the world in general. I am worried about the economy and everyone’s livelihoods. And I am worried about my future plans, which this whole situation is threatening to affect quite profoundly. 
I am also very angry. I’m angry at how people making poor decisions and breaking the law led to this outbreak starting in the first place. And I’m angry at how unprepared governments around the world have been for this sort of situation.
text_short_wave1: I am very anxious about this whole situation- worried about people’s health and the economy, and sad that bad things are happening. I’m also very angry that all this has been allowed to happen and that we were all so unprepared for it.
text_long_wave2: Overall, I feel depressed about everything. The corona situation has robbed me of my dream job in America, and is making everyday life a misery. I currently work in a supermarket, and the company doesn’t seem to care about keeping us safe, and a lot of our customers don’t follow social distancing or mask wearing rules. The government has let all of us down with their dreadful mismanagement of the pandemic and I will never forgive them. I do, however, feel optimistic about the future. We have the vaccines and cases are falling, so it seems things might finally get better.
text_short_wave2: Whilst things are getting better and the vaccines are working, the situation is nonetheless dreadful and depressing. The government have mismanaged the pandemic massively and have let us all down.
text_long_wave3: I feel a lot more relaxed about Corona than before, mostly due to myself and my family all having been vaccinated against it. However, it is still a threat and still has the potential to cause significant disruption to life, so I remain cautious, just not as much as I was before. It is frustrating that the UK government is ending free Covid testing, as this is an important tool in tracking the virus, and helps people to make responsible decisions and protect others. We must remain wary as new variants could occur at any moment.
text_short_wave3: I’m not as worried as I used to be due to the success of vaccines, but I still believe that we need to be cautious, as Covid is still a dangerous virus with the potential to mutate into new variants.
life_event_descr_wave3: Getting into a committed relationship
life_event_descr_2_wave3: Losing out on a job opportunity due to lockdown
life_event_descr: A good friends son died of covid and I see this women cry daily at work and it’s heartbreaking to see such a lovely family lost without their only son and she couldn’t even have a proper funeral for h

text_long_wave1:
I feel anxious about the current situation because of the uncertainty and how much it has affected our daily lives so far, and we do not know how long it is going to go on for. It is worrying hearing about the current infection rate and the increase in deaths per day. I am also angry at all the people that are completely ignoring the requirements for us to socially distance ourselves from relatives and friends. 
I feel worried about the lack of robust information about Covid-19, for example the lack of information on how to 'treat' the virus and fear that way more people are actually infected than the official figures show.
text_short_wave1: I feel incredibly angry at those ignoring the quarantine measures in place to protect us and mitigate against the spread of the virus; we drastically need to slow the anxiously rapid infection and death rate in order to protect our most vulnearble.
text_long_wave2: The Covid situation at the moment is very worrying with schools reopening. I am fearful that the Covid situation will get worse again before it gets better. I feel sad at the amount of pain this has caused people, including the people close to me. I am angry at how much COVID is having an impact upon my education and my health, it is affecting my day to day living and I am also nervous that restrictions will be lifted in the next few months. In addition, I am incredibly angry at those who are ignoring the Covid lockdown rules.
text_short_wave2: Covid has had an huge impact on our day to day living, our education and our healthcare. I am very wary of the situation getting worse before it gets better - another lockdown would have a devastating effect.
text_long_wave3: I feel worried about the increase in transmission of Covid-19 more recently. I am not however worried about contracting COVID-19 and I go about my normal daily business. I feel sad at all of the disruption that COVID-19 has caused to society and the pain that it has caused individuals but  I feel optimistic for the future. I am happy that life is able to resume as normal, but there is still a concern of another variant that is potentially more dangerous that the current one. I am angry at the inaction of the UK government at the very start of the pandemic, however I feel like it is time to move on.
text_short_wave3: Does the current spread of COVID-19 concern anyone else? I think it is time to move on, but it is still at the back of my thoughts.
life_event_descr: I got a new job during this time.

text_long_wave1: I feel anxious, restless and worried about my relatives. Annoyed at the world's governments for not acting sooner, and concerned for the effect it will have on my child. I enjoy staying at home, but feel frustrated at not easily obtaining groceries and that I can't spend time with my grandparents. I'm generally an optimist but feel that this problem will affect us for quite a long time, and long-term am extremely concerned that vulnerable relatives will contract the virus and die. I also feel despairing of people who are not taking the threat seriously.
text_short_wave1: Can't wait for this all to be over, it is so difficult knowing that spending time with loved ones could harm them.
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2:
I’m glad that my parents and grandparents have had vaccines, which feels hopeful for the future. But i’m sad that my child can’t have the social experiences that I think she should at this age. I’m frustrated that we are stuck at home and it’s too cold to go walking or play outside. 

The weather is compounding my mood - if it was sunny and warm I wouldn’t mind so much. But the months of freezing weather have made me so miserable.

Overall I have benefited from the virus, I got a job in an industry that’s profiting and can work from home, but recently it’s been hard to see the up side because it’s been so long. Even small things that would make me happy at the moment, like nipping to ikea for a new piece of furniture is impossible. I feel totally stuck and fed up, and overworked.
text_short_wave2: So fed up, looking forward to some warm weather and taking the kids out to see friends when the farm park reopens. Feels like winter has gone on forever!! Not long now... I hope!

text_long_wave3:
I feel less scared and also optimistic now that we can plan holidays and trips again. But i am also apprehensive in case we are suddenly inhibited again, due to personal illness or national lockdowns. 

In general i am happy that we are kind of back to normal, while retaining things like home working which directly benefits me. 

Although almost everyone i know has had covid, i don’t think my family or i have, so i am slightly worried that we might feel really ill if we get it. This doesn’t really affect what we choose to do though, as i don’t like crowded places anyway and choose to avoid them regardless of virus status.
text_short_wave3: Happy that we are beginning to live our lives again, cautiously.

The constant and conflicting news stories are relentless and I find myself doomsurfing on the internet and social media most days, including late at night, which is preventing me sleeping
text_short_wave1: Fed up of the constant and conflicting news stories. The onslaught is relentless. In a constant state of anxiety.

As I am vulnerable and cannot be vaccinated at the moment, I'm really scared about the future as I think people will stop caring at all about social distancing and face coverings as soon as they are vaccinated, not considering those of use who are vulnerable but cannot be vaccinated. It is a very scary time and I don't know what the future holds apart from more shielding and isolation and anxiety.
text_short_wave2: Fed up of people's selfish behaviour with no thought for the vulnerable.

I actually enjoyed the lockdowns, especially the first one. It was exciting and different and I had a great time, one of the best periods of my life to be honest. I have another daughter in the UK who is recovering from a mild case of Covid-19, so feel relieved about her recovery.
text_short_wave1: Wishing Boris Johnson a long life and a short premiership.

text_short_wave2: The NHS will beat coronavirus not because of Johnson and Hancock, but in spite of them.

text_short_wave3: Let's all get out and celebrate the end of omicron before the next variant comes along. Life between waves of covid is what you make it!

text_long_wave1:
I feel very sad and frustrated. My father was diagnosed with motor neurone disease just before coronavirus took hold. I am so sad to be missing out on precious memories with him and hope once this is all over I will still have time.  We have had to cancel our family holiday to Italy and I worry I will never get that chance again.  
I’m worried for my husband who needs to return offshore next week and fear for his safety. 
Myself and my daughters have been self isolating for 5 weeks now as my eldest daughter is immunosuppressed.  My children miss their friends and schools. 
This is an extremely hard time for everyone but we all need to do as we have been asked and we will get through it.
text_short_wave1: Everyone needs to listen to the instructions that have been given by our government.It makes me so angry to see pictures of people relaxing in parks,people thinking they are invincible!Myself & my family have left the house 3 times in 5 weeks for food collection order that’s all!
text_long_wave2:
I feel robbed of life for over a year - my children have suffered greatly and I worry about the experiences they have missed.  My terminally ill father has missed out greatly - from the lack of support available, services cut, unable to see friends, enjoying holidays and just generally everything that would have made his life a little easier at this difficult time. 

I feel we could have recovered from this a lot quicker as a country as we are an island and could have stopped travel right from the beginning that makes me angry.
text_short_wave2: I feel very angry that covid has been allowed to take a year of our lives and we are still living in lockdown when some other countries are much nearer to living a normal life with cases almost eradicated.
text_long_wave3: I find the current situation quite frustrating, I feel it is time we move on with our lives, lift restrictions etc but it is still quite scary.  I don’t understand why we can’t get back face to face with our doctor yet I can go to a football game or party it just doesn’t make sense. I’m angry for all the time I have missed with family over the last 2 years, my father passed away from motor neurone disease in October (he was diagnosed just before the first lockdown)and when I think about all the things he could have still done and friends he could have spent time with had covid not been here it makes me really upset.
text_short_wave3: Covid has affected us all very badly, it is time we will never get back but it is time, as scary as it is, to get back to life!

text_long_wave1:
I feel incredibly sad that so many people are dying with this horrible virus. It seems to be a real genetic lottery at the moment and it all depends on your genes to see if you survive or not. 
I am also angry at the government for not investing in the NHS which they are now relying on heavily to pull everyone through. 
I also feel anxiety for the people currently suffering and for my family. If the age at which people die from the virus now no longer just limited to older generations, then it stresses me out that anyone close to me can die.

A bit fatigued by it all now and hoping it will all end soon.

I think the whole pandemic has meant people's priorities have changed significantly. I am still working from home but do feel that work has invaded home life. I have put better steps in place to look after my mental health. On the good side being there with my family and getting to school runs and not having to take the tube has been a god send. I don't miss the commute at all.
text_short_wave2: Fatigued. Tired. Exhausted. When will this whole thing end. Will we get better?
text_long_wave3:
While the Covid situation seems to have 'gone away', I don't think it will ever leave us and it is something we will have to live with forever I expect. I kind of agree with the living with covid plans as I expect we all have to learn to live it. I do also think that eventually, Covid will be just another flu which also kills vulnerable people each year. 
It is at this time I wonder if perhaps a look back over the last 2 years we can see if there was a way we could have done things differently. Lockdown changed a lot of peoples lives but not always for the better. I do wonder if younger generations will remember this and how they will think or look back to this time.
text_short_wave3: Feel like Covid will never leave us but am also blessed that my loved ones weren't severely impacted by this deadly disease. Also feel sorrow for those who didn't survive and hope they all rest in peace. Wishing everyone a blessed day and remember life is short so live to the max

Corona is very scary although things are easing off still scared of potential relapse in virus causing future lockdowns and causing depression.

As it stands I am still nervous just to fact that virus has not gone away but people are still dying and getting infected with yet people have gone back to normal life style.

I understand life goes on but we still need to be cautious and also show a bit more understanding for other people fears and anxieties with the virus and respect peoples personal space.

life_event_descr: I became unemployed at the beginning of the first lockdown (March 2020) and did not have any work until October.

text_long_wave1: I’m scared someone in my family home will get the virus and end up severely ill in hospital. I’m constantly worried that if any of us go into hospital they may die alone. This worries me more with my two children. I’m being eaten up with anxiety at the thought of them being scared and without their mum or dad to make them feel better. I’m paralysed with fear that there may not be life support equipment for any of us should we need it. I’m concerned that if any of us get the Corona virus it’s missed as being severe enough to go to hospital and we die at home in pain. I am doing my best to keep my family away from other people so we can stay as healthy as possible
text_short_wave1: I am so petrified of someone in my home getting the corona virus. My anxiety is through the roof. What if they don’t have a ventilator for one of us? What if one of us doesn’t fit their criteria for staying alive?!
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2:
I feel quite content in my knowledge and understanding of covid and how a virus mutates.
I do not feel confident in the governments dealing of this. Far too many mistakes by them. Big organisations, including supermarkets have a pandemic policy in place. It took far too long for this to be implemented.
I’m happy my children are back at school but not happy if they have to isolate for a period of time. My youngest really struggles with the constant changes and not knowing if he is in school or not. Bearing in mind that we haven’t been around germs for a long time my children will catch something which will mean more time out from school.

Conspiracy theorists - keep out! 
#coronavirus #covid-19 #tinfoilhat #seeapsychologist #getwellsoon

text_long_wave3: I’m no longer as worried as I was about covid. I feel that it’s only a matter of time before we all get it. I do worry about how the NHS will cope and I worry about the economy from the lockdowns. I think we have a better idea of the virus and how it develops and mutates which helps me feel more relieved. I understand there are people who are more vulnerable than others and will have more severe symptoms. I feel it’s time to live with the virus but we also need to follow simple protective measures.
text_short_wave3: Learn to live with covid and follow simple protective measures. #livewiththevirus #wearamask #washyourhands
life_event_descr: Got a new job which required commuting to the office one day a week.

I also feel worried that I will contract the virus and pass it onto my family as I am a keyworker and I still have to go to work. I also feel
text_short_wave1: Sick of the media trying to scaremonger people and making people feel more worried than they need to be.
text_long_wave2: I feel concerned that the Coronavirus will continue to rob many lives and affect our lives for the future. It makes me feel anxious as I wonder what the world will look like when it is safe to return to some normality again. It makes me nervous thinking about what ‘’normal’ might be and whether we will have a new normal that we have to just adapt to. Coronavirus has affected every person in some way and it has changed the world. It makes me feel anxious thinking about the amount of people who have lost their jobs, their homes and their families.
text_short_wave2: Coronavirus is taking so many lives it’s scary!
text_long_wave3: I don’t feel as concerned about getting coronavirus anymore as I have had it twice and I didn’t tend to be too poorly, I am highly anxious that lots of people nearby are catching it again and I don’t want to pass it on to other people who have never had it before. This is because I don’t know how poorly they might get from never having it and I would hate to be the reason of this. Also, although restrictions are lifted and isolation rules are no more, I feel that I would still isolate if I caught covid again. Isolation for me was very difficult and made me miserable.
text_short_wave3: Wish coronavirus would leave us all alone now. Fed up of it.
life_event_descr_wave3: A new relationship.

text_long_wave1: I feel very anxious about the whole situation. people are being selfish by going out to socialise and aren't looking out for themselves or others. it makes me worried how long we will be in this lockdown situation. I am classed as a key worker so am still having to go to work - nursery based. this makes me really nervous when around the children as who knows who may be a carrier of the virus. my partner and I are self isolating together and I am, at times, dropping essentials off to my parents and grandparents who are both considered as high risk.
text_short_wave1: selfish people still going out need to SERIOUSLY think about their actions!
text_long_wave2: the corona situation currently makes me feel really sad. So many lives lost! If the government had made harder and harsher decisions i feel that the country would be in a better place for sure. I am glad that most people will have had their vaccines now, and although i am a key worker and have worked throughout the WHOLE of the pandemic as a early years practitioner, I have no eligibility for the vaccine until my age group has priority (i'm 26). That is a huge kick in the teeth not only for me, but those who work in my sector.
text_short_wave2: Corona is hopefully on it's way out - better day's are coming
text_long_wave3: I feel the covid situation is levelling out now, and I’m pleased about it. Less of an impact on my life and my daily experiences. Most people I know have now had covid and whilst they have been unwell and I was very well, I’m glad I had it rather than my booster jabs. I had my 2 initial Jabs but chose not to have boosters. I am refusing to pay for lateral flow tests so if I am unwell there is a chance it could be covid but life moves on and we have to get on with things. I feel that covid will settle down to be another thing like the flu and I’ve never been eligible for the flu jab so I won’t be taking any notice of covid moving forward
text_short_wave3: Corona is a situation that is levelling out and needs to be another potential illness rather than a way of life
life_event_descr: Moving home, spending time with my family made me realise I was ready to move back home

text_long_wave1: I feel the country would be better off if everyone stops being selfish and stays indoors. In addition to this police should patrol public spaces greater due to many still gathering at parks regardless of the laws enforced. Coronavirus is greatly affecting everyone especially those like me who live with a grandparent so have to be more careful when leaving the house in order to not bring it home due to old people being at a much higher risk of developing worse symptoms resulting in hospitalisation which puts a much greater strain upon the NHS.
text_short_wave1: Everyone needs to stay indoors in order to keep everyone in the UK at a lower risk of catching coronavirus, if this is the case then everywhere will be able to be more lenient with social distancing measures. STOP BEING SELFISH STAY AT HOME SO EVERYONE WILL BE ABLE TO GO OUT SOON
text_long_wave2: At the moment I feel less anxious about the pandemic due to the vaccine being rolled out and the number of deaths per day decreasing significantly. The advances in the vaccines and lateral flow tests have led me to feel less stressed and safer to go out for exercise and for essential journeys to do the weekly shop. In addition, the fact more individuals are choosing to wear masks fills me with a higher level of confidence and makes me feel much safer than before when many people were choosing not to wear them even if they did not suffer from any health issues preventing them from wearing any form of facial covering whether that be a mask and/or a shield.
text_short_wave2: With the vaccine rate increasing on a daily basis it makes me look forward to my 21st Birthday knowing there is a possibility I could at least go out for dinner with my partner and some level of the new normal!
text_long_wave3: At the moment I am very happy in relation to the Corona situation due to less people dying as a result of increased vaccinations. I am also happy as I no longer have to wear a face covering when using public transport and in public places unless I so wish too. I believe being allowed to have freedom again is extremely helpful towards mental health and so I am much happier at the prospect of no more lockdowns. I enjoy that I am able to go to university and have on campus teaching as opposed to at the height of the pandemic when this was not a possibility and all teaching was reserved online. I feel as a country we are learning to live with Corona and understand that yes people can still take precautions but that it is something that will continue and eventually die out.
text_short_wave3: Extremely grateful to be able to meet up with friends in public spaces without face coverings and get to see people I haven't seen in years as a result of the pandemic!
life_event_descr_wave3: I met my partner online during the pandemic which made it extremely difficult to see each other when being in a lockdown and living over 2.5 hours away from each other.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: Completed my undergraduate degree online and started a post-graduate online as a result of the pandemic.

text_long_wave1:
The Coronavirus situation hasn't adversely affected my immediate family's financial situation because myself and my husband are public sector workers. If anything we're better off because we're working from home (i.e. saving money on transport) and not paying nursery/childcare fees.

Nobody I know has been seriously ill with the disease although I am concerned for my husband and mother-in-law who have underlying health issues. I am less worried than I was however because they are social distancing, and the people I know who've had it have gotten over it fairly easily. 

We were due to go on holiday to California at the weekend and this has obviously been cancelled, which is frustrating. We don't know when we'll get another chance to go away. We should be getting full refunds for everything though (apart from the money spent on holiday clothes, etc). 

I am worried for the frontline NHS staff and for other key workers, and concerned about the economic situation. 

It is difficult being stuck inside the house with a baby and a 3-year old but as our circumstances are better than others' I don't feel I can complain.
text_short_wave1: I am concerned for our NHS frontline staff and for our economy, I'm grateful that I'm not personally affected. I'm worried for family with underlying health issues. I hope it's all over soon.
text_long_wave2: I’m sad about how many people have died and the livelihoods lost. I’m angry at the governments mishandling and hypocrisy. I’m bored of lockdown. I miss my friends and family. I’m keen for things to get back to normal. My young children have missed out on so much. I want a holiday. I want to be able to do things. I’m relieved that nobody I’m close to died. I’m grateful my in-laws have the vaccine. I’m gutted two places I liked going to have closed down. I’m looking forward to summer and the roadmap.
text_short_wave2: I’m sad about all the lives and livelihoods that have been lost but I’m looking forward to coming out of lockdown and us being able to move on and get back to normal.
text_long_wave3:
My anxiety around Covid at the moment is mainly due to the fact that we’re flying to the USA next week and I’m worried that my 2-year old will pick up Covid and we’ll have to cancel everything. I had Covid myself a couple of weeks ago so I’m not worried about picking it up. Everyone is catching it but nobody is getting seriously ill. I’m actually a bit more hopeful about vaccination and herd immunity. 
I’m looking forward to things getting back to normal, and moving on from the past two years. We’re moving to hybrid working at work which will be beneficial for me.
text_short_wave3: I’m worried my daughter is going to catch Covid before we go on holiday next week and we’ll have to cancel everything!
life_event_descr_wave3: I have two very young children and it was very difficult being locked down with them. My husband really struggled with his mental health.
life_event_descr: Seeing so many deaths and battling depression

I’m also really anxious for my friend and her family as her mother has contracted the virus and is currently in hospital recieving treatment, we are all hopeful she is going to pull through

I don't want my son who is 2 and a half years old to grow up scared or think that face masks are the norm, i want him to have a normal childhood like i did.
text_short_wave3: Fed up of hearing about corona now, life must go on!

I am a bit lonely and a bit frustrated at not being able to see anyone but mostly I am sad I guess and anxious. It is my son's 8th Birthday tomorrow and he can't have a party and most of his presents haven't turned up yet.
Went out today for an emergency shop of what we could find to tide him over - just hope he has a good day.
Tired though, just blown up 75 balloons!!
So all in all a real mixture of feelings, I hope he has a good day and I hope everyone gets better soon. It must be hard for all the people on the front line or are suffering financially

Having said that I know some people are wary and even scared, especially those with some serious conditions. I also feel that those serving within the national health servbice must be very worried which must be recognised as a serious concern
text_short_wave3: I am concerned but comfortable

I do feel very fortunate though as I have a lovely garden to get some fresh air in an outside space and I'm making good use of online contact which punctuates the days and weeks with some valuable communication. I'm fairly productive at home and getting a range of tasks done, so feeling a reasonable sense of purpose and enjoying a short walk in my local area most days.
text_short_wave1: Short term pain for longer term gain.

I still worry about how the government is treating the situation though and whether they are doing the correct thing or not. Overall, I'm happier than I was this time last year and I feel that the situation is only going to improve, but only if we all do our part to stay safe.

I have risk because I have to go to the supermarket, I have to shop for my parents. It's stressful. Im thankful for bonus time with my children though. So much of our lives is rushed  and we live it tired, but we finally have a chance to rest and enjoy quality time together in a way that feels almost unique, with work limited and more free time than I can ever remember having.
text_short_wave1: I'm so thankful for this special time with my family, even if we cant go out much, but I also fear for them, my parents and myself. This is the most unique and odd time that I can ever remember.
text_long_wave2: I feel that there is hope for the future now, but I have an underlying condition and still haven’t been vaccinated, so I still have some anxiety at catching COVID. text_short_wave2: I’m pleased that infections as deaths are falling and that a reopening of the country might be reasonably imminent, but I’m still unvaccinated and am anxious as I have a chronic condition that could be made much worse by COVID. Life is hard enough as it is.
text_long_wave3: I think that our national decision to basically decide to ignore the fact that the pandemic is still happening is absurd and impacts hugely on the lives of vulnerable people. The fact that we have such a noisy anti-vax campaign is also a national embarrassment.
