text_long_wave1: I'm viewing the process of social distancing and shutdown as a chance for elements of society and the workplace to develop and reset, particularly in terms of inclusivity and working norms. I am not in any risk groups and I honestly feel quite relaxed about the whole thing. I am normally a mildly-moderately anxious person but I have not felt this calm for so long in years. I recognise that what is happening is significant and that I am in an extremely lucky position (able to work from home, not vulnerable, et cetera), and I do feel for those on the front lines or who lose loved ones. But ultimately I am really quite calm and relaxed. I am a little more apprehensive about the situation when things get back to normal but again, demographically I am unlikely to suffer substantial distress.
text_short_wave1: Without wishing to be smug, feeling very calm and relaxed right now. The peacefulness of social distancing and working from home is great, and I want to help others in some ways if I can.
text_long_wave2:
I have no real concerns about catching Corona - I am, however, in need of some different space in which to live and work and am feeling ground down by the lockdown. Recognising that I am lucky to be working and have somewhere to live, but both my wife and I have become a little short-tempered recently and I think it is due to living and working at home in stressful jobs without any route for socialisation or catharsis. Zoom fatigue is also a prominent aspect of my life!

I am trepidatious because people seem to want to """"""""go back to how it was"""""""" but this was not without its problems and however trying the last year has been, there are positive lessons to learn about work, connectivity and community, and I hope these are taken forward.

I have a small level of anxiety about the Corona vaccination because I am extremely scared of needles, but I will not hesitate to get the jab when the opportunity arises.
text_short_wave2: I used to love the sofa, but I am so over Corona #bored #wfh
text_long_wave3:
At the time of writing I am quite relaxed about corona - I am more worried about inconvenience and indirect effects (for example, I had a cold last week and tested several times + was concerned about how much I would be inconvenienced if I had to remain at home - as it turned out, 3 x LFTs came up negative so I felt able to go about my work as usual). 

I am triple-vaxxed and had a rough reaction to the first vaccination. This has made me more comfortable because I feel like, being vaccinated, any corona experience I have will be much less bad than otherwise. 

I am ambivalent about the relaxing of restrictions. I agree in many respects but I do think good infection control practice (e.g. wearing masks) should remain in place until either more effective medicines are developed, or until the virus is categorically endemic rather than pandemic.
text_short_wave3: I hope we are coming out of corona - I am a little bored of it if I am honest. I want to learn more about research into medicine and vaccines because it isn't going away, and we don't know how annoying another variant could be

text_long_wave1:
I feel sad with regards to some news (colleague's death, mental health issues of peers and others); but I also feel very lucky as I can work from home - and not everyone has this opportunity. At the same time I feel a little tired of feeling lucky this way...
I also had some good news with respect to my job, so I feel a little guilty relatively to the others. I also feel powerless to help, as I do not have any relevant skills & thus I'm not useful right now. This is a silly feeling, as it doesn't help anyone; at the same time it's not actually strong enough to prompt me to do more than just a few donations and gift vouchers. 
I also feel rather sad about my friends, who are in a worse position. I feel entirely blessed with my partner - but again, I'm lucky & not everyone is. 
So, overall, it's a mix of feeling sad & damn lucky - and sad that one needs to feel lucky that way.

I am worried thinking about my uncle, who has very serious MS and would be at huge risk of dying if he contracted the virus. text_long_wave1: Right now I mostly feel pretty tired/lethargic, alongside a generally more relaxed mood. It's been a strange day - I've mostly been calm, have had some spells of happiness yet have also had a period of feeling sad about the current situation. I'm missing being able to go on really long walks, feel free to head into the city, and generally to be able to live more normally. That said, I'd far rather this than fall ill or contribute to anyone else's illness. I've found myself reading lots of news articles/listening to radio shows and podcasts through the days to make sure I'm staying on top of the latest happenings. The coronavirus really scares me; especially as an asthmatic. Yet I've not felt anxious today. Generally, I'm mostly fine by day. The anxiety can creep out in the night or my dreams though (yet not every night) and I'm still sleeping okay on the most part.
text_short_wave1: This is the most surreal experience that most of us have lived through and I long for a time when we can all look back on the situation and know we've made it through/learn from its many lessons. I'm sad (and scared) that for many of us this won't be the case.
text_long_wave2: I largely feel more hopeful about the corona situation. The statistics look promising – it appears as if the vaccine programme is working well and the UK numbers have rapidly fallen over the lockdown period. I've been fortunate to have already received my first jab (far earlier than I expected for my age and the level of my asthma). I'm still being super cautious and have been living like I'm in lockdown for pretty much a year and feel lucky to be able to continue doing so until after my second dose. I'd still be afraid of contracting the virus right now, do worry about whether there's going to be another big variant bombshell in time, and also for others re jobs etc.
text_short_wave2: I'm hopeful we're seeing easier times ahead for everyone...and there aren't any nasty virus surprises in store!
text_long_wave3: I'm feeling a bit unsure about everything. It seems I keep hearing of friends of friends and family members who are falling sick with covid. Most don't seem to feel too bad and others feel quite rotten, but there's nobody who seems to be reacting terribly in our circle. That said, as someone clinically vulnerable, and with a very reactive immune system, I still worry about how my body will respond if it falls sick. Even if that's a case of battling some long covid symptoms, which sound awful. We're due to have some works start on our house next week and I'm nervous about having the workmen here, particularly as they're no longer doing routine testing but just testing if they have symptoms. I wish the government would keep more routine testing going and could have staged the lifting of the restrictions more gradually. Though I appreciate many people may disagree with this.
text_short_wave3: I understand restrictions must be lifted, I just wish they could've been staged more gradually (with free testing available throughout)! Plus how can we trust people to choose to isolate when needed, when so many didn't when legally obliged?!

text_short_wave1: Frustrated and worried about coronavirus but grateful to be at home safe withy children.
text_long_wave2: I am less worried about the corona situation at the moment than I was previously. Rates of infection are dropping across the country and there is a detailed road map out of lockdown. I am looking forward to the days getting warmer and brighter and being able to meet up outside with my family. I work in a school with children who are medically vulnerable and are not yet eligible for the vaccine so I do feel worried that one of them might catch the virus and be very poorly with it.

I am still testing regularly but only because I am worrying about passing it on to the vulnerable people I work with. I am still mixing with colleagues and family who are close contacts where as last year I would not have gone near them.

text_long_wave1:
I’m feeling fairly relaxed about it all. I’m not worried about potentially getting ill, but I am very annoyed about the UK government response. They have been so ineffective in their implementation of a lockdown, they have failed the NHS by not providing adequate PPE and also failed all of us by pursuing a path which does not require testing of suspected cases. You cannot track a pandemic if you don’t test everyone.
They have lied about ventilators, claiming that a company was making them specially despite the fact that companies which already made them were not ordered from.  They claimed not to get the memo from the EU regarding bulk buying of ventilators. I really hope that once this is all over, this sham government are held to account by everyone, including the media who just seemed to nod and agree with everything coming from Downing Street.

I’m sick of being locked down for a virus that has a high survival rate for the vast majority of the population. 
I feel worried that I will be forced to take a vaccine that is as yet unproven to be effective at preventing the spread of corona virus or stopping someone from getting coronavirus. I’m also worried about how there is talk about making it difficult for those who chose not to take the vaccine to resume a normal life-it is unethical in my opinion to take away individual choice from a person to do as they wish with their own body.
I feel conflicted about it all because it is undoubtedly a tragedy for those who have lost loved ones but on the other hand, we are being asked to modify our lives for something that the majority of people will survive.

I appreciate that case numbers are still high but it no longer poses the same threat to the vast majority of people so it’s time for those of us who want to get on with things to be able to do so, whilst allowing those who are vulnerable or still have anxiety about the situation to also be able to do what they need to do to goon with daily life.

I also feel extremely proud of all the key workers, this situation really has brought out the best in some people. On the other hand, a minority of people aren’t staying inside as they should be, and are flouting the rules to enjoy some warm weather. These people make me extremely angry, as there are NHS workers putting their lives on the line every single day, while some people can’t seem to deal with not sunbathing for a few weeks.

On the one hand I feel fortunate that I have not been affected financially in a negative way, I do not need to leave the house unless I want to, have a garden where I can get fresh air, sunshine and exercise, have enough food for a few weeks, and am finding plenty of things to do to keep occupied.  I am also in frequent contact with a good number of people by phone/email/text.

As a range of things I usually do regularly(such as choir, art class, etc) and future plans (such as holiday and visit to family) were cancelled I have felt disappointment, but overall accept this.

I am feeling worried on behalf of other people whose health is more vulnerable than mine, a sense of uncertainty about how long this situation will persist and concern for people I know who are 'key workers'.

text_long_wave2: This evening I received a tip off from a friend that people over 56 can now book a vaccination online, so I did that immediately and now have appointments for the 1st and 2nd vaccination booked.  Hence I am feeling personally very happy, but nevertheless appreciate that we are still in a serious situation with 'normality' a long way off.  As I am retired (early) and live alone, I don't have the worry of mixing at work (as a former teacher I am glad not to be facing the stress that the return on Monday may pose for my old colleagues) and have been able to limit contact with others.
text_short_wave2: Nearly a year in, there is light at the end of the tunnel.  We have the hope from vaccination, but we still need to keep up our efforts to keep each other safe.  I am grateful for the way we have supported each other over the past year and we will go forward stronger, together.

text_long_wave3: In many respects my life has returned to 'normal' in that the leisure pursuits in which I was involved have restarted, such as choirs and art class.  I am aware, however, that the case rate is rising and I seem to know an increasing number of people of a similar age to me (late 50s/early 60s) and likewise triple vaccinated with whom I have recently socialised  who have recently tested positive.  So, it is in the back of my mind that although I have been free from Covid throughout the past two years, I might still become infected.  I am still wary about travelling abroad, even though restrictions have been relaxed.  I was due to go to Germany in 2020, including to the Oberammergau Passion play; this was postponed to 2022 but a month or two ago, I decided to cancel this holiday.  I found it difficult to work up any enthusiasm for the travel/being at an event which would be attended by thousands and decided that I really didn't care about losing the deposit.  This contrasts with how I felt when I booked the holiday back in 2018 as my retirement present to myself, when I really relished the prospect of going.  Instead, I have booked a self-catering holiday in the UK for the Autumn.  Until the beginning of 2022, I had for many months been plotting my own graph each day of the local  case rate but got bored with doing this.  To be honest, anything in the news about Covid at the moment is rather overshadowed by concern about the war in Ukraine.

My mum is a front-line worker and so I am perpetually anxious about her and my family contracting the virus. I'm extremely worried about my chances of survival if I contract it as I am chronically ill. I'm also deathly worried for my parents, who aren't really in the most at-risk age group but are still 'older' and my father has a history of strokes. It kind of feels like an inevitability that we will contract it and feeling like someone (or possible multiple of people in my family) could die feels like a mind-numbing reality. I feel like I'm sitting around waiting to die all the time. 

In general the situation feels bleak. I feel like I have the most sympathy and concern for still-developing countries and refugees who are either displaced or people from war-torn countries. What hope do they have. The knock-on effects from this on a global scale will be so painful.

I am doing what I can to help, including volunteering, and trying to focus on work, though I feel frequently distracted, unable to focus, despairing, and though I can't concentrate a troubling amount of the time. I feel sorry for the country and world in the long-term as well as the current time. We need each other and connecting only online or by phone feels exhausting and draining too much of the time. I am grateful and feel lucky to have beautiful countryside around me and the ability to walk and run in it. It is one of the few calming presences in my days. I know there are many facing far more awful situations and feel guilty for struggling so much.

text_long_wave3:
I'm still amazed and enraged by the UK's Covid-19 death toll.  We're an island nation with complete control over our borders like New Zealand, Taiwan and Australia, but our government chose to allow anyone and everyone to fly in and out of the UK for months after it was obvious there was a virus that was deadly for some people.  Most of those 150,000 deaths were preventable, but not considered important by our government.
Our government is now pretending the pandemic is over.  I went into the Foodbank where I volunteer today to be told another voluneer's husband had died.  They'd both been vaccinated and boosted,, they caught C19 at the same time, she recovered, he was hospitalized for three days and died.  
It's not over, and there will be thousands who die like him because our government now thinks the NHS won't be swamped by cases and therefore life can go back to normal.  
It can for those who are fit and healthy, but 40% of our population isn't.  The NHS won't recover either, so thousands and thousands of perfectly preventable deaths will happen because there simply aren't enough staff with enough time to deal with all of the people who need healthcare.  
I loathe what we've become - an 'I'm alright Jack' society led by someone who's not fit to hold the door open for doctors, nurses, delivery drivers, physiotherapists, shop assistants and all the other key workers who kept the country going even when PPE wasn't available to protect them, before vaccines were available.
We can clap for key workers but we won't pay them what they're due because that would actually cost us something.  Clapping's free, and people that stood on their doorsteps and clapped thought they were good people - it smacked of hypocrisy then and it absolutely stinks now.  
I'm ashamed of us.

My partner has coronavirus for the second time.  I have not contracted coronavirus yet even though live with her.  Her symptoms are minimal this time and I believe this is due to her immune system developing resistance.  The first time she had the virus she lost her smell and taste, this hasn't happened this time.  I am worried that as I haven't had the virus I'll be more susceptible in the future, especially if there are stronger variants of the virus.  

I believe the vaccine's she has had have helped but I'm a worried about my boy, who is 10, having the vaccine.  When my partner had the virus the first time around, the advice from nhs24 was that children tend to brush the virus off.  Now the advice is that children should have the vaccine as they're susceptible. text_long_wave1: It is a concern to me but I feel like our family is doing its best to keep itself safe, and the virus has not yet directly affected anyone particularly close to me, nor is it particularly widespread (or at least known to be) in my area. It seems like in several countries that a corner has been turned, and although we are a little behind in the UK, it is encouraging to see a light at the end of the tunnel. However, we are all feeling fairly stir-crazy having been stuck in our house for so long, especially as we are used to being very active and going out and about.
text_short_wave1: Staying at home and keeping our chin up. Take care everyone, we can get through this!
text_long_wave2: I have been really heartened by the vaccine roll-out and the fall in cases nationwide. It definitely feels like there's light at the end of the tunnel. I just hope that things still go in the right direction as we start to open up society again, particularly with schools opening next week; I definitely don't want another lockdown. I'm starting to plan meet-ups with my family again, which I haven't been even contemplating for a very long time. I feel fortunate to have not been overly affected personally by the pandemic.
text_short_wave2: Feeling hopeful that the worst is behind us and that the vaccine will help us get back to normal in time for summer.
text_long_wave3: It feels like other world events have displaced Covid in the news agenda, even though it's currently pretty widespread still. The vaccines have made a lot of difference to people's feelings about it, as well as of course their experience of having it. It does feel like it's just something that we're going to have to end up living with in future, and that vaccinations will continue on a regular basis, but perhaps only for (or prioritising) the elderly or the clinically vulnerable, as we do with flu vaccination programs.
text_short_wave3: Covid might be here to stay - but that doesn't mean we should give up on the hygienic and social practices that we developed to keep each other safe during the last two years.
life_event_descr_wave3: The opportunity to work from home more has allowed me to spend so much more time with my wife and two young children, as I work a long way away from my office base.

text_long_wave1:
Regarding the Coronavirus situation, I am feeling moderately anxious which seems to increase with the continued lockdown in the United Kingdom.

I feel that my anxiety is related to the impact the virus will have on society in general, the economy, my income and the health and livelihood of people around me, and in particular people who are more vulnerable.

I think that governments are starting to act more tactfully in combatting the virus and its wider effect on society and to communicate clearer messages and information to the public. However I strongly believe that the UK government did not respond efficiently to the virus' initial breakout.

At the same time I am feeling optimistic that the situation will improve relatively soon and that life should start to return to normal quicker than expected.

I was also recently vaccinated so I am less anxious about catching the virus. I still miss socialising with friends and going on holiday (and even being in the office, sometimes!) but hope these activities might resume relatively soon.

text_long_wave1:
I feel anxiety and a sense of helplessness and dread. It’s difficult waiting for something awful to happen and not knowing when it will hit. I also feel cut off from others, despite the use of social media to keep in touch. It’s just not the same, and I am worried about security of Zoom etc. 
Still working, I feel fear of being in the office, perhaps with people who have the virus. I resent those who can work safely from home full time and choose to go out more than necessary. I feel huge gratitude to others keeping key services functioning but I find the restrictions on shopping difficult-one way systems in supermarkets are strange and feel awkward, and the shortage of some basics is infuriating.
text_short_wave1: There’s a sense of impending doom, and helplessness as you can’t stop it happening but you don’t know when it’s going to hit and how long it’ll last. You hope others are doing their bit, but it’s hard to know, and it seems there is room for interpretation re what’s ‘essential’.

Concerned about friends and family members. Desperate to be able to meet up with people and socialise again.

text_long_wave1:
I am slightly anxious and worried for family and friends who are older or suffering from pre-existing conditions which increase the mortality chances from COVID-19; self-employed close family worrying about the financial aspects around this; friends who have lost their jobs; and family and friends working in the NHS.

I am fortunate enough to live with a friend of the same age (30), with no children, and able to work from home with a rather low risk of negative impact to employment status. So in that respect the main sense of anxiousness is in regard to others, yet also the social distancing and lack of face-to-face contact with friends and family causes a sort of sense of disassociation from normal reality (rather than loneliness or isolation per se).
text_short_wave1: The scenes of people queuing metres apart in silence, stealing awkward glances shows a sense of disconcerting departure from our normal reality, and a realisation that everything we take as part of normal life is much more fragile than we could have imagined.
text_long_wave2: I feel some optimism given the speed of the vaccine rollout in my country. However, as there are variants of the virus there I am slightly anxious that if the rest of the world is not vaccinated to a significant degree then this all might go on for much longer. There is a plan for reducing restrictions in my country so there is something to look forward to with regards to visiting family and friends once again, so I remain hopeful and optimistic that there is an end in sight. I also feel some anger towards our government who have used the crisis to line the pockets of their friends whilst presiding over one of the worst death rates in the world, and one of the hardest-hit economies.
text_short_wave2: Let's all get vaccinated so there is some optimism, and let's bring the government to account for all their failings over this crisis.
text_long_wave3: I feel like we're in a better / manageable place now we have a vaccine rolled out. The large numbers of cases are still concerning given that a new variant that could be more vaccine-resistant is possible. Hospital cases are at least at a more manageable level at the moment so that is a positive. I am slightly concerned that the vaccine efficiency will """"""""wear off"""""""" for older people who had the last dose of the vaccine earliest. In general however I am pretty much back to normal with regards to social life, and still working from home the majority of the time (which is my preference).
text_short_wave3: Let's hope the removal of all restrictions won't lead to another very unpleasant variant.

Currently I have an array of emotion. I’m also fearful we will end up losing our jobs and with the country on its knees economically I can’t see getting another job as an easy task.

I am sad as I miss my two young nieces immensely, we would look after them fortnightly whilst my sister worked and I miss them so much. At that age they change so quickly.

I am content that currently we have a nice house for me and my partner and my son to shelter in and that we have each other with no health issues yet but I feel guilt for feeling this when I do because of all the pain others are experiencing. I feel useless that I should be doing more to make a difference when it comes to my grandchildren one day asking me what I did I’ll only be able to answer stay inside. 

I feel fearful that we may catch the virus I get extreme anxiety food shopping it reminds me of an apocalypse. 

I have hope when I see people coming together and helping to best this disease from nurses to food delivery drivers and I am immensely proud of my country. As you can see a whole rainbow of emotions.

text_long_wave2: I feel sad about everything we’ve missed out on over the last year but hopeful that things will get better soon and that we will be able to see our friends, family and loved ones again. I also feel sad for those that have lost loved ones during this pandemic. I feel angry at the way the government has handled the situation and how it is now treating NHS staff so badly. I am worried about the new strains of Coronavirus being introduced (e.g. the Brazillian strain) and the vaccines not working against them.
text_short_wave2: NHS staff who have been working throughout this pandemic deserve more than a 1% pay rise!
text_long_wave3: I feel a little anxious about the Corona situation at the moment, especially concerning older family members, if they were to catch it and feel unwell. I’m not sure how it would affect them, especially any vulnerable family members. I also worry it will ruin future plans we have for the upcoming year as we have missed out on so much already. I am currently isolating with Covid at the moment and although I feel unwell the symptoms are not too bad so I feel lucky in that respect. I feel people should still wear masks out in public to protect each other and Covid seems very prevalent at the moment.
text_short_wave3: More people need to wear masks to protect themselves and each other.
life_event_descr: Finishing uni

text_long_wave1:
I feel scared and feel physically sick when I think about the situation a lot. I have friends who are nurses and care workers or other key workers and the general public has no real idea of what is going on. The extent to which this is causing problems for our NHS. I feel sad for my relatives who have health conditions and those that have lost their jobs. It's a scary time.
I am worried about the future of the economy once this is over. It's something that has never happened before so that creates huge anxiety.
text_short_wave1: We're living in strange and scary times. Please stay at home, protect the NHS and save lives.
text_long_wave2:
I feel as though people are becoming complacent too early. I understand the excitement but I'm a little worried. I am really looking forward to normality...a safe normality. The pandemic has brought some positives but it has also bought lots of negatives and difficult situations for some. I'm hopeful. 
I'm very much looking forward to seeing my mother sisters and brothers again. I'm looking forward to my son seeing family and friends as he is only small so has missed out on so much interaction. I look forward to going into the office at some point and doing normal things. Like going to bars restaurants and cinemas. That will be great when we can do those things. Even going swimming or on holiday will be great too.
text_short_wave2: There is hope. We will be able to get back out into the world safely soon and do those things we took for granted.
text_long_wave3:
As my family and I have all now had Covid and are fully vaccinated I feel less worried about Covid. I feel things are gradually getting back to normal and I see a positive future. 
We are going back to work in the office and are planning our first holiday abroad in 2 years. Things are definitely relaxing and as long as we are still wearing our masks and washing our hands as often as possible. My son is only young so the pandemic lifestyle is all he's known for so long. I look forward to him bring able to experience some different things like flying on a plane and going to a different country to experience their culture.
text_short_wave3: I feel positive that things are finally getting back to some kind of new normal after the last 2 crazy years of Covid.
life_event_descr: I was diagnosed with depression.

text_long_wave1:
I'm self-employed, in the Arts & Entertainment industry, so all of my upcoming work has been cancelled, which obviously adds to the difficulty in the current circumstances. My concerns about money and survival contribute to my overall mood.
As far as the virus itself, I'm hopeful. I believe I may have had it and recovered, and I believe what is currently being done is having an impact. I'm also interested to see that the situation is prompting some countries to try new ideas, such as Universal Basic Income. I'm worried that some vulnerable members of my family may fall ill.
text_short_wave1: Be responsible, think of others and help where you can. Keep busy, stay safe and try to find a way to use this time in the most productive manner possible. Come back stronger.
text_long_wave2: I’m kind of tired. I run my own business, and although we’ve been fortunate and survived without too much damage, the constant need to adapt and change our operations from day to day has been very wearing. I’ve also lost a family member to COVID, so that’s sad, and frustrating because it need not have happened. I’m looking forward to getting out, travelling, seeing people I haven’t seen for a long while, getting back to my work as it should be. Overall I’m hopeful that things are starting to get better now, but I also hope that doesn’t mean the mistakes, hypocrisy and mismanagement get forgotten.
text_short_wave2: As we begin to return to some semblance of normal life, how long before our ‘heroes’ are forgotten again while our ‘leaders’ pat themselves on the back and give themselves a bonus? With a lot of luck, perhaps this pandemic might make us look, and change.
text_long_wave3: I’m optimistic that we are beginning to live with Covid in a manageable way. I still worry a little that we will see another outbreak of a more severe variant. I am very sad, frustrated and angry about the attack on Ukraine, but also deeply disgusted and angry that politicians here in the UK have used it to sweep their disregard for lockdown rules and contempt for the general public under the carpet. I feel a little tired when I think about the work I’ll have to do to get my business back to pre-Covid levels.
text_short_wave3: Yes, the pandemic was hard, but at least the richest got staggeringly richer and had some great parties while my stepfather died alone in hospital.
life_event_descr_wave3: The unexpected death of my stepfather.
life_event_descr: dd

text_long_wave1: The Corona situation is worrying me and causing me to be anxious. I am worried about my family who are mostly keyworkers and therefore have to be out and about on the frontlines And thankful that I am able to work from home during this situation and know that my young daughter is safe in the house and we have everything we need right now. In regards to shopping and utilities and general home stuff. I don't have to worry too much about myself but I worry about others. I am anxious over how long this situation will last in the UK and what the follow on effect will be for the world as we know it
text_short_wave1: Scared and anxious! Anyone else feeling this way and want to talk? Share some loads? Help eachother out?
text_long_wave2:
I'm tired and fed up of the situation now. I have tried to follow the lockdown and social distancing measures throughout the pandemic but regularly see people flaunting that they aren't following the precautions and it makes me sad for my daughter. She gets confused on why she is told not to do something, only to see grown ups doing that exact thing. Homeschooling has been hard alongside working from home, and I'm scared that the schools may close again even though they've only just opened up again after so long.
I have had the first covid vaccine and can not wait for the second and for others to have had it too. My mother is also coming to the end of cancer treatment that we only found out about at the end of 2020
text_short_wave2: Tired and fed up. Can everyone please just follow the guidelines
text_long_wave3: I am quite fed up of the Coronavirus situation at the moment. It feels like it has dragged on too long and nobody really knows what the next steps are. I don't know whether I am supposed to wears masks or not anymore. Am I supposed to isolate or not? What do I do if I get symptoms, or my partner or daughter? There is too much uncertainty and not enough answers to the mass of questions I and many other people I'm sure have. I am also tired of them trying to continue using Covid to stop people finding out and learning about other situations in the news at the moment. It seems like a bit of a scapegoat
text_short_wave3: Arghh fed up! To wear or not to wear (a mask)?
life_event_descr: new relationship

text_long_wave1: I feel scared for the future of the world, and I feel sad that so many people have been lost. But I'm mostly angry that people keep refusing to follow the rules put in place to protect them. The situation wouldnt be so bad if people on the whole weren't so stupid and took the time to think about anyone other than themself for 5 minutes. All the selfish young people who were still going out with their friends, without thinking that even though they might get Corona and be fine they may spread it to someone who is immunocompromised or has preexisting breathing problems and wont ever recover.
text_short_wave1: If we all weren't such mugs we'd still be allowed to go out for more than just exercise
text_long_wave2: I'm finding it difficult to.be apart from my friends from university, and my boyfriend. I miss having a social life and becoming able to do what I want when I want. I miss my old life, but part of me feels like that life is never coming back. I'm sad and angry that people, myself included, didn't take the pandemic seriously to begin with, because things are awful now,.and it feels like they won't get better. I'm sad that my degree has been half and half out of lockdown and in lockdown, and I'm worried it will decrease the validity of whatever grade I come out with in summer. If I do well, will people thing they were going easy.becaise of the situation, if I do badly will people think I'm stupid because I couldn't learn from home? I'm angry all the time about the situation and the people still.not taking it seriously. I go to work and have to deal with customers not wearing masks properly, and paying with all.the change they have instead of card, and the only thing that has eased my mind about me coming in contact with all these idiots is the fact that now all my grandparents, and parents are vaccinated so I won't pass anything bad to.them from work.
text_short_wave2: Been a whole year since life was normal, probably gonna be another whole year before things even start to go back to normal #fuming #covidiots #fuckborris
text_long_wave3: I feel that we are going back to normal too soon. I have stopped wearing a mask but I do not go anywhere that could be considered a covid risk. It feels like the government has just decided to ignore it until it goes away. But more and more people are still getting ill, and now we don't have to isolate if we test positive? Like, what even is that mentality. Its stupid and I'm angry at not only the government but the people who I know won't isolate when they know they have it and spread covid further.
text_short_wave3: Test positive but don't have to isolate? 2 years ago people were fined for seeing family when they were well, now you can go spread it as much as you want!?!
life_event_descr_wave3: Began training to teach
life_event_descr: I had a little baby girl
life_event_descr_2: Moved House

text_long_wave1:
I am worried about my family as several members of my family are vulnerable to Corona.

I am worried about catching it and passing it to them so isolating as much as possible.

Anxious about how long the situation is going to go on for. Miss my job and those i work with. Miss my freedom. Concerned about mental health with being in isolation.

Wish people would listen to the government and authorities and stay at home. Also wish people would not panic buy as there is absolutely no need when you can do your shopping once a week as normal.

Doing my best to have a routine and do a variety of things each day.
text_short_wave1: Anxious, scared, annoyed and frustrated to name a few emotions in regard to how i feel about corona. Grateful for our keyworkers. Stay safe.
text_long_wave2:
I am worried that if i catch the virus i will pass it on to my husband who is very vulnerable. I worry about catching it at a supermarket or in a shop as you don't know who has touched what. It is uncomfortable being in a public place as a lot of people don't distance or wear their mask properly. We now have our shopping delivered but we have to collect our prescriptions from the pharmacy. I don't like queuing for the above reasons and because of weather conditions.

The good thing is that we have both had our first vaccine, so that does help us feel a bit more at ease. We both had the Astra Zeneca vaccine.
text_short_wave2: Why is it so difficult to wear a mask properly and stand where the markings tell you to?
text_long_wave3:
Figures are on the rise again, so I am a bit concerned about it.

My husband is vulnerable due to being immunocompromised. I do worry sometimes that if he caught covid he would be very ill. But he is fully vaccinated and recently had a 4th vaccine.

I have so far never tested positive so I feel like it's only a matter of time until I do. This is scary.

I think covid is here to stay.  Its hard to believe we first went into lockdown 2 years ago.

We are going on holiday in July and I'm a bit concerned about covid, but we do have to move on at some point.

I am wondering if we will all get offered another booster vaccine in the future.
text_short_wave3: Scared, uncertain, time to move on?
life_event_descr_wave3: My mental health

text_long_wave1:
I feel like there’s a lot of uncertainty which is really troubling. I’m also concerned as I’ve been shielding due to an underlying health condition and this is worrying. I worry rather a lot by how long this pandemic is going to lost, the overall impact on the economy, jobs that will be lost, peoples lives that will be affected of of course and possibly more important than anything else, the lives that will be lost because of this terrible pandemic.

I feel for all the healthcare professionals doing a sterling job to keep people safe and well. I feel that they’re doing a fabulous job but it’s fire fighting at its best as I do not feel we are at the height of the pandemic just yet and the situation will get worse before it’s better.
text_short_wave1: Feeling nervous anxious and superfluous to requirements and lonely.
text_long_wave2: I feel very uneasy about the lockdown situation.  I know that it's to minimise the contagion rate and whilst I'm fearful of contracting the virus, I'm equally concerned of the impact of my mental health.  My mental health is suffering with a lack of social interaction and normalcy in seeing people and living life.  I feel like I am totally ready for restrictions to be lifted (and with precautions such as masks) but i feel as though it's time to begin to lift restrictions and allow a semblance of normalcy to resume.
text_short_wave2: Ready to resume project #livemylife #covid #coronavirus
text_long_wave3: I feel that things could have been handled better.  I lost my mum at the start of the pandemic and wasn't able to see her before she died and this upsets and angers me.  I think more of a level of pragmatism should have been applied with all the suitable precautions to allow loved ones to see terminal relatives in hospitals.  I feel calmer overall than I did with the whole corona virus situation, especially with being triple jabbed but I do not feel comfortable.  I'm in an at risk group with taking immune system suppresants and this makes me more worried than the average person.
text_short_wave3: I like that we're resuming to normalcy but I don't think we're out of the woods yet
life_event_descr_wave3: the death of my mother

text_long_wave1:
Lockdown is doable, what is difficult is the uncertainty over the future, particularly the impact on my child's education and lack of ability to socialise with other children . 

I worry about our health and that of friends and family.   I feel sad about not seeing my parents and worry how long they can cope with isolation.  

I worry about food supplies, although I have been lucky with deliveries.  

My anxiety is actually less, as there is so much less to plan and do.  But at times I worry about how long this will go on for and what sort of society will be left.  

I feel very cross when I see people not complying with the guidelines, for eg my neighbour has her family visiting every day.
text_short_wave1: Everyone needs to stay at home - then the time that we can leave our homes will be sooner!
text_long_wave2:
I am very excited and hopeful about things opening up.  I feel it is almost possible to make plans in the future.  I feel confident in allowing my child back to school although I would prefer that children did not have to wear masks in the classroom.  

I am very excited about having my vaccine and i check most days if I am eligible yet.  

However I am shocked that this has happened and feel that it was handled very badly by the Government.  I am particularly cross about money being made by friends of Ministers.  I think a lot of very bad decisions were made last year, although this year has been better.
text_short_wave2: Hopeful for the future, things will be normal again.
text_long_wave3: I am actually not particularly worried, however the cases are still relatively high and therefore  it is still a general underlying concern. I am definitely not at all as worried as I was the previous year and the year before that, and it feels like we as a country and a society have begun to move on from it in many ways, however I feel like it will stay with us for a long time as a sort of collective trauma. Hopefully it does not come back as a major issue soon.
text_short_wave3: Hopefully we're moving on from Covid!

text_long_wave1:
I’ve been very relaxed about the whole
Situation up until this week where it is starting to make me very nervous how it is developing. I am worried for the older people in my family and I am also worried that many people are still not taking this seriously. I really hope that we can still exercise as I am a keen runner and need to run for my mental wellbeing and I don’t see how it effects the spread of I am alone and away from public. I have just heard that the prime minister is in intensive care now which is another reason for the whole country to panic
text_short_wave1: This is starting to become a real worry for myself and my family now!! Covid19 has become a very very serious threat to EVERYONE!!
text_long_wave2:
I am disgusted in all the corruption undertaken by my government in the U.K. they have used the situation to make. Obey for themselves and there friends.
I feel that the vaccine is really taking affect now and figures are coming down.
I am looking forward to everything opening up again hopefully in the summer!
The British media has not helped anyone during this time with its scaremongering and the British public buy into it.
The nurses have just received a laughable 1% pay rise while the members of parliament receive 11%. This is an absolute injustice!!!
text_short_wave2: I feel that the coronavirus is slowly on its way to being under control in this country. We gambled a little on the vaccines and approving them very early compared to other countries but it seems to be having a great affect with our number of cases and deaths coming down. Hopeful
text_long_wave3:
To me corona virus is now just like having the flu. In the next month or two no one will even be testing for it due to having to pay for tests. We can go about everyday life as per normal and not worry about repercussions of not isolating etc when you have the virus anymore. 

We have learned to deal with the virus now and it’s going to be around for years on and off.

Most people are now immunised either by having it before or by having the vaccine so the fear factor is no longer where it was.
I do still feel for older generations as they still need to worry as they are likely to be affected by this much more than younger people
text_short_wave3: Corona virus is now just like a common cold for most people. We have all been vaccinated and should be able to carry on about our lives as normal
life_event_descr: We had multiple events as we lost all of our pets during these 2 years. We are still at home on most days not going out which has a negative effect on us.
life_event_descr_2: My partner was having trouble at their workplace. Overworked and underappreciated. Eventually ended up leaving that position and also left that field of work also.

text_long_wave1:
I am extremely worried.  The government seems to be trying to pin the blame for any bad outcomes on the actions of a small minority of the population rather than the delayed response to the arrival of COVID-19 into the country (no tracing of contacts etc).  My recently widowed mother lives some way from us and is over 70 and having to shield.  She needs dental work but can't get it.  My Parents-in-law are also both over 70 and ex-smokers.  There doesn't appear to be any exit strategy to our current situation.  I fear my industry (classical music) will be utterly decimated by this and will never recover thus causing emotional and financial strain.
I worry about the impact this is having on my toddler who is suddenly no longer going to nursery / playing with the neighbours' children / visiting relatives or even going in the car!  We can't explain what is happening.
I have asthma which is usually mild but has been playing up this winter so I am especially worried about the possibiity of catching COVID-19.  I worry that it is impossible to self-isolate from the rest of the family in our small flat if one of us catches it (especially as I am still breastfeeding).  I also worry that the restrictions will tighten and not allow us to take our child outside for a daily walk - we have no garden and this is vital to our mental wellbeing.
I am also worried about friends who fall into the vulnerable category but live too far across London for me to be able to easily help them shield.
text_short_wave1: COVID-19, how do I hate thee?  To the extent of my four walls and the daily exercise I am currently allowed.  Why dost thou disrupt our lives so greatly and keep us from our loved ones?
text_long_wave2: I feel that much of the past year has been wasted.  That government has lined their own pockets and those of their cronies at the expense of the poor, women and children.  Mental health is now at crisis point and they have terrified healthy people into thinking they will die.  There seems to be no cohesive idea on how to get out of this situation and no care taken of the many who have fallen in-between the cracks.  Mainly I am angry at this and bored of the small world I now live in.  I want to be able to do my job (singer) and my child to experience the world properly.
text_short_wave2: Groundhog day with no sense of of a happy ending imminent.  So angry at those who should, and could, have done more.  Those safe and solvent whilst those at the bottom of the pile struggle on.  Women and children especially have been thrown under a bus on this.
text_long_wave3:
I am ready for life to restart.  I understand that the virus has not gone away and have a CEV family member.  However, we can't lock ourselves away for ever - that is not living.  I do think there is a better middle ground to be found - i.e making good ventilation systems compulsory in new buildings and to be retrofitted to older buildings asap - especially schools.
I worry that people have lost their ability to risk assess and some seem surprised that they are catching other bugs, not just covid!
I am bored of waiting to catch it.  I worry that I will test positive and not be able to take a planned trip to visit a family member in some time.
I worry that my industry (classical music) will never fully recover and that freelancers like myself will find ourselves with ever worsening fees and conditions as the cost of living races up.
text_short_wave3: Ready to move on with care for others and myself.  Let's use the opportunity to build a new framework for work, life and society.
life_event_descr_wave3: My father died just before the first lockdown.  Being unable to grieve properly with my widowed mother and being closeted home with a 16 mth old led to depression
life_event_descr_2_wave3: I started therapy in December 2020.
life_event_descr: My parent in laws became ill and were at significantly greater risk if they contracted Corona.

text_long_wave1:
I'm not too concerned about catching corona (I'm pretty sure I have already had it). I'm more concerned about how the lock downs that several countries have imposed will affect the economy in the upcoming months. 

However I do also believe that the country and world economy will eventually bounce back from this, but I do think that it will be a while until we see a full recovery.

The human race is great adapting to surviving against the odds and this is another factor that we will adapt to.
text_short_wave1: Keep strong everyone and we will get through this together!
text_long_wave2:
I feel hopeful that the pandemic in this country will be coming to an end in a few months and we can get back some of our freedoms that we had before the pandemic.

I am still unsure as to when the rest of the world will be able to gain some normality and boarders will be fully open like they were pre-pandemic.

It could take over a year until the whole world is back to what it was pre-pandemic.

I think vaccines are good and the only viable way out of the current situation. I am not too worried about mutations as I trust that the vaccines can easily be tweaked to deal with this, similar to the flu vaccine each year.
text_short_wave2: Feeling very optimistic about Corona currently
text_long_wave3: Currently I am aware that the pandemic is still going on, however I feel the world is slowly coming round to the idea of living with Corona. This is in part due to a better awareness and the success of the vaccines. I believe that the vaccines will only improve in the future and eventually corona could be gone for good. One would hope that the Governments of the world would have had key takeaways from this current pandemic to deal with any future ones. Future pandemics will take place and hopefully we will be in a better place to deal with them.
text_short_wave3: Corona seems to be subsiding. Fingers crossed this remains the case! #Beavan
life_event_descr_wave3: I bought a flat in mid-2020
life_event_descr: New job

text_long_wave1:
I feel confused by all of the online news surrounding the situation and fearful about finances if the situation worsens.
I fear that people with or without the virus will find it difficult to get any help that they might need at this time.
I do feel thankful that I can focus on the household jobs that I don't get time to do when I am working and I have time to be creative if i feel like it. I am happy I can spend time with my partner but I do not like the feeling of being constricted to staying indoors.
text_short_wave1: Hoping this situation resolves soon and we learn from it as a society, it has definitely made me appreciate nature.
text_long_wave2: I feel it has been a very hard for those throughout this pandemic whether still working or not, I have been in retail throughout and have seen the public change, some good some really bad, I feel the long term restrictions that were put in place have done a lot of damage. I am eager to make plans for the future again. I miss social interaction and luxuries like going to the hair dresser, it has now been a year and a half since my last visit! My nephew was born at the start of the pandemic so unfortunately this lack of outside the household connection is a normality for him at the moment.
text_short_wave2: Can’t wait to be able to hug my favourite people again and spend some quality time with those I’ve not seen for so long 😢
text_long_wave3: I feel that the situation has become seen as the “new normal” I have consistently heard by word of mouth of people contracting the virus and isolating throughout the past year, people don’t seem to be as scared as they were even though the virus is just as active as a year or two ago it seems. I feel that there are long term negative effects from contracting this virus(and/or having the vaccine for said virus) that have not been addressed with the public yet. I also believe that the whole situation (I.e lockdowns,masks,social distancing) has deeply affected peoples lives and mental health and this also needs to be addressed.
text_short_wave3: It’s been a whole thing watching the corona situation play out, it’s been what? 2, nearly 3 years? I can barely remember life before it all and yet it seems like I’ve accomplished nothing and just scraped my way through in that whole time. How is everyone doing?

text_long_wave1: I am Worried more for the people who are suffering and dying as a result of the virus. I miss normal day to day life as I should be studying at university right now, however have had to leave London and come home to study online. I’m also worried for my dads business as he is self employed and the corona virus is majorly effecting his income therefore effecting our home life. It’s hard following the rules of isolation as I have not seen friends and some family in months but I know it has to be done if we want the situation to improve. However I am hopeful that everyone will get through this and I believe the world will be better once we have overcome this
text_short_wave1: If everyone can please stay inside and only leave the house for essentials, we can all see our friends and family sooner and return to normality as soon as possible. Everyone constantly going out to meet with friends are selfish and ignorant and are only thinking of them selves.
text_long_wave2: I feel like it’s starting to come to an end, I feel drained and tired of living the same day everyday. But I am well and healthy. Covid-19 just feels like a part of my life now, I’ve learnt to live with it. I do really miss my old life though, going out and having fun with friends. I think about past memories and future ones to come once this is al over. I’m grateful I never got unwell and contracted the virus and even more grateful none of my family members did. The pandemic is really effecting my motivates toon at university though, I’m struggling to keep focus and maintain my standard of work
text_short_wave2: I’m so over Covid, just want my life back lol
text_long_wave3: Although Covid cases are rising again I do not feel worried about catching it and passing it on as many people have had Covid already so may be more immune to it and many people are vaccinated. I am don’t fear falling unwell with it either. I am also not worried about the government closing the retail/education/hospitality sector as well so I feel quite relaxed about the Covid situation in terms of just living with it and am happy to go about my life as normal again. The only part that makes me feel uncomfortable is knowing that it isn’t necessary to isolate if testing positive and I feel that putting this responsibility in the publics choice is a bad idea. I think if you knowingly have Covid, you should stay home but unfortunately there will be people who choose to go out whilst infected.
text_short_wave3: I am happy life is returning back to normal after Covid but I don’t think the government should put so much trust in the public to still isolate if they test positive when it is no longer mandatory.

text_long_wave1:
Fearful of what it to come and worried about how it will affect my family. Both in regards to their health, especially my parents and how it will affect my immediate family financially, my husband has been asked to take a 20% pay cut and will will struggle. However we are in a better position than many as at the moment he keeps his job. What will happen when the crisis is over though is undefined as far as his employment is concerned.
For the first time I fully support Boris Johnson and the policies put in place by the British government, I am thankful that our leadership appears to be basing their response on scientific data and common sense which appears to be wholly not the case, particularly for countries such as the United States and more extremely Belarus. Inappropriate decisions by governments will cause more people to die.
text_short_wave1: Stay safe, stay at home, do the right thing.
text_long_wave2: I'm anxious to recieve my second vaccine as I'm in a shielding group. My children are not returning to school on March 8th, as I feel it is safer for me and them to return after the Easter break. This lockdown has been harder as the weather isn't as good and its harder to spend lots of time outside, this is especially true for my children. We are more prepared this time though and there are elements of the isolation of lockdown that are positive and I'll miss very much when live returns to pre-Covid normal, whenever that may be.
text_short_wave2: It should be optional for those children who have a shielding family member return to school on March 8th
text_long_wave3:
Having caught COVID in January, I still haven’t recovered and am now discussing the possibility of long COVID in addition to the existing chronic illness I have.

text_long_wave1: Honestly it mostly feels very surreal. I spend a lot of time at home anyway (I work from home as a freelance artist) so it doesn't feel too different from my everyday life, but I just feel like there is a big dark cloud of uncertainty and anxiety at the back of my mind at all times. (It feels shared though, like everyone else is also feeling this.) I live with my partner and we get on very well so I have felt supported in that way, but feeling ever so slightly afraid every time we leave the house and not being able to see our friends is quite difficult. I think it feels almost like a grieving process. You can be distracted from thinking about it for a certain amount of time, and when you are reminded, all the fear and confusion and frustration comes back anew. I am worried for the economy and I'm saddened for people who will lose people or suffer, and for the NHS and its workers. I'm angry at the government for stripping back the resources needed to fight it, and for being lax at every opportunity. It feels very like we are helpless. There is next to nothing we can do, besides supporting our friends and family (remotely) and reaching out to neighbours. It's very hard to get my head around the entire situation as a whole, and as such, it feels very surreal.
text_short_wave1: It's all very surreal. I feel lucky to have the resources and support I have, and terribly sad for those who are suffering, or will suffer. Being at home so much is simultaneously comfortable and terribly frightening.
text_long_wave2: While I am hopeful about the ongoing vaccination program I feel very defeated and hopeless about the pandemic globally, and frustrated by people's attitudes and selfishness. I miss my friends and family but my fear of catching or transmitting the virus is keeping me being very careful and staying at home. I feel anxious about the future of the planet, not so much for my own situation but the world in general, poverty, inequality and politics. I'm generally quite an optimistic person but lately I have been feeling very worn down.
text_short_wave2: The cycles of lockdown, rising cases, lockdown, rising cases feels like it's going to last forever... I hope the continued vaccinations will prove me wrong.
text_long_wave3: I am feeling much better than I ever have been before - that is I have significantly less anxiety about covid itself but I'm still worried for the future, particularly in regards to other people's behaviour. I'm tired and worried but happier than I have been as I feel more able to do things like see friends and go places without as much anxiety. I just wish others would be more responsible with mask wearing etc. because I think it's important everyone remains cautious in order to protect everyone and prevent further unnecessary spread of the virus. I'm still very worried about long covid in me and people I care about.

text_long_wave1:
Mostly I am continually anxious. Stuck in a weird dichotomy of trying to relax and make the most of working from home and the opportunity that extra time presents, and the angst and fear of  losing work, possible health impacts on friends and family and having to survive on even less money.
This is amplified by the constant frustration that the truth surrounding government response is clouded in obfuscation and political games. 
I am generally skeptical of consensus and as we are presented with a narrative that suggests that we may harm ourselves or others severely If we choose to question the narrative, this presents a hard pill to swallow. As such I am finding myself immersed in the horrendous story as it happens, and simultaneously horrified by my complicity in my own mental torture.
text_short_wave1: Getting tired of playing emotional Whack-A- Mole!
text_long_wave2:
I'm mostly angry about the seemingly endless corruption and mishandling of the Covid response in the UK. This is paired with a deep sense of frustration and hopelessness at the political class who seem to be able to act with impunity. There's an anger at divisions that have formed in relationships with friends who have taken a polar opposite opinion of the crisis, and a deep sense of dissapointment at how opinions and behaviour have been dangerously manipulated.
I'm also a little nervous about things returning to normal as I've grown accustomed to the routines and restrictions we currently have. As someone with anxiety, the thought of social pressures returning is giving me frayed nerves.

At this point in time I am mostly angry about corruption and mismanagement by government officials. I am furious that as a country we seem to have little or no recourse when faced with theft and corruption.
I am also very disappointed that many people I know have displayed what I consider to be selfish and carless behaviors. The divisions that Covid has caused will have repercussions for decades.
There is also a level of acceptance that things have to get back to some kind of normal and that this involves an element of risk.

My parents are both 65 so I'm aware they're slightly more at risk than I am, but they're both relatively healthy so I'm not particularly concerned.

I've been vaccinated, as have my older parents whom I live with, so I'm feeling hopeful for the future. Variants of the virus are a concern, of course, and the government's endless bungling (border control!), but I don't think a happier summer is completely unlikely. I do have phases of feeling sadder or isolated, in balance with any cheeriness, and reading the news never helps with this, yet I can't help but scroll...

I work in public health so I'm acutely aware of my local situation but this is another cause for hope; I can see things are much better than they were in January simply from the number of outbreak control teams we have to convene. The workload remains humongous though, and many of us have lived and breathed covid for over a year now. We can't burnout because who else is there to do the job, but I do feel fatigue will set in at some point.

I have been disgusted with our government’s response to Covid all along, and that hasn’t changed. On the positive side, it’s great that vaccines are having some level of success, although it worries me that they seem to be less effective against new variants.
text_short_wave3: Coronavirus hasn’t gone away.
life_event_descr_wave3: I moved house. I feel much happier here as we have a bigger garden and no longer live next to unkind people.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: I started taking anti-anxiety medication.

text_long_wave1:
I am very concerned and worried, both myself and son have asthma and is spreading fast.
People aren't taking as serious as they should be, don't want to touch anything just incase.
Shops are still struggling for basic essentials like toilet roll and 
Is all I have been thinking about since the start of March 2020, beginning to drive me insane! 
I have heard of pharmacy staff, NHS are pushed and over tired not to mention worried coming home. I don't like partner leaving for supplies, would rather do self and know have been safe/cautious!
text_short_wave1: At this very moment, I feel corona is a virus we should be taking very seriously. Its still a quite unknown virus which has adapted to all its surroundings
text_long_wave2:
At this moment I am anxious because we are exiting lockdown and when economy reopens covid will again spread to high levels of cases as has been proven to do before. There are new strain cases and no new guidelines for schools etc (my son is 5 and can still cuddle ALL his classmates). I feel there are too many of the public not adhering to the rules put in place to keep others and self safe. Schools run a major risk of transmitting virus as simply can't implement the safety needed, its nurseries and younger years having case loads. Cant expect older children and teens not to socialise closely either, its unrealistic. In my opinion there should be a lockdown style approach until everyone is vaccinated even if it takes a couple of years. Wellbeing may be affected but we are in a PANDEMIC so sacrifices for the long run need to be made. Going in and out of lockdowns with mass deaths and cases per time isn't doing any good. Problem with the UK is compliance, government don't know how to enforce as public have zero respect. 
Since the beginning and even now I was/disinfect products from shops, limit my outings to places like the shops (deliveries instead), have not seen friends and family properly in over a year, take my son to outdoor parks/public areas, my son doesn't get to play after school with anyone.. we do everything more than by the book to stay safe as son has asthma and I'm a smoker so our lungs not the best. Whats the point when half the public not even bothering and the government can't wait to reopen everywhere and end up back to square one? Thats where I'm at.
text_short_wave2:
So were about to go around the covid roundabout again. 
Everything reopens, people think everything's fine, virus spreads out of hand, government wait until last moment to call a lockdown, back to waiting on numbers dropping from home. 
Anyone else notice the pattern here, no?
text_long_wave3: I feel less anxious and fearful than I did a year ago at this time. Have barely checked the covid news over the last month or so. People I know who have had don't seem to be getting very unwell and neither did my son so have hope it's less extreme has was at the beginning. Life feels more normal, being able to socialise and go to shops with ease. I'm happier and feel a bit safer knowing that people aren't being hospitalised or dying on high levels. I choose to still follow guidelines on mask wearing/regular testing as believe that's how havnt caught yet. I'm double vaccinated which I think has helped to some degree but won't be vaccinating my 6 year old as he had covid and was fine so there's no point as is a unknown small risk could be side effects. It worries me slightly if the government decide to begin to ignore covid because things are going well at the moment. It's a virus which seems to mutate at some rate be silly to take caution away from it. All in all I'm more optimistic and relaxed than was last year about the covid situation, still cautious though.
text_short_wave3: We've made it! We walk into our new normality, a cautious but appreciated one. We remember everyone we lost along the way and they remind us life is precious. When faced with a new threat we acted, we fought and we are winning. Stay safe out there and live life to the fullest!
employment status_wave3: Due to start a new job within the next month

text_long_wave1:
Tremendous anxiety and fear, especially for others, most especially for anyone who HAS to be exposed to the possibility of infection (for whatever reason). 
I am cross about anyone who persists in not taking this virus seriously. I'm really cross about people in positions of power who are not doing their job. I should have put the 'anger' slider on 9 but I feel so distanced from them it didn't seem honest. 
I also feel fatalistic. 
Sometimes I think this pandemic has been a long time coming.
Sometimes, I wonder if the virus is a 'natural' cull to give the planet time to breathe a little.
I also feel overwhelmed if I dwell on it all for too long, or read too much about it. 
I worry for the animals.
I hope that if we come out the other side, a better life for everyone will emerge.
text_short_wave1: Not looking good. At all.
text_long_wave2:
Confused and conflicted. Overwhelmed and past caring. Anxious and resigned. Deeply angry and disgusted by the government's behaviour, greed and corruption. Full of compassion for anyone who has to cope with the consequenses of Covid. Fatalistic.
I had my first jab yesterday. In the evening I had side-effects of very strong shivers and aches. A fitful night. Today I feel fragile. Someone told me the after-effects are worse with the second jab. 
The same person said they would have the vaccination; they distrust the information given and are wary of the lack of time over testing. They are sceptical of the Covid deaths numbers. This person owns a care home. 
The vaccination centre was so well organised and everyone was kind and helpful, I was impressed. Now, I find myself wondering if it's all a stage set. 
Throughout the pandemic, my motivation has been to stay out of hospital; to not add to the workload; to help the NHS and to look after myself. I didn't clap for carers - I think they should all be paid properly. The 1% payrise announced today is so depressing, mean, corrupt, greedy. I  can't help but loathe this government and all the people in power who are self-serving. I am angry.
text_short_wave2: Don't vote Tory
text_long_wave3:
I live in a wood with my dog and hardly ever leave it except to do shopping and other necessary errands. This has been the case throughout lockdown. I didn't feel particularly different during lockdown and I still don't now as my life has been how it's always been in recent years. What has changed is the intensity of my anger and disgust at the current government - it's hard to separate the Corona situation from the Tories as they have have mismanaged, stolen, lied and taken the situation as a massive opportunity for behaving like this.
I feel relatively safe from Covid/variants but don't take it for granted. I do worry that if I were to be ill from Covid it could affect me badly due to smoking. I have had 3 jabs and thought the NHS and volunteers did an incredible job. I also fear greatly for the NHS in the hands of these criminals who want to get rid of it.
I try not to hate but I loathe this government more than ever.
text_short_wave3: Corona is a warning to us all.
life_event_descr_wave3: A divorce coupled with Corona made me appreciate, daily, how lucky I have been.

Feeling relaxed and a lot more

They did what was easy. And because of that all these people died. Some family got COVID and are still suffering from long term effects. Because Boris couldn’t do what was needed of him.

Not fearful of the disease. I’ve had some of the symptoms. Angry with government response or lack of it. Way too complacent about the threat. More concerned about their careers than helping people. Disgust at the number of people flouting the social distancing ban. Also disgusted by people abusing key workers and especially angry at the individuals who find it necessary to spit at others and inflict fear that they’ve been infected.
