text_short_wave2: Lockdown day.....who even knows anymore. Realised my Custard Cream is misspelt & actually a Cstard Cream
text_long_wave3: Corona seems to be rising again but the panic of last year has ebbed away. This is due to a general feeling that it’s just another virus that everyone will get at some point. You just have to do what you can to reduce your risks of serious illness. Although it has been reported that cases are rising again, I don’t feel overly worried or feel like I have to isolate away. I do care for elderly family but they’ve had all their jabs (as have I) so there’s less worry about serious complications if they were to get Corona now.
text_short_wave3: More covid cases = more immunity in the community

text_long_wave1: I feel anxious about my income, I had to self isolate because I was presenting symptoms and I got laid off for that and didn't even get paid sick pay. Now, I don't know what to do, the government is not helping me at all. Also, I am more anxious because I am the one that supports my mom and grandmother who are in another country. I don't know what will kill me first, corona or stress. I had many plans, and this thing is postponing all of them. I know I can overcome this, but the stage I'm at the moment is too dark. I want this to finish now.
text_short_wave1: Just like Joe Exotic said: """"""""I am never going to financially recover from this""""""""
text_long_wave2: I'm really concerned about the outcome of this. Some news says that this situation could keep going for a couple of years, and that scares the hell out of me. I certainly can't keep living like this. I think they're trying to control us more than they already did. I just want to be free. The theory I like the most and the one I hope that is true is that they're trying to force the economy to become online based. My mental health is the worse it has ever been since this happened but also it was thanks to this lockdown that I could focus on my small business and it thrived so I'm grateful for that.
text_short_wave2: I can't take this situation anymore.
text_long_wave3: I think is thing of the past... And everyone around me doesn't seem to care either. It is not affecting my life anymore, but I still use facemask everywhere though. I don't want to take another jab, I've taken 2 and they felt awful a lot worse than covid itself.  I don't hear anyone talking about it, I think war is the new covid. However, this doesn't mean I don't believe in covid because I did experience it and it was awful but society has to move on. I'm not going to lie sometimes I kind of miss it because I work online and I had more work than ever in 2020, and now the world is kind of awful because of the war, recession and work has been slow.  I don't know what else to say.
text_short_wave3: I miss lockdown but we must go on

text_long_wave1: The unknown is what makes me anxious,  I’m healthy so am not to worried if I catch it,  as I think I would recover.  The feeling of not knowing when we will come out of lockdown is daunting and the bad behaviour of the few not social distancing makes me feel that the lockdown will become stricter and longer. I started a new job and was made redundant within 3 weeks so have the worry of my future,  I worry how quickly the economy will recover.  The fear of being out of work is very concerning as I’ve never not worked and this more than anything causes me the most anxiety.
text_short_wave1: Please listen to the advice, stay indoors, stay safe
text_long_wave2: I have found this lockdown much harder than 2020, even though this time I go to work during the week, not being able to do anything in the evenings and weekends has been much harder for me and makes me feel slightly anxious and sad.    I just didn’t think it would still be happening this long.  I am very much looking forward to being able to see friends again, go shopping and get my hair done and go on holiday.  Making arrangements to go out makes me excited but I do feel a little anxious that they won’t happen.
text_short_wave2: Should have been away this weekend 😔,  instead another boring weekend with just the housework to do,  the biggest excitement is choosing which supermarket to go to! cannot wait until life becomes normal again 😀
text_long_wave3: I am relieved that as a country we are nearly back to what was normal 2 years ago.   I never want to go through the last 2 years again, and feel disbelief in how we had to live especially for the first year,  it was tough.  I am much happier now that I can go out without worrying about checking in, wearing masks and meeting more than 6 people.  I am also extremely happy that I am able to travel abroad and visit my children, and with the relaxation of testing before travel it is making it less stressful.  At Christmas it was hard to get excited until I knew my supervised LFT that had to be taken 48 hrs before was negative,  then also had the same stress on the return.  So very happy when I travel next week that I no longer have to test and complete passenger locator forms.
text_short_wave3: #covid very happy that I no longer need to test to go on holiday. #backtonormallife
life_event_descr_wave3: I lost my job in the first few weeks,  but found a new job walking distance from my home that I very much enjoy, earning the same salary, but don't have the hour and a half train journey
life_event_descr: Job change
life_event_descr_2: I had to move back home and lost my job

text_long_wave1: I am feeling upset and anxious for people who are directly affected by Coronavirus, especially those who are very ill. Personally, I do not know anyone who is ill, but my parents are both key workers so I am worried about them. However, I also feel relaxed and I now have more time to complete uni work. I am trying to see as many positives in this situation as possible. I am concerned about the effect this will all have on the economy and my personal money situation as I have been furloughed, but many people have it worse than I do.
text_short_wave1: I am worried about those who are vulnerable, and I am upset for those who have lost loved ones. Yet, I am looking at the positive factors in this situation such as the time to appreciate family and time to complete uni work.
text_long_wave2: The progress being made in the UK in terms of vaccination is very promising, with 22 million individuals having been vaccinated so far. I will be one of the last to be vaccinated, but I am looking forward to getting it. As we are getting closer to summer, I am feeling hopeful that this year will be a lot more normal than last year. Cases, hospital admissions, and deaths have fallen greatly over the last few months. I am looking forward to this lockdown ending, and being able to see and hug all of my friends and family again!
text_short_wave2: Vaccination progress is looking good! Looking forward to a good summer.
text_long_wave3: In the last few months I have been able to travel again with little restrictions. I feel safe when I am out and about, and I definitely don’t have any fear.  Life has pretty much gone back to normal for me so I am not worried or scared about Covid. I can work as usual, and socialise how I used to back in 2019. I understand that people are still catching covid, and some become seriously ill, so I feel bad for those people. I am angry at how the government handled the situation, and especially angry about them not following their own rules (parties etc). Maybe I am lucky, but overall I am happy with the current situation.
text_short_wave3: I’m really happy that covid restrictions have ended and we can travel again!
life_event_descr: My partner father of my son has cheated on me. I blame covid and of course his bitch for that.

text_long_wave1:
I feel very anxious of how long this was last, how many people will die. And if normal life will ever be the same again.
Personally I am worried about job security and of course my family who are older, who I have chosen to volunteer isolate with.

It feels you have no power to do anything to help apart from stay at home which is frustrating. I would like to do more, but do not really know how to start as my village has got a really good support network.

I want to do more, but have no direction which makes isolation hard. But I also feel that is a selfish attitude to have with so many people dieing
text_short_wave1:
I feel very lost, concerned and worried for the state of our country.
With so many people dying and people not all heeding the advice to stay at home. Will the world recover, and will normal life ever be the same?!?
text_long_wave2: At the moment I feel quite anxious about Corona, I don't really believe the numbers on the tv about the number of people vaccinated as had a nightmare booking my older parents in for a vaccine. It feels like a lot of the older generation has been forgotten about, so makes me think at the moment it's all very disorganized. The schools go back on Monday and I worry that the number of infections might get sky high again. I want to have some sort of life this year but not sure it will be possible with Covid which makes me quite depressed at the moment.
text_short_wave2: Will this ever end, fed up with negative stories every day about Covid. Or figures on vaccinations that I don't believe is true - Please just give us good news and correct figures
text_long_wave3:
I feel more relaxed about the Corona situation. Yesterday was the first day I did not wear my mask in shops or on the bus. I still wear on the tube or requested to. It feels that things are starting to get back to normal.

If I see a lot of people in certain places wearing masks then out of respect than I will to. My best friend visited last week from Italy we have not seen each other since before Corona started. We both felt that we were becoming less scared and want to travel and do more things and really get our confidence back for all things.
text_short_wave3: Currently I feel that things are on the up, the sun is shining the weather is warmer so less people should be sick. I feel we have past the worse of Corona and things are looking brighter and more hopeful
life_event_descr_wave3: Working from home, my stress levels have gone down, I am more organised. Feel in a better place to tackle things like Corona

text_long_wave1: I am feeling very nervous and anxious, not just at the current situation but at the fact of the unknown for the future of the individual people of the world, countries as a whole and even the world as a whole. When will the lockdown end? But what happens then? How do we go back to normal? What will normal be? Will it ever go back to how it was before this? Will we ever be able to move as freely in the world again? These are all unanswerable questions at the moment but the most worrying questions of all.
text_short_wave1: Nervous, blubbery mess, it is in times like this where you do realise the uncertainty and unknown are the scariest thing of them all.
text_long_wave2: I am feeling okay regarding the situation as a whole, my family have all had their first jab so that has relaxed me about working in a school. However, I am now just feeling fed up and sad about staying inside and not being able to do things or go anywhere on my days off, even if that is popping into my village for a coffee. I am not angry any more about decisions made, I understand that it must have been hard to make decisions on something no one knew anything about, it is just annoying that decisions are still not being met (e.g. shutting of the borders), that could mean we can be 'free' for longer and safer. I personally would much prefer to travel within the UK and boost our economy if it meant there would be fewer lockdowns than to travel abroad.
text_short_wave2: I am feeling fed up with lockdown, don't get me wrong I won't break the rules, but it is upsetting to walk past pubs and cafes and not be able to pop in and boost the economy and not be able to do anything. I am completely fed up.
text_long_wave3:
I do not feel worried about the COVID situation and after having vaccines am happier to be out and about and visiting new places. I am no longer wearing face masks in any situation. I am no longer as worried for my health and safety, although am still concerned if my elderly relatives were to catch it. 
Despite being less worried when someone coughs or sneezes in a public place or has poor hygiene I am now extra cautious around them and become worried. 
I also get anxious at any cough which I have and any COVID symptoms I have as I worry it is COVID when it could be any common cold.
text_short_wave3: I am happy we are beginning to get back to normal, but stay safe and cautious everybody!

text_long_wave1: I feel like the corona situation is on its way to being fixed. Everyone should stay home to help the situation. It is hard but everyone can do it. Everyone just had to find stuff to entertain themselves. The important thing is that everyone can help by just staying inside. We have a long way to go yet but the signs are good that things will level out and then improve. I suspect we’ll be social distancing for at least another month. I do worry about the economy but I think the government and everyone is doing the best they can. It is an unseen event so everyone is having to figure it out together. There’s been a lot of businesses doing what they can to help people; all the free exercise videos and people offering to get food for people that can’t get out. I hope this continues and the NHS gets more funding because this has proven how vital it is to the UK and how it is under funded. It will undoubtedly have put strain on a lot of relationships and people’s mental health but everyone can help to make it easier. If people don’t follow the lockdown guidances it will just get worse and it will all go on longer than is needed
text_short_wave1: Coronavirus has turned everyone life upside but I just hope we can turn it into a positive. Help fund the NHS and see all the good that has happened to the environment and animals
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2: I feel it is on its way to getting better. I think the corona virus is on its way out but I don't think life will be back to normal for a while. I have accepted that life will take a while to get back to normal so I am calm with it all. I just hope people don't go silly so that it takes longer than it should for things to get better. I think the world will take longer than the UK to get back to normal and that will set people back. I do worry about places that aren't taking the right action like Brazil as it slows the progress down.
text_short_wave2: I'm glad things are on the right track with corona. Can't wait for life to be back to normal but better to be safe than sorry.
text_long_wave3: I think the corona situation is complex. I understand the need to move on from corona with it having less of an impact. However, it does not seem worth reporting numbers if we are not doing anything about it. Masks are a thing of the past for the majority and people are living a normal life. Yet corona is still prevalent. I agree it is time to move on from corona but keep an eye on it. People are getting corona more now than ever but less are actually sick. It seems increasingly prevalent in my area and many around me have it or have had it this month. I have managed to avoid it despite making no effort to do so.
text_short_wave3: How can corona cases be so high but I still manage to dodge it? Live really is back to normal even with corona hanging around
life_event_descr_wave3: I got a job at the start of lcokdown
employment status_wave3: Due to start a new job within the next month

text_long_wave1:
Feel worried and scared for the future. It's good that the numbers are going down, but don't understand how we can then go back to normal without it returning? Feel I need to do more to help as I have been furloughed so have the time but then I also lack in motivation with just doing things at home. But that is not new for me. I feel lucky that we have a garden to go in and feel bad for those confined to small spaces and those on their own. 
Fingers crossed the numbers continue to go down and we can overcome this.
text_short_wave1: This situation is scary and I hope it doesn't get further out of control. I worry for loved ones.
text_long_wave2: I feel that there is light at the end of the tunnel and am counting down the days until the certain restrictions end such as when we can mix indoors and when shops/services open and 21st June. I feel happier now that most of the vulnerable have been vaccinated which hopefully should mean less hospital admissions if they did still catch it. I just really hope we don't get restrictions back or that they delay the dates they said we can do certain things, we all really need to get back to normal now. It's really important especially for family and friends to see each other, some people have been alone for far too long.
text_short_wave2: Feeling hopeful, roll on summer, coronavirus you can go now!
text_long_wave3: I do not feel as worried as I did at the start of the pandemic. The majority of people are now vaccinated so hopefully anyone that does get it should feel the effects less. I don't like that some companies are still using it as an excuse for not doing things that they previously did, such as offering certain services. It is very frustrating trying to get a face to face appointment at the GP surgery and it's even harder to get any kind of appointment with them unless you phone at a certain time of the morning, wait in a long queue and are able to be seen that day. I wish they would allow us to book appointments in advance as used to as people cannot always attend same day appointments or even spend 20 mins on the phone trying to get through. I believe there is a massive long-term effect of the pandemic such as businesses closing and people missing out of treatment.
text_short_wave3: Feeling optimistic about Covid-19 however I believe it's going to be difficult for life to return to exactly how it was before :(
life_event_descr_wave3: Sorry I read the question wrongly. I have had events that have been impacted by Covid-19 but I don't think that is what you asked. I think you are asking if events impacted the way we dealt with covid
life_event_descr: My grandmother becoming I’ll and then getting help, meeting my boyfriend early in the pandemic, having covid myself

text_long_wave1: My mood changes with the news of the day. Today I am a little more optimistic especially as the number of infections has dropped dramatically. I am not daft enough to show too much hope though as they could easily go up again. Last night I was very sad when I heard the PM had been taken to hospital. It also damaged my morale and I think if we were to lose him the country as a whole would take quite a hit.  I am fearful but try to keep that in check with logic. If the usual flu season casulaties were reported in the same way as this virus has, the figures would be much more scary. If flu was a notifiable disease then we would have lockdown just about every year.
text_short_wave1:
(I would use a quote I have recently seen) 
Let everything happen to you: beauty and terror.  Just keep going. No feeling is final.
text_long_wave2: I am angry that it has been allowed to go on for so long. I am angry I have wasted a year of my life through governement and SAGE incompetence. I am angry that although there are thousands of respected scientists who have said we could have done everything differently they were never nced listened to because for the government to admit that would mean losing face. I forgive the reaction a year ago but within weeks most sensible people could see whilst this was a pandemic, it wasnt on the scale that it was reacted to. i saw with great sadness today on the news schoolchildren being taught how to take Corona tests and I was sickened to my stomach at the sight of this. There has been so much unecessary expense, effort not to mention the extra deaths that are coming down the line due to missed diagnosis and treaments, nto to mention the poverty when furlough ends and a million people are laid off, if not more. This must never be allowed ot happen again and there needs to be impartial enquiries with each death investigated as to whether c19 was their cause of death as we all know the vast majority died of other things. And when this data comes out and the mistake is revealed, no less than jail time should be meted out to Johnson Hancock, Whittey and all the others. i have already decided that unless there is a massive shake up I will never vote again. My faith in this government and this country as a whole (due to the stasi like orders to snitch and the bickering over distancing and masks etc) has never been at a lower point.
text_short_wave2: Despite the figures dropping due to the time of year the governement persist in their charade and we still have to pretend it is as they say it is. Hopefully as time progresses their incompetence wil be fully exposed and a price will be paid for their criminal negligence.
text_long_wave3: I am very angry as day by day more information is being revealed that the reaction to the virus was a massive over reaction and the money wasted is going to cause us all huge problems as time goes on. Lives are being lost due to missed and delayed appointments which were not neccessary. Astonishingly, people like Whittey are getting knighthoods instead of being put on trial for crimes against humanity and wreckless endangerment to life. There needs to be a response to their deeds so it can never be allowed to happen again.
text_short_wave3: Day by day more proof comes out that the whole pandemic reaction was unwarrented. Heads need to roll for what was done to this country.
life_event_descr: Becoming a parent

text_long_wave1: I am feeling very scared. Scared for my partner, for my children and for myself. I am paranoid about one of us catching it.  My OCD has intensified and my anxiety is spiralling out of control. I am petrified one of us will get ill. I am worried about losing money/jobs. I am struggling to cope with being in lock down.  If lockdown gets stricter I fear I will not cope.  I am so very sad for all of the lives lost and scared for all of the frontline workers battling to save everyone.  I can’t see a way out from this.
text_short_wave1: I am so scared.  Wishing for a miracle to help us through this.
text_long_wave2: I am feeling burnt out and in desperate need of a change of scenery. I am hoping that virus levels will continue to fall so that lockdown measures can be relaxed and I can take my children to the woods or the beach. They need it for their mental health.  My family and I have stuck to every lockdown rule set and we are finding it increasingly frustrating seeing people break these rules - especially when we have sacrificed so much. I am trying to feel optimistic for the future but when I can receive the vaccine seems a long time away.
text_short_wave2: The few ruin it for the many. We would have beaten this virus a lot quicker if people weren't so selfish and made the same sacrifices the rest of us have.
employment status_wave2: Due to start a new job within the next month
text_long_wave3: I feel that the government are taking the wrong approach with the current handling of the pandemic and that ultimately there are going to be many more deaths. The fact that people will no longer need to self isolate if they test positive is ridiculous. This will be a sure fire way to spread the infection and put people at risk.  The mental health of so many people has been greatly affected over the past two years, myself included. There need to be provisions for people who are suffering with their mental health. My daughter has never had a normal school year and isn't getting to do the things a six year old child should be doing in school. Trying to get a doctors appointment is usually an impossible task. On the rare occasion that you can get a reponse, you have a telephone consultation when you really need to see them face to face. The government need to rectify this by putting provisions in place. They will come to regret the way they have decided to handle covid currently. This is a very scary situation and I am dreading the second part of this year.
text_short_wave3: The government are playing with people's lives. All they care about is money. They will regret how they are handling this situation.

text_long_wave1:
It’s a worrying time and brings out much anxiety. You realise how much you take for granted being able to see family and go out whenever you want. It’s also worrying in terms of work and economy - will small family run businesses survive? How long will it take them to build back up and can they with so many people losing jobs, losing income etc?
How long will we have to stay in lockdown? What will the impact be on many things. But it also brings out what people really feel and who are really important to them. You really do find out who your friends are and how very important your family are - staying in touch is so important.
text_short_wave1: Don’t let COVID-19 keep spreading. Stay home. Stay inside. Protect the NHS. Protect your loved ones.
text_long_wave2: Still quite anxious about it. Happy that lots of people are getting vaccines and that it seems to be having an effect. But worried about what the last 12 months has left behind in relation to state of the economy, folk holding off seeing their doctor and therefore more terminal illness diagnoses, fear of going back to some sort of normality and not wanting everything back as it was. Looking forward to spending time with family and friends again. Have got used to working from home and hope this continues.
text_short_wave2: We’re almost there but still can’t be complacent. Stick to the rules a little while longer and we’ll get there.
text_long_wave3:
Not as anxious as 2 years ago although slightly anxious at the thought of going back to normality with lack of masks and no PCR tests and therefore passing on Covid to vulnerable people. Think people will just think it’s all over and go back to exactly how things were pre pandemic. However cases are higher than ever before and infection is still rife in the community. Am concerned at what people will say if I decide to continue to wear a mask in certain situations eg on public transport and in busy places etc. 
some good things have come from all of this like being able to work from home and don’t want that to end - hybrid working is the way forward and employees can prove how well it has worked.
Do worry about how this has left our country as a whole in terms of financial implications and how / when we’ll recover fully.
text_short_wave3: We’ve come through the past 2 years but we still need to be careful and protect the vulnerable people around us.

text_long_wave1: I feel very relaxed about the situation. My immediate family are all at low risk. We are social distancing in the ideal situation, with a reasonably sized house and garden and no underlying health conditions. I feel mildly worried for my dad who is over 70 with high blood pressure and does not seem to be taking this seriously enough, but my overriding feeling is one of gratitude that my immediate family are in no danger and living comfortably. I am self employed and have slightly less work, but we have taken a mortgage holiday and our general outgoings are reduced by staying at home, so we don't have financial worries. I feel slight guilt that we are in such a fortunate situation whilst others are suffering and that I cannot volunteer for the NHS because my husband is already a key worker. I feel slightly sad that my children are missing out on their regular activities but aware that they are lucky to do them in normal times. I don't socialise much anyway so I am not really missing the social interaction. I feel I am in as good a position as it is possible to be in under the circumstances and I am grateful for that.
text_short_wave1: I feel grateful that we have a house and garden to relax in. We are not stuck at home, we are safe at home. None of my immediate family are in the at risk category. I feel grateful to the NHS and relaxed about our own situation.
text_long_wave2: I feel relatively positive about the fact that the vaccines are being rolled out and that the children are able to go back to school. I feel a mild amount of worry that everyone seems to think the schools will end up closing again and also that this could happen due to variants.  In general I feel happy that things are looking like they will soon be starting to get back to normal.  I'm in no rush to travel abroad but would love to have a normal summer being able to see family and travel within the UK.
text_short_wave2: So pleased schools are able to open again.  I hope this is the last time they close and that we really are going to start getting back to normal. So thankful to the NHS and the vaccine developers.
text_long_wave3: I feel that the time to worry about the situation has passed.  Our family have all had the virus, adults have been vaccinated and children didn't get it badly.  My only worry is having to spend a lot of money on covid tests if we do get symptoms as they are no longer free.  The virus itself doesn't bother me although I will continue to take the vaccinations that are available to me and ask my children to do the same because they will prevent us from getting the virus so badly.  I am slightly worried about my elderly dad catching it but so far he has avoided it although people in his house have had it.
text_short_wave3: Vaccinations are necessary and sensible to protect us all.  However those of us who are vaccinated and without underlying health conditions shouldn't be too worried about ourselves but should continue to take precautions (particularly vaccines) to protect the vulnerable.
life_event_descr: We experienced the suicide of a family member
life_event_descr_2: Taking on new roles in my job in the NHS to support covid response

text_long_wave1: I am feeling calmer now we’ve been isolation for 3+ weeks but I feel so scared for family and friends. I continue to feel anxious about deliveries and the ‘outside world’ coming in to our bubble. I am in awe of those on the front line. Normally I am very impatient but I’ve come to terms with the fact this will be a long and painful process in many senses. I feel concerned for my son that this social distance will ostracise him from learning opportunities and the ability to socialise. At 2 years old I am relieved that he does not understand some of what he is missing out on. The only positive emotion comes from the opportunity to spend quality time together as a family without interruption.
text_short_wave1: Something so minute wreaking havoc and horror in the lives of us all. It’s invisibility is what I fear most. So thankful for our key workers. They are what allow me to feel safe and cocooned in our home. I am hopeful for how people will approach life after COVID19
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2: I don’t want to relax. I feel happier now my husband is vaccinated. Strangely my anxiety and concern is about my family rather than myself. I feel angered about others relaxed approach. I’ve been angered by seeing neighbours out and about with covid. I’m excited about some sort of normality returning but equally this makes me thoroughly nervous. I think the government have had a hideous situation to deal with and no matter what they’ve done there’s always going to be people who disagree. I think this will permanently change society. In some ways for the better.
text_short_wave2: Corona has changed us, made us reevaluate what is important, made us appreciate what we have and learn to look closely at ourselves. There is a fear and anxiety that will take a long time to break down. It’s made me appreciate science and kindness.

text_long_wave3: I have relaxed. I worry I have relaxed too much. I feel confident with my level of protection and have got all vaccinations as soon as I could. I’m not too concerned for my four year old son as I feel it won’t impact but I do still worry for my husband who has a heart condition. I do feel that the vaccinations have given him protection. Frankly I’m amazed we have not had covid as far as I know, despite exposure. I do worry about travel and that it will rear its head when we’ve planned to go away. I feel desperately sad for those who have lost family and still see it as a threat but not as severe.
text_short_wave3: I feel confident that the worst is over but know that the language and lifestyle that we’ve been living for the past two years is now our reality.
life_event_descr_wave3: Husband working from home has changed relationships and strengthened his bond with our son.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: My mum having pulmonary embolism

life_event_descr_2: Relationship breakdown.

text_long_wave1: I am able to work from home, its a nice day today and I've been working in the garden for the last hour so I'm very comfortable.  I am able to do my weekly shop at my local supermarket down the road which is not too much bother and I am making an effort to stay at home unless I go for a walk (once a day) or shop (once a week) so I feel happy as I can be in this scenario and happy to sit it out until we are allowed to go out more freely. I have concern and anxiety for the older people in our communities, particularly those more stubborn that insist on going out and popping to the shops several times a week putting themsleves and others at risk.  I appreciate not everyone is able to be too comfortable at home due to a variety of factors but I think its important for us to all make the best effort we can.
text_short_wave1: Stay at home everyone, it's not worth risking the health of others even if you will be fine.
text_long_wave2: I am feeling optimistic.  Both of my parents have had their first vaccine dose and will hopefully receive the second within the next month or two.  When they are vaccinated I will feel even more at ease.  For myself, my partner and I both had COVID back in November 2020, although it wasn't great I, fortunately, did not have any serious issues. I'm really looking forward to travelling abroad again possibly this summer if it becomes possible.  I am also looking forward to getting vaccinated but I am most wanting the older people to get both of their vaccinations.
text_short_wave2: Stay positive.  Summer 2021 will be better than last summer.
text_long_wave3: I feel that the Corona situation has largely calmed down and passed in my country (United Kingdom).  Although there will be countries struggling with the impact Corona has had on them for years to come, such as more developing countries, I mostly feel fine about the situation here now and it is all pretty much back to normal.  I feel fine and safe to go about my usual business and I would comfortably travel abroad during this time.  I wouldn't hesitate to wear a mask in a medical environment such as a hospital or doctor's surgery to protect the more vulnerable though and have compassion for those that still have concerns.
text_short_wave3: Coronavirus is largely over in the UK and it is something we have to live with moving forwards.  The more vulnerable may still feel unsettled which is completely understandable and I will try to be compasionate about that.
life_event_descr_wave3: I was able to fully work from home which is something I absolutely love doing and has increased my work life balance.
life_event_descr: i got pregnant and struggled for 7 years, managed to save loads of money, got a dog and got engaged

text_long_wave1: I think I have quite mixed emotions really. I am enjoying spending more time with my family. I don't really mind being stuck at home at all and I'm happy to use Facetime to chat with my extended family. On the other hand I'm really annoyed about the way NHS staff have been treated by the government and the hypocritical way they are being praised while being denied what they need to stay safe. I'm also quite fed up with social media and am making an effort to avoid it. There are too many people with misdirected anger - having a go at their neighbours.
text_short_wave1: If you're a Tory you have no right clapping NHS workers. Where was your support for the last 10 years?
text_long_wave2: I am tired of the continuing situation but also nervous that the few benefits that have come from it will all be forgotten or abandoned in the rush to get back to normal. I didn't trust or like the government before this situation and nothing they have done has changed my mind, but I'm sad that generally people don't seem to agree. It seems they could do anything and people would still vote for them. I've been very lucky in that I haven't lost anybody to this disease, which probably makes me a bit complacent.
text_short_wave2: when will things go back to normal (eg everywhere's crowded and you have to go to the office)
text_long_wave3: I feel resigned to the fact that nothing is going to be learned from. At the start of the pandemic everyone was saying how it would change everything. Now I feel like it will change nothing, and even the people who have behaved in a criminal way (politicians and their friends who have been gifted large sums of public money) will get away with it. Work is all returning to normal for the vast majority of people. Sick pay is being cut back, benefits, everything is going back to how it was before. Nothing will change as a result of this. I think we will all just forget.
text_short_wave3: In 5 years time we'll be saying 'remember the pandemic' and chuckling, and that will be it. All the death will have been for nothing.
life_event_descr_wave3: Diagnosed with depression

text_long_wave1: I am not extreemly worried about the corrona virus situation, I know it will pass eventually if we al follow the rules and stay inside. However, it is extreemly annoyong as it means I wont be able to see my girlfriend for a while. I will also not be able too see any of my friends in person, but we all manage to talk online everyday. This situation has given me the opotunity to become healthier as i am eating better and exersicing more in my garden, which is a positive outcome for this situation. I am only slightly scared for my grandma as she is alone and vunerable, but I know she will be fine in the end.
text_short_wave1: Stay inside, think about others, protect the NHS
text_long_wave2: At this very moment, I am quite frustrated with the corona situation, the government has not handled the pandemic as well as it should have. Being in lockdown is not fun and I would like it to be over soon. I'm anxious about how the situation has affected people close to me, as many people have had a much worse time than I have. However, I feel positive about the future, I believe the vaccines are effective and that enough people will take them so that we will be in a much more normal situation come the summer.
text_short_wave2: Board now. Can this be over soon so everything can go back to normal. Thank you.
text_long_wave3: Things seem to have gone back to close to normal so I am not feeling too worried about the coronavirus situation. In the last couple of weeks/months, I have been able to go to work, go out with friends, and generally spend more time doing activities that I was not able to do in the last couple of years. However, I have recently tested positive for coronavirus for the first time which has made me slightly anxious for the people who are around me as they are slightly more at risk to the desires than I am. This has also made me a bit annoyed at the current guidelines that are in place as coronavirus is still clearly an issue in society, but the guidelines make it seem that it has gone away.
text_short_wave3: Things are looking more positive now! But I want to remind everyone that COVID is still around and is a real pain if you get it, so stay safe, wear a makes, and take risks when you know you can afford it.

text_long_wave1: I’m scared. I’m scared that if myself, my husband or my young kids get ill that we’ll be separated. I’m scared of what the world looks like on the other side of this. I’m scared my elderly parents in Australia might fall ill and I’ll be trapped in the UK. I’m sad that my Pop in Australia is about to turn 100 and won’t be able to see any of his family. I feel sorry for the NHS workers who jobs place them in an environment surrounded by this virus. I feel safe in my little bubble, in my house, garden and local park but as anxious when the groceries are delivered. I am thankful I can still get deliveries. I’m thankful I gave birth three months ago when i could choose a homebirth with my family close by. I am happy when online purchases arrive as it feels like a slice of the normal but feel guilty that they may not be considered essential and are wasting the resources of the mail service. I feel guilty that I’m on maternity leave and not working even though my job isn’t one as a key worker
text_short_wave1: '@covid19 - you are f**ken scary. I’m scared for my kids, my partner and my parents and most of all for the world you will leave behind.
text_long_wave2: Sad about the economy and lives the lock down has effected. Sad about the lives lost. I also feel fortunate to have a job, thankful for my family and a home. Because nurseries are open I have my sanity. I feel sad that as an Australian expat, my family hasn’t meet my 14 month old daughter and no idea when they will. I feel anxious about the vaccine shortage as I’m yet to get one. But I’m thankful my husband, who is a teacher, has had his. Mostly I feel like we’re all just waiting for life to restart. Things are nice and calm and our world is small but we know there’s so much more and we miss it
text_short_wave2: I’m tired. Tired of working from home, of avoiding friends, shops and cafes, of video calls, of walks, of fresh air. I’m tired of having a small world. The world is big and fast and exciting and I can’t wait for it to start speeding up again.
text_long_wave3: I’m happy. I’m happy that things are going back to normal. I feel comfortable socialising without a mask and going to busy places again. Today I went to cafe, a park, meet up with some new people to volunteer, into London to see a theatre show and it all felt wonderful.  I understand the risk to myself and family and thanks to science and vaccinations, I’m not afraid of the virus. We’ve been lucky enough to avoid it but I’m sure we’ll catch it one way or another and I’m comfortable with that. I also realise how important normal life is to my own mental health and will always grieve for what I lost during lockdown.
text_short_wave3: Thankful science has allowed our normal lives to resume. I’ve missed the old me and am happy to be happy again
life_event_descr_wave3: Parent reduced work hours to allow me to have a better work/life balance

text_long_wave1:
Im very concerned and anxious. Due to COVID-19 I have no income and worries about when I can work again. I’m also worried that my parents or someone close to me might get sick and might not make it. There is so much uncertainty and I am getting really upset by it all. I know it isn’t forever but it feels like it at times. I’m wanting everyone to take it seriously and stay at home so we can get over this quickly. 
This whole situation is making me depressed. Social media is not helping as all the celebrities are living their fancy lifestyles and separated from normality.
text_short_wave1: Please stay at home. Better days are coming.
text_long_wave2: I feel anxious moving forward what is going to happen and whether there will be another spike of cases and how people will be once lockdown restrictions are lifted. I am still hesitant to go about normal activities due to me trusting those out there to follow the rule as I do not believe many have. I'm sad a lot of things have happened over the year, it has been an extremely tough year for me and been a struggle at times. There have been few happy periods and I can't wait till things improve so I can feel happy again. Overall I am feeling hopeful for the future but that is in a year or so.
text_short_wave2: The light at the end of the tunnel is getting brighter. Better days are upon us.
text_long_wave3: I've grown tired of the whole situation. I'm hoping that more day to day activities will return to normal but with people making sensible decisions i.e. not going out when positive. I do feel hopeful for the future and that the worst of it has passed but this does not negate from the terrible effects of the virus. A lot of people have suffered in which I feel sad for and hope that those can find peace. I hope that my future plans will still go ahead such as holidays and that it is like those pre-covid days in which it was easier to travel. Also I do not want to catch it so will continually be careful.
text_short_wave3: Normality is nearly there. Can't wait!

I am not sure when all this is going to end but I get the feeling late June/July is the first time I am going to see a resemblance of normality. I am glad that at least on my weekly trip to Tesco's that the shelves are now returning to normal and that people have stopped panic buying items which was just totally stupid.
text_short_wave1: Please someone from the UK government answer this question for me please...why are we still letting foreign nations into our country on numerous planes even from New York daily

text_short_wave3: covid still rife in my area but things going back to normal ;-))

text_long_wave1: I think it's a bit worrying but Chris Whitty CMO has recovered and seems well. Nobody close to me has been touched by the virus so it does feel a little abstract and external. I think everything all feels a bit surreal; almost like a plot from a film. I am frustrated that a lot of people are flaunting the rules and seem to think that social distancing doesn't apply to them which seems reckless and selfish. I don't want someone I care about, or even myself, to become ill, maybe critically, because someone wanted to go and sunbathe in a park.
text_short_wave1: The virus situation is worrying and peculiar. I hope people stop being selfish; I don't want to lose someone I love because people couldn't resist sunbathing in the park en masse.
text_long_wave2: I feel quite fatigued by the situation and the lockdown. It feels like the UK response hasn't been good; we have lost lives and livelihoods. I want things to go back to normal but I understand the need for the current restrictions. I think the rollout of the vaccine has been really impressive and will definitely help get us back on track for """"""""normal"""""""" life. I think COVID-19 will become part of every day life, a bit like flu, in the future. I miss my friends a lot, and with the restrictions I haven't been able to see them, as we can't travel. I think the situation has been going on so long that I'm feeling really tired. I am trying to think of the future and keep cheerful.
text_short_wave2: Just looking forward to seeing my friends when the world opens up again!
text_long_wave3: I feel like the serious complications seem to be lessening but the increase in cases and lack of rules is worrying. I do want to go back to normal and I am finding myself feeling fed up and a bit burnt out about it all. At the same time, I am concerned about the risks. I am worried about the pressure that might be placed on the NHS again if things continue to get worse again. I feel grateful for not having contracted COVID so far but worried my time is coming. I am also somewhat concerned about the long term impacts of having the infection - whilst I feel like there's a certain inevitability about catching it, the worry is what it might do to someone long term if it doesn't kill them.
text_short_wave3: The situation is worrying; the increase in cases and the lack of rules and a lack of clarity on the death and hospitalisation rates.
life_event_descr: Have lost a friend to Covid and my sister works in a and e and we have been worrying about the health and well-being effect it has on her.
life_event_descr_2: Being in lockdown with my family allowed us time that we don’t usually have as a family to spend a few weeks together.

text_long_wave1: I feel tired and withdrawn and like this will never end. Im anxious about mine and my families health and the economy and how we will recover. Im not sure if this part of the survey is flawed as i originally wrote a really long piece and it wouldnt accept it even though it was more than 500 characters. But little things like that seem to irritate me more than usual. I feel annoyed and sad as well as worried my ocd will go through the roof when the restrictions are relaxed. My cousin and aunt work as nurses in a badly hit hospital so i am concerned for them and my elderly grandma they visit to give shopping to.  I am hating being cooped up with my partner who im arguing with more than usual as he is snapping and being horrible more than usual which stresses me out as usually i am very laid back. In my head i want to break lockdown and just travel to my family but i never would and i feel powerless and useless to help other people.
text_short_wave1: Coronavirus has me stir crazy. I wouldnt mind isolation alone but with a difficult partner its hell.
text_long_wave2: I am bored and depressed feeling trapped from something i view as low risk to myself and my peers. Money is the biggest issue. I feel that the pandemic has really highlighted a lot of health problems within our society. I am not concerned about catching the virus as my age group is low risk. I am hoping lockdowns end very soon as i feel mental health problems are much worse than covid19 in the long run and society will have more poverty as a result. I also feel fed up and tired and unmotivated and stressed as a result of lockdown and the media scaremongering and people being hysterical and over the top whenever someone disagrees with them on the topic.
text_short_wave2: Covid19 is real and we need to protect the vulnerable, but not at the expense of our jobs, mental health and lives.
text_long_wave3: Not at all worried as I've had it twice. I am concerned about the economy and the lack of jobs, worried about future control the government can take. Not anxious about the disease at all although did lose someone I knew. Feel excited for the world to open up again and have a future. I have a strong desire to do much more. The economic financial crisis is my main concern. As is the NHS being so outdated and useless......... people unable to get appointments with a Dr or dentist people dying from preventable disease because everyone was so scared of COVID
text_short_wave3: Glad corona virus restrictions have finally ended!

text_long_wave1:
I feel angry at people who are not following the Government advice - I have seen larger groups of people every day and l have seen many instances of people not following social distancing guidelines.
I feel like the Government are being evasive about the Prime Minister being in hospital which is making me worry that perhaps the situation is being worse than we are being led to believe. I am also very stressed at how NHS workers are unable to access equipment and tests when more well known people are able to access them with what appears to be very little effort.
I worry for self employed people at this time and the support they are getting and I am angry at big companies with rich owners who actually have the capacity to help but do not.
text_short_wave1: The PM will be receiving the very best health care there is whilst medical staff, the elderly, the infirm, the self employed, the poor and the vulnerable have to make do with whatever is offered to them (if anything)
text_long_wave2:
I am currently feeling very frustrated at how this situation has been handled and it feels like there is still no clear end in sight. Despite the vaccination roll out there are still huge sacrifices we have to make. I miss my freedom and being able to live my life the way I want to. 
I feel like the government has been so slow to respond to everything that it is now making the situation drag along even longer than necessary. I am frustrated at seeing how my friends in Europe seem to have more form of a life - even though they have curfews they can still see people in small groups and have some form of social life. I also feel like ordinary people are being blamed instead of being empathised with what is a very difficult situation.
Whilst I understand the importance of following the guidelines it has now gotten to a stage where I am more concerned for my mental state that the virus.
text_short_wave2: Cannot wait for all this to be over so I can spend time with all my loved ones! Missing you all and excited to be reunited (soon I hope!)
text_long_wave3:
I am feeling angry at how the situation has been handled and the long term effects on society and the economy. I feel like the Government and media have handled things poorly and created fear but then have quickly dropped all restrictions leaving people uncertain and feeling vulnerable. 
I feel like the public were blamed for their actions when the Government should have shown stronger leadership and and done so with honesty and clarity. There were mixed messages and I feel like the pandemic was also used as a diversion from other important issues
text_short_wave3: How can we trust the dropping of restrictions when nothing was clear during the pandemic itself?

text_long_wave1: Not particularly worried about myself but concerned for family, especially those who are older or otherwise particularly vulnerable to the worst effects of coronavirus. Although I can see that positive steps have been made, I am generally disappointed with the government response, both in terms of mixed messaging and the failure to expand testing capability. I think the financial measures to protect jobs, encourage workers to stay home, and assist people to pay bills must go further. I am very worried for those in the health service, particularly due to the shocking lack of PE and ventilators, which is at least partly due to the failings of Conservative governments to fund the NHS and other public services.
text_short_wave1: Whilst I have no problem being asked to stay home and avoid contact for the time being, the government must match the public's commitment to play its part by ramping up testing and ensuring that PPE is available to all frontline workers.
employment status_wave1: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave2: I feel very worn out by the ongoing situation but also apprehensive about the dangers of 'getting back to normal'. I often feel as though there is no light at the end of the tunnel. I have frequently been disgusted and angry at the shocking failures in governance that have exacerbated the crisis and the lack of nuance in the discussion, especially in the media, about the costs and benefits of constantly flipping between 'opening up' and full lockdown with nothing in between. I am beginning to feel hopeful that things will improve, especially with widespread vaccination.
text_short_wave2: I don't see why, given all that we have discovered about this virus, the response to any change in the level of transmission has to be framed as a binary choice between a full lockdown and 'back to normal'. Why do we refuse to learn any of the lessons from this crisis?
employment status_wave2: Not in paid work (e.g. homemaker', 'retired or disabled)
text_long_wave3: I feel, and have felt for some time, a great deal of frustration and at times worry about the equation of 'living with Covid' to pretending that it never existed. Whilst I would not support further lockdowns at this time and understand that society cannot be shut down forever, I don't see why low-impact mitigations and measures, like free lateral flow tests and working from home where possible are not being kept in place, with further measures ready to be reintroduced in winter months. I am also conscious that the pandemic is far from over in much of the Global South.
text_short_wave3: I think that the proper approach to Covid, at least for the time being is to hope for the best and plan for the worst; to keep some measures, like LFTs in place, with a clear plan that can be implemented if further measures become necessary.
life_event_descr_wave3: As society has opened back up following lockdowns and restrictions, I have retreated to the safety and comfort of my flat much more than before.

 the good thing is thats its made me appreciate more what is truly important in life and i will appreciate this more in the future

i know covid is not over but i feel we are past the worst of it. this is a relief and i feel like i can get on with my life and enjoy myself which makes me happier than before.

i now have a desire bigger than before to go and travel the world and see it at its best.

text_short_wave3: happy weve seen the worst of covid

text_long_wave1: I feel very anxious about the global coronavirus situation both from a population level and on an individual level. I have previously been hospitalised in ICU when I was 18 with pneumonia so whilst I feel very concerned about the health implications for myself I also feel a very strong empathy and sympathy for all of the individuals suffering with coronavirus, and the families which are being affected by it. I believe this anxiety is made worse by the constant media attention, although I do understand why this is necessary given the severity of the situation.
text_short_wave1: I am feeling very anxious about the coronavirus situation as I worry about the health implications for both my family (who work on the front line) and of those in the general public, in addition to how the virus may affect me directly.
text_long_wave2: At this present time I feel relatively optimistic about coming to the end of the coronavirus pandemic. I feel hopeful that we will be able to stick to the timeline for coming out of lockdown and that things will return to normal soon. I feel we are hopefully now over the worst of it and the number of cases will continue to decline, mainly due to the vaccination programme but also the lockdown rules. I am most looking forward to being able to see my family after the pandemic is over, as although I have really appreciated the additional time to work from home and spend with my partner, I have really missed seeing my wider family who live quite far from me.

text_long_wave1: I feel ok with the situation, so far as things affecting me personally. I'm thankful that I no longer live in the 2-bed flat in London, but in a rented house in Devon, surrounded by countryside, with a garden. I'm focusing on the positives, in terms of time to do things I've not had chance to do for a while, and focusing on the business that my husband and I run. We can go for walks straight from the front door, shopping is sometimes less straight-forward, in terms of what's available, but... we can cope. My 85 year old mother is in touch with me, she's ok. My only worry is for the small businesses in our local town; I fear for them, and hope that most are able to survive. I know many won't be so lucky, and that saddens me. But the isolation side of things really doesn't worry me. When my husband's on a contract, I'm home alone during the week anyway, so in some ways, this is much the same!
text_short_wave1: Thankful to be in lockdown here, with tons of gardening to do, a quieter road, and spring busy springing. Know it's much harder for some, though.
text_long_wave2: It's been like living in Groundhog Day, but without there being any sense of personal development and moving forward. Sure, I've been able to develop some new skills, such as copywriting, or doing more on the tech side of the business, but it's been a year of endless loss. And although there are promises of lifting restrictions, I'm deeply cynical about how much will actually be lifted. Three weeks to 'flatten the curve' turned into months, then back into more lockdown; 'the vaccine will turn things around', except that actually, the vaccine hasn't changed anything, and won't change anything. Not when everyone is willing to see business destroyed, livelihoods ruined, and the police moving forward to totalitarianism.
text_short_wave2: 'All this buttoning and unbuttoning'
text_long_wave3: Irritated by the attempt to ramp up fear and anxiety over Covid again. All for something that is still, at heart, not more dangerous than ‘flu (both kill people, but you never heard much on flu…) The media narrative played into the government agenda to create fear and panic - seeing it as a great success that they’d succeeded in their aims. All for what? To facilitate the work of WEF and create the New World Order. How much more do you want me to say, for goodness’s sakes? I never cared about Covid, never believed the media, despair at how people so quickly leapt to follow the rules, and equally despaired at how they turned into sanctimonious little Hitlers at the drop of the hat. Following rubbish data from a discredited source, and it all deflated like a spent bladder once the hypocrisy of the government was exposed. Best thing ever! Show it all for the sham it was. Oh yes, people died. But ‘with’ not ‘of’ for the most part.
text_short_wave3: Looking forward to seeing what trumped up excuse for social coercion and manipulation the government and media will come up with next. Perhaps we can all lick dud or Climate Change? Either way, we’re one step closer to WEF’s agenda 2030: own nothing and be happy. Logan’s Run 2

text_long_wave1:
At the moment it feels like suppressing  sadness. You forget it’s there for a while, do ‘normal’ tasks and then it hits you how scary the current situation is. It’s the fear of the unknown. You’re pretty sure you and your family are going to get the virus but there’s no way of knowing how bad the symptoms could be. It’s anxiety for family and worry for yourself. It’s wanting a cuddle with parents and family who aren’t close by and wondering if and when we’ll be together again. 
I would describe my emotions like a roller coaster. Having a young family helps as during the day life goes on and I can generally focus on them and I feel grateful that we’re getting extra time together. When they go to bed I seem to get a half an hour come down where my adrenaline kicks in and I process the days events. I’m trying to take extra care over my media use as my stress levels seem to increase when I read or watch too much news.
text_short_wave1: The corona situation seems to have condensed very clearly what and who is important. Everyone just wants to be with family, key workers have been seen for their worth but the class divide seems to have been highlighted in a rather unsettling way. Maybe positive progress will come
text_long_wave2: It feels like their is a small glimmer of light at the end of the tunnel. I don’t fully trust everything that’s reported so I’m still a little anxious how likely things are going to return to ‘normal’ before the summer but I feel a lot better knowing my loved ones are starting to get vaccinated. I’m still waiting for mine but it’s a small step in the right direction. I definitely feel upset and frustrated at how long it’s been/ still will be before I get to see my close family. I am a key worker and I occasionally get angry at people I know who are not following the rules even though I have no choice but to continue to come in close contact with other people.
text_short_wave2: Corona. You have made us appreciate things more, appreciate our family more, reflect on what is really important more. You have made us stop, made us grieve, made us think. Thank you. Now please leave.
text_long_wave3:
Now I’ve had my vaccinations I feel a lot happier about the situation. I feel better once my children have also been vaccinated. Now I just want to return to normality and deal with the repercussions of the past two years.

My anger is directed towards tombs government who have repeatedly not adhered to the rules the rest of us have stuck to. The lack of respect for people - many very vulnerable - who still are abiding by rules to keep others as well as themselves safe is infuriating. It worries me how far the ‘one rule for them, one rule for us’ could go.

I am a key worker so my sense of the pandemic has been shaped by trying to maintain some form of normality. As a teacher I can see how Children’s mental health has been affected and it worries me that our numbers are so small to take care of so many very vulnerable children. I can also see how the gap between the have and have nots will continue to widen over the next decade because the social work needed to support families is simply not there. Again this makes me very angry when I see how our government behaves and then pretends to show empathy.
text_short_wave3: Corona you have highlighted all our societal differences and how wide the gap is between those who have and those who have not. Maybe in time we will see this crisis as a key moment in the progress of health and social care. Maybe. Sadly not today.

text_long_wave1:
Anxious. The Prime Minister is in Intensive Care as of this evening. 
As a former nurse I have a good understanding how serious this is, and how fast people can deteriorate. I feel until now an awful lot of people have been dabbling with obeying the rules and this is a HUGE wake up call. 
Four weeks ago I instituted a handwashing station at home, beside the front door, in my utility room. Liquid soap, single use hand drying cloths which go straight into the washing machine. 
A week later I tild my son who works in a supermarket that his uniform had to go straight in the wash when he comes in from work and I started wiping down the groceries with dilute bleach. 
I haven't been out apart from grocery shopping for three weeks and haven't seen my partner, who lives 40 miles away, for three weeks either. I am taking this VERY seriously and was doing all this stuff a long time before my friends were. They thought I was a bit mad, to be honest. 
This is a time where the government say JUMP and the correct response it How High?

text_long_wave2:
I saw my partner in early December and then for a couple of days at Christmas (under Scottish rules, as a non-cohabiting couple we could meet for more than one day. We have not met since. 3 says out of the last 81. 
Last week, we almost split up. 
It is so difficult to keep a relationship going under these circumstances. I am worried about us. He is starting to suffer from depression and I have had a resurgence of anxiety. The estimate for us being vaccinated is the end of April. 

I’m not even angry any more. I focus on one day, sometimes just in the morning or the hour ahead. I can’t plan anything. There is no point. I’m just sad about the opportunities lost, not only for myself, for us, but for everyone. 
I think I am resigned to it being months before we can meet and next year before life is tolerable. 
Normal doesn’t exist any more.
text_short_wave2:
Everyone is experiencing grief about losses. Lost opportunities, lost friends, lost time. 
Mostly. This is about the loss of hope.
text_long_wave3:
My situation has changed. Six weeks ago I fell in my garden and basically smashed my right shoulder so badly it has required a total shoulder replacement. 
As a result I am now in a cycle of hospital appointments and physio. I cannot drive and won’t be able to until at least July. 
Having sort of calmed down about Covid I am now very worried about it. I need the appointments to work in a particular sequence. Scans, physio and medical. If I get covid it will knock the sequence out and my rehabilitation could be affected. 
I can’t drive so I am reliant on friends to take me to appointments because I don’t want to risk public transport. I am suddenly dependent on others. 
And covid is making me plan VERY carefully.

This is yet another situation where China failed to fix a problem; in the past proclaimed that these markets are banned, yet it's blatant that they have not been with this virus occurring. In response to the virus, I am disgusted WHO is backing China when refusing to oppose pro-CCP sensitive questions, and possibly manipulating statistics. The victims of this situation will die in cases beyond the virus, where vulnerable populations will be hurt, once again, due to irresponsibility. I am sickened by thinking of the world post-Covid19. All those with lost jobs, regulations being placed when nobodies paying attention, increase of poverty and wealth displacement. There's too many thoughts and feelings, though sadness and repulsion seem to be the easiest way to define how I feel.

Even those with a modicum of common sense would realise that wearing a mask would protect one from aerosol transmission. text_long_wave3:
I am now much more relaxed about the Coronavirus situation. I did catch it right at the beginning - on my 70th birthday in fact. Whilst I was ill in the sense that I felt as if I had ‘flu, I certainly never thought that I was in mortal danger. So, having survived it (without having had the benefit of vaccination), I have not been anxious about it since. However I am much more concerned about the effects of isolation - not for myself, but for the more vulnerable in society. 
I feel that there is a lot that we can learn from the experience. Societal changes that were deemed necessary at the time have, in some cases, given us opportunities for a reset. For instance, I won’t go back to full time working at the University any more, but will teach online wherever possible. I get much more work done if I don’t have to commute. This has reduced my stress, workload, travel time and a considerable amount of money for travel. 
I have also reconnected with family and friends and also with nature (walking, gardening etc).
text_short_wave3: Coronavirus has given us the opportunity for a reset. Let’s not lose sight of some of the benefits.
life_event_descr_wave3: Reconnection with nature. Resetting of work practices.

text_long_wave1:
I'm incredibly concerned for the health of my close family. My parents are both in the most vulnerable age range, and my father in particular has health concerns. My sister works in the NHS as a home carer, visiting people in their homes, which puts her at tremendous risk. Personally, my finances are in a bad state of affairs as I work in entertainments and have had no work at all for several weeks and no income. I'm struggling to pay for food.
The lockdown itself hasn't bothered me too much, I've been able to keep myself busy so far, but the general anxiety of the growing crisis edging ever closer to my life is causing me some distress.
text_short_wave1: I'm fearful that life will never be the same again one way or another, and that it will take a long time for anything resembling normality to return, if at all.
text_long_wave2:
At the every beginning of the crisis I had fears over whether or not the government was capable of handling the situation effectively, whether the people who were tasked with taking charge of the official response and protecting the population as much as possible would be up to the task. I liked to think that at the very least they would be able to make the most basic efforts of minimising transmission as much as possible
As I sit here almost a full year later having lived through the crisis as it unfolded, the overwhelming emotions I have right now are very much anger and disgust. I believe that the government had the information they needed about the potential issues that Covid could create, but at this point it's clear that they chose to ignore the people who were advising them and pursue a dangerous course of action that has resulted in one of the worst infection and death rates in the world. Inactivity at critical moments, conflicting information, late decisions and bad judgment all contributed to what has turned into what feels like a complete failure of governance.
Not only that, but they have actively used the crisis as a means to award lucrative Covid-related contracts to personal friends and associates, often without any service or materials coming back in exchange.
Now my greatest fear is that the amount of time between the first and second stages of the vaccinations - more time than recommended by the vaccine makers and industry experts - could potentially create the perfect environment for a resistant strain to develop, alongside the mutations we're seeing appear.
As a person who contracted a moderate Covid infection over Christmas I can confirm that this feels different to anything I have ever experienced before, and almost three months later I still have minor issues occasionally as a result. I believe that this could all have been avoided to a large extent, but for the decisions and actions of the very people who we trusted to make competent and wise choices on our behalf.
text_short_wave2: Currently angry at the government, sad for society in general and fearful over the future developments of the virus, as well as the economic situation in the country.
text_long_wave3: I feel that we have lost all control over the situation now, or what control we ever had. I think that the government response even from the very outset has been poor, with even the most basic decisions being taken too late to be effective, which has led to an excessive amount of infections and deaths. Now we are also having to deal with conspiracies about the Covid situation, not only on the origin of the virus but also the actual existence of it, the vaccines and the motives of governments regarding restrictions and associated guidelines and rules. We will never be free of Covid now, and I worry that new varients will emerge that will cause greater problems for us.

Finally, I am really nostalgic about things that I used to enjoy before, while now I feel like I am missing out on experiences. 
Surprisingly, the experience of being so restricted makes me feel grateful and appreciating of everything that I was able to do before the lockdown.

text_long_wave1:
I feel that we are in a very delicate situation right now. The pandemic is really hitting hard in most parts of the world. I fear for my family, where some of my relatives don't have a choice but to continue working. They are at high risk of contracting the virus. This makes me feel fearful half of the time. 

Personally, with the UK going in lockdown, it is the correct decision, but I do feel a little trapped and lonely right now. I feel that I can't escape my home and I hope this changes soon.

text_short_wave1: Coronavirus spiralling out of control
text_long_wave2:
I am more relaxed now compared to a few months ago, as vaccines have started to be administered throughout my country. I am still worried about the spread of new variants of the virus, but I'm mostly more optimistic about the direction we are heading to eliminate COVID-19. 

At this moment, I'm still worried about loved ones who are vulnerable to the effect of the virus and ones that work for the NHS. I know some acquaintances who have been affected by the virus and people who have died from it, so I have taken extra caution to ensure I can minimise the chances of contracting it and spreading the virus to vulnerable people within my family and within my local community. 

I have taken a very cautious approach to the outbreak and have mostly reduced my hours at work.
text_short_wave2: This virus is no joke. We need to be united to tackle it. Wear a mask, practice social distancing and stay safe.
text_long_wave3:
Coronavirus seems to have mutated to a more harmless variant, hence I am more relaxed about the situation right now. However, I am still cautious and remain vigilant in public spaces with crowds and will continue to wear a mask despite it not being mandatory in my region. I would still rather not infect vulnerable people who may be at risk of the virus. 

Last year, I would try to avoid crowded places as much as possible. However, in the last few months I haven't really been apprehensive in these situations and have been willing to take the risk. 

Overall, the future is looking better, but we need to remain cautious as we are unable to predict if the virus will mutate to more harmful variants in the future.

text_long_wave1: I am surprisingly calm. I try to stay in the moment and force myself to accept that I personally cannot improve the situation more than adhere to the advice and rules put in place. I thought I would be more anxious but I seem to have settled in a """"""""I'm doing what I can"""""""" and """"""""I cannot change or prevent any possible outcomes by worrying about it"""""""" This is not typical for me as I am a very anxious person normally, which makes me suspicious that there will be reprecussions later. I still """"""""go"""""""" to therapy once a week over video call which keeps me sane.
text_short_wave1: This isn't time for selfishness, or the """"""""this doesn't apply to me""""""""-mindset.  We need to take care of each other and ourselves by adhering to the rules.
eng_native_wave1: No but I speak it fluently
text_long_wave2:
I have recently moved back home, from a huge city to a very small town. Things are less prominent here, I can go outside without meeting another person etc. It is easier to feel safer and to forget about the situation here. When I lived in the city I thought I could feel its entire population tense in fear of the lockdown, the death rates.
I have lost some of that acute fear and anxiety now. I feel guilt to the friends still in the city that are locked down, and struggle to be understood by anyone in my town, since none of them experienced lockdown whatsoever. 
I am worried about the state of the world, of the mental health of so many many people. I worry about the pandemic fatigue creeping in- how people tell themselves it's safe just because they're tired of the situation.
text_short_wave2: Feeling like this year is a bad, never-to-be-resolved, subplot in a Lost-esque TV show. Like it shouldn't be real, and surely I'll wake up soon & it'll be February 2020 & we can do it all again, virus-free, normal. I can't remember much, & what I recall is pure shit #exhausted

text_long_wave3:
I feel conflicted. I am exhausted by keeping up with the numbers, the deaths, the variants, the anti-vaxxers, the worry, the despair, just all of it. It has become mundane and commonplace and it's so difficult to maintain a health relationship to the pandemic and how to think about it. Recently I have stopped reading the news because I came to the conclusion that at the moment it does more harm than good, and doesn't benefit me in any way. Life has gone back more to normal after the second and third vaccine dose, but I struggle with choosing to go to a public space or somewhere I know will be relatively crowded. I fear that the pandemic has fully revived my social anxiety and issues, and due to that I have been indulging it for almost two years now (albeit for mine and others' safety), I worry that it will be difficult to address and manage.
I'm not as worried about being infected anymore, I am young, healthy, and vaccinated. I still feel guilty if I choose to do something social, something frivolous, such as going into a non-essential shop.
