Holidays cancelled, birthdays affected. I am very worried about the health and wellbeing of my family and friends who are all compromised due to underlying health conditions. People are not following the rules of social distancing and believing it's just the flu. Needlesly risking other people's lifes due to their own ignorance and stupidity. It has been difficult trying to get time off work in order to self isolate so as to protect my family. The economy is going to tank again just as I was starting to gain my feet from the last financial crisis in 2008 which hit a few months after I finished high school. Stronger sanctions should have been in place weeks before the where to try and minimise the disruption to the world. All travel from hotspots banned, people quarantined for 14 days, large gatherings cancelled sooner. Hopefully lessons will be learnt for next time. The only glimmer of light is that people are helping others in need. I hope this can continue long after this is over.

text_long_wave1: I am far less anxious about myself, and more so about my loved ones. My parents in particular worry me, and as I’m not with them that is the primary source of my anxiety. I think that the UK wasted valuable time that they could have used gathering supplies and tests and should have locked down earlier. Instead they seem to have fallen for their own exceptionalism and that is clearly proving false now, so I have anger about how this situation was handled and deeply hope we massively increase our testing soon.
text_short_wave1: I know that it’s scary and boring, but we all really need to stay inside. Too many vulnerable people are being forced to rely on the assiduousness and adherence to government guidance of strangers, and that must be terrifying. Put yourself in their shoes and stay inside.
text_long_wave2: I’m annoyed with the government for handling the situation so badly, at the cost of so many lives. On a personal level I’ve been extremely lucky in that no one close to me has been ill so far, but I still worry every day that that could change. I found out I was pregnant with my first child around this time last year and have since gone through an extremely isolated pregnancy and childbirth, and my son has been unable to meet his grandparents. All of this also brings feelings of anger, but mostly sadness, and I hope things improve soon.
text_short_wave2: It’s been a year and not much has changed. Our government has only just begun to implement common-sense measures such as a travel quarantine. Thousands have died yet the government faces no consequences for their mishandling of the situation nor for their corrupt dealings. Why?
text_long_wave3: I feel that Covid has absolutely not gone away and although vaccinations have afforded us some protections it’s ridiculous to eliminate all restriction and aid. I am especially concerned as I have a one year old who is unable to get vaccinated and I desperately want to keep him safe. I also worry about the huge amounts of waste created from testing, disposable masks, etc, despite knowing why they’re necessary. I am, however, optimistic that some of the changes made during the height of the pandemic will remain, such as remote working.
text_short_wave3: Rising case numbers and the elimination of all restrictions makes me very fearful for the future.
life_event_descr_wave3: I was pregnant and subsequently had a baby during the pandemic.

text_long_wave1:
Very anxious and fearful. 
I think it’s mainly the fear of the unknown. Will I catch it? Will I die? How long will it go on for. 
There’s so many unknowns 
Very worried for my family members and then my child. She’s the reason we’ve been isolating for the last 3 weeks, to protect her 
It worries me like mad when my husband has to work, as he’s in and out of people’s houses fixing boilers. We’re being very cautious and just taking each day as it comes. 
Hopefully people will listen and stay at home, although we did just go for our daily walk and see a group of teenagers playing football.
text_short_wave1: Why can’t people listen and stay at home! The nhs is struggling and vulnerable people are going to die. All because people can’t stay at home. It’s infuriating that people can’t see that this is temporary and things will get better, if we all follow the rules and stay at home!
text_long_wave2:
Hopeful and Optimistic. I am having my second jab tomorrow and looking forward to lockdown being lifted soon. 
It’ll be nice to have some sort of life again with my little girl and have days out
The last year has seemed to go pretty quickly looking back though
Other than that, it’ll be nice to get back to work full time too 
and be able to have childcare again! 
I miss the little things like the beach. It’ll be nice to go for a walk along one again and breathe in the sea air

It also nice to see the daily numbers dropping in my local area
text_short_wave2: Feeling very optimistic about the covid situation! Numbers dropping daily and it’s looking positive and going in the right direction. Let’s hope people keep it up and keep sticking to the lockdown rules. Won’t be long and we’ll hopefully have some normality back! Can’t wait
text_long_wave3:
I feel a lot more relaxed about it. I’ve had it twice and my close family have had it and been quite well. So the anxiety is a lot less. 
I’m a lot more confident being out and not wearing a mask and being in larger groups of people 
Also being in work is a lot more relaxed with being a health care worker. 
Over all my mental health is a lot better due to less anxiety 

It’s frustrating how rubbish the government have been during this time. They should all be held responsible for their actions and all the lives that have been lost

Also knowing there are plans for lockdown to end in the next few months makes me feel better too- although I do feel anxious about life after the pandemic since we have been indoors for so long now away from people. I haven't been out of the house much since the first lockdown last year.

text_long_wave1:
My emotions have been quite up and down over the last few weeks as a result of being in lockdown. Sometimes I feel quite content. I know I am very lucky due to my situation at home. But there have been times where I feel lonely and miss having the opportunity to see important people in my life, such as my boyfriend.

I also feel for all the people whose families are being so badly effected and for those who have lost and are losing loved ones. Two of my friends lost their grandads within a couple of days each other and I think that is when the situation really hit home for me.
text_short_wave1: It is devastating to see so many people's families and lives falling apart. At this time it is so important to take the time to appreciate what and who we have and to come together to help those struggling.
text_long_wave2: At the moment I feel quite optimistic and relaxed about the corona situation. this is because i know the vaccine is accessible and things will be back to normal soon. I also feel that the situation has been over-exaggerated in the media, through only representing the bad figures and not any of the positives, such as the survival rate. it has made university more stressful, having to do it online and having online meetings. Right now i feel closer to my family, having had the opportunity to spend more time with all of us together
text_short_wave2: Feeling very optimistic about the future, can't wait until I can just hang out with friends in the sun
text_long_wave3:
At this moment in time, I don't feel any worry or anxiousness in regard to the pandemic situation. If anything I feel slight anger, because I would like things to return to normal. Despite being vaccinated myself, I feel that travel restrictions for unvaccinated individuals should be removed.

Most things have returned back to normal but as my partner is not vaccinated, we are restricted in what we can do. This has lead to some frustration on my part as travelling is a big part of my life. Hopefully these changes will be removed over the next few months.
text_short_wave3: Ready for travel restrictions to be removed so we can go away again soon

text_long_wave1: The Corona situation is a very differcult thing to take in. Watching the news Daily, hearing about more negative news has been hard to take on my anxiety and I fear it so much. I'm worried about my loved ones as some of them have their own health problems that could put them at massive risk and that's the most scary thing about this virus. I fear it will get a lot worse before things get better which could go on to last months which will have such a negative affect on so many people mentally, physically and financially.
text_short_wave1: The selfishness of parts of society have shown in the worse thing this counrty has gone through since the second world war, from stockpilling, putting the prices up on medical supplies such as hand wash and loo roll. But we have also seen so many brave and amazing key workers.
text_long_wave2: I feel relaxed about the current situation, It's been a difficult period over the last few months especially. Now with the vaccine rollout in full swing things are looking brighter knowing we can have a road map in action knowing better times are ahead. It's also positive that the case rates have fallen drastically to more lower levels. The one big concern is the threat of new variants which could hinder all long term effects of the vaccine rollout. The variants from South Africa were a concern
text_short_wave2: The corona situation has been not only mentally draining it's taken it's toll on pretty much every part of our lifes. Life has changed for the longer term in however capacity that will be in. Finally though after more than a year of this pandemic hopefully we can get some peace
text_long_wave3: I feel nothing bad towards the covid situation at this current moment as I've already caught it and had 3 jabs so can't really be any more protected than that. I believe that we all Need to live our lives as normal as possible now, having been around for over 2 years I think it's the right time for us to think about putting the pandemic behind us, I do recognise that we will Need to have a 4th jab likely to be in the autumn time but will be just like the flu jab yearly. I feel more important issues are currently taking place within the World with the war in Ukraine I believe could lead to a greater war across the world.
text_short_wave3: 2 years on, feels like forever we have been living with covid, but time to look forward with me already having caught covid and having my booster jab I don't think you can get much better protection that going forward. Ditch the masks if you feel comfortable to but wear them to
life_event_descr_wave3: We had a close death in our family which was impacted when I had covid.

text_long_wave1: At the moment, I am feeling quite sad about the amount of people that are contracting and dying from the virus. Particularly, when it is people who are known to me or have been in close proximity to someone I know. I fear that someone in my family may not be safe. Also, I have some family members in the NHS who I am particularly worried about and my grandad who is vulnerable and living with him has made me anxious about being sanitary. When I don't consciously think about the situation I am able to relax and occupy my time. The worry is that there is no knowing how long the lockdown is going to last and what the repurcussions will be.
text_short_wave1: Getting a lot of things done during this lockdown. But worried about the NHS staff and vulnerable people. Let's hope this lockdown is over soon so make sure to socially isolate so we can get back to normal life.
text_long_wave2: I am currently feeling hopeful about the situation, as the vaccination is being rolled out. I am excited to start getting back to normal life, hopefully in a few months. I am less worried now as the rate of deaths and cases is decreasing which makes me feel more confident that we will have some more normality back soon enough. I am feeling a little less relaxed than I was though as I am starting to get frustrated with spending so much time at home and not having much to do. At first, I was enjoying the time at home but now I am getting a little fed up as everyday feels the same. I would like to see my family and friends and get outside to do some interesting things.
text_short_wave2: I am feeling really positive lately. Now we have the vaccine being rolled out, there is some hope that we can get back to normal life. I am hopeful that we will be able to see our friends and family as we used to and start to go back to the things that we used to enjoy.
text_long_wave3: I feel a lot more comfortable with the situation as life has gotten back to normal. Whilst there is still a lot of cases of covid the rates of deaths and people getting really Ill has reduced  which is very positive. It seems that we are no adjusting to covid as a typical illness like the flu.I am happy and excited that we are now able to do life as normal. My anxiety around the situation has reduced. Similarly when we were first getting back to normal I was very anxious about everything due to covid. However I do not feel like this anymore
text_short_wave3: Whilst there is still cases of covid around, I am happy that we are adjusting back to normal life. It is positive to see the rates of people getting seriously I’ll from covid is reducing

text_long_wave1:
At the moment I feel guilt for enjoying the isolation, I suffer with social anxiety and sadly, this staying inside has allowed me to regain control of my routine and fall back in love with my hobbies, but in the same vein I'm scared for what's to come when it's all over or even before it is, I'm worried about my family members, my job and when the world will be back to normal. 
Currently my place of employment is closed and as it's a small business there is a good chance it will go under as the local authority isn't supporting them as best they can. I honestly have no idea what life will be when this is all over.
text_short_wave1: I feel very confused. I'm trying to find the positives in the currently situation but it's difficult.
text_long_wave2: At the moment I feel like the end is coming, but now, I feel worried about what the world will look like after wards. Will we ever have the world as we knew it before? I'm excited to see family and friends, but there are many that have been permanently affected by all this and I'm worried they won't be how I remember them. I'm scared for losing my time and my comfort blanket of isolation. I'm scared about going back to work as I've had so much time off I'm completely re-evaluating what I want to do.
text_short_wave2: I can't wait for this to all be over #lockdown
text_long_wave3: I feel like the pandemic as a whole is basically over but the feelings I'm left with aren't. I've developed agrophobia because of it and now struggle on a daily basis, I also have family members who haven't left their house basically since it started. I also still look for it on the news all the time and kind of expect us to be hit with another wave at any moment. I hate all that we've lost because of it, businesses and general way of life, it makes me sad all the time. It’s also weird to think this may be the biggest tradgedy I experience in my lifetime and it’s not even over yet. A couple of days ago it marked 2 years since the start of the pandemic, but it doesn’t feel that long and maybe that makes it even worse.
text_short_wave3: I'm still scared about this life we'rd living.

Personally it hasn't effected me much, i did lose alot of work but i found other things. Never been worried about catching it. text_short_wave3: Corona should be taken seriously.

text_long_wave1: I am anxious about the situation as a whole but mainly worried about the more vulnerable people in my family, however I know we are all taking precautions and following the correct guidelines at this time. Being in lockdown is manageable although difficult as I normally use my friends and busy university life to keep my mind busy most of the time, so being isolated has had a slight negative effect on my mental health but I am doing my best to deal with it. The only anger I feel about the situation is perhaps how the government handled this originally (but they're better now) and the people who ignore the lockdown rules who I feel are very selfish in a time like this.
text_short_wave1: This time is hard for everyone, but the more people follow the guidelines set out, the quicker this will be over and we can all get back to our normal lives.
text_long_wave2: I am more concerned that the government still isn't handling the covid situation well than I am about actually catching the virus myself. The idea that we could be put in another lockdown after the current one worries me especially with the amount of vaccines and time that has gone into trying to return life back to normal. Although I understand it is a horrible virus that has affected people all over the world, I haven't personally had it nor anyone else I'm close with, the main way I've been affected is since last March I've only been to my university once for a practical and so my education has been negatively affected.
text_short_wave2: Everybody should get the vaccine as soon as possible so we can start returning to more normal lives once again
text_long_wave3: I feel accepting of the situation as it is ongoing and I can not do anything to stop it but be careful to ensure the wellbeing of those I care about, such as family and friends. I was very sad and anxious at the start of the pandemic but since restrictions were lifted I have enjoyed living life more normally again and am no longer as anxious or sad. Also, I understand the science behind the virus, especially the vaccines, and trust that I am protected enough from falling too ill as I'm vaccinated, which is the main reason I'm comfortable partaking in activities I did before the pandemic.
text_short_wave3: The virus is still out there and a threat but I trust the vaccine and the science behind it so I believe we should try to start living normally again.

text_long_wave1:
I feel anxious and stressed about how long this situation will continue and how long we will be isolated. I worry for my mental health, as I suffer from anxiety and depression and isolation has always been a trigger. 

I feel sad for those who have lost loved ones, especially when I hear of front line workers losing their lives. 

I feel further away from my family than ever before. 

I feel like I'll be judged when I leave the house, even though I am only going out for legitimate reasons. 

I feel angry at stupid people who carry on sunbathing in parks and visiting friends. I also fee angry at people on the street or in the supermarket who don't try to keep their distance.
text_short_wave1: I feel strange being indoors so much but even stranger when I leave the house. I miss human contact but am terrified of it. I miss commuting. I miss grocery shopping. I miss taking the bins out without feeling watched. I feel alone yet more a part of my community than ever.
text_long_wave2: I feel frustrated that it is still affecting our lives so strongly. I am also frustrated that the government bumped my health condition (asthma) from Group 6 in the vaccines. I'm sad my family couldn't visit the country this year and anxious because I don't know when I'll be able to see them again. I am also bored of working from home as I feel very isolated from my colleagues and not part of the team. I'm looking forward to restrictions lifting a little so I can see my friends but nervous that it will cause cases to rise again.
text_short_wave2: Never thought I'd say this but I miss my commute. I miss going into an office every day. I feel isolated and alone but also terrified of crowds and public transport. Ugh!
text_long_wave3: Worried about the way society is relaxing towards it. I had Covid last week and now my dad (in another country) has it, so it's definitely not """"""""over"""""""" even if we're acting as if it is. I am concerned cases are going to keep rising and/or new variants will form because we're being so lax now. I am hopeful the vaccine will help reduce the severity for those who are infected and I'm looking forward to getting my top-up/fourth jab once available. I do think the government should continue offering free lateral flow and PCR tests because it means more people will test themselves and isolate.
text_short_wave3: Bloody sick of Covid but that doesn't mean we can just pretend it's over. Stay cautious, stay safe.
life_event_descr: My anxiety returned a bit in lockdown and I injured my back

text_long_wave1: The constant news cycle, featuring little confirmed information, is exhausting and frustrating. It feels like everything comes with an estimation or a guess, which fluctuates and causes uncertainty. In relation to that, not knowing when the pandemic will end, or when/if a cure will be found is anxiety inducing. But I would prefer to know less about this, until something is concrete. Whilst being inside for long periods of time can add to the symptoms of depression, I currently feel good about using this extra time to work on personal projects.
text_short_wave1: Realising the extent and unknown longevity of the pandemic is incredibly surreal, and feels impossible think about.
text_long_wave2: I am frustrated that the choices the government are making, to move the UK out of lockdown, don't seem to be considerate of what we have learned from what has happened previously. I am anxious because children are returning to schools without being vaccinated, despite them previously being referred to as """"""""super spreaders"""""""". I am worried that we are making steps that will lead to the NHS becoming overwhelmed again and that there will be more deaths. I am upset that the government seem to see these deaths as numbers on a graph, rather than individuals with lives, families, dreams and aspirations - which are just as important as theirs.
text_short_wave2: We must be considerate of what has happened so far in regards to the pandemic, and move forward with patience and compassion. I'm scared that the worst is yet to come if we don't.
text_long_wave3: I am concerned about the long term effects of the Corona situation, particularly as the UK has removed rules on isolating after catching the virus - I worry about what this means for the elderly and vulnerable people in the population. I think it would be a good idea to continue distancing and wearing masks where possible. I understand that we must """"""""return"""""""" to """"""""normal"""""""" at some point, but think the change could be staggered and more thoughtful to those who are more susceptible to becoming very ill with the virus.
text_short_wave3: The Corona situation has taken so many lives and its disheartening to see so many pretend it doesn't, and never, existed.
life_event_descr_wave3: I haven't earned a living wage for almost two years. I find it much harder to leave the house now. I have a lot less energy than I once did.

text_long_wave1: The situation with Coronavirus has caused my life (and more or less everybody else's) to be put on hold. Form me as a professional golfer this means that I am unable to play, causing me to lose my income. This is more than anything just incredibly frustrating. I am not an anxious person but the current situation is making me feel slightly anxious as to when I will be able to get back out to the golf course and begin to improve again. This main anxiety is coming from my inability to do my job which sort of gives me a feeling of pointlessness at the moment.
text_short_wave1: I am very frustrated with the current situation which is effectively rendering me useless at the moment. Staying at home is necessary but basically doing nothing is making me feel a bit anxious as to how I am going to be able to perform at my job when I do eventually return.
text_long_wave2: I feel that the restrictions have gone on too long. I am a healthy young adult trying to make my way in my career (and therefore contribute) to society. However, all the restrictions have prevented ,e doing so and have potentially ruined the course of my career. The heavy handed approach seems to have no end. This sacrifice was so that old and fat people are more likely to survive. Absolutely galling that the economy has been crippled for the sake of people who have put themselves in a position where they are more liable to ill effects of the virus or people who can more or less choose to isolate if they wish. The pandemic has really exposed the horrific level of health within our population.
text_short_wave2: Please let those people who are fit and healthy to continue their lives out to do just that. Everybody is sacrificing for the sake of old and unfit people and we are ruining millions of lives because of it. It time to see sense and restart our economy.
text_long_wave3: I am happy that things are progressing back to normal life in relation to the COVID Pandemic. I am not scared about COVID and having had the virus over Christmas the effect on me was comparable to a regular cold. I think the vaccine has been effective and we must now all get back to work. The greatest problem with COVID is the lasting financial uncertainty caused by many of the steps we took to try and protect the old and vulnerable. As a very fit individual I feel I have been penalised by many of the strict measures. What we can learn from COVID as a society is we need to be much fitter and healthier. There are too many overweight people who have burdened everybody else. These people need to take responsibility for their own health.
text_short_wave3: COVID really should put the health crisis in the UK to the forefront of the news. As a population we need to get fitter and healthier. Doing so would be the single greatest thing we could achieve to relieve pressure from the NHS.

text_long_wave1: I am immensely frustrated right now. Despite having the best performance ever at the beginning of the year, my employer has significantly reduced my salary mainly to support it’s staff elsewhere. We are uncertain as to whether we will be able to go on our summer holiday abroad that we saved up for all year, and we are stuck in the house with 2 young children who are also very frustrated with the same (mainly indoor) activities day after day. And all of this is essentially out of my control, which is where the frustration stems from
text_short_wave1: Bored, frustrated, broke, and running out of box sets
text_long_wave2: With the vaccine programme I am starting to feel more hopeful that things will get better by the summer. I fear I will still be anxious around people for some time to come. I am fed up of lockdown and want to be able to return to some sort of normal. Thankfully with the return of schools my children will get to see their friends again. I am also hopeful of travel being allowed by the summer to permit a holiday for me and my family which we all feel we desperately need. Fingers crossed we are allowed to go abroad
text_short_wave2: Feeling hopeful of some sort of return to normality in the coming months
text_long_wave3: Where I live most of the adult population is now vaccinated. As a result, while cases are still high, hospitalisations and deaths are now  low. Life has mostly returned to normal, with some enduring changes in travel, and how we work. I perceive my personal risk to be low so I feel like I just want to get on with life. I get highly irritated when people talk about reintroducing restrictions, or when organisations are still using the impact of covid as an excuse for poor service. There is talk of further booster vaccination
text_short_wave3: Let’s get on with life. Vaccines work. Stop using Covid’ as an excuse.
life_event_descr: A friend of mine passed away, of non covid reasons, and their family could not be there with them when they passed. Also the funeral could only be attended by 30 people which was a disgrace.

text_long_wave1:
Having just read the news about Boris Johnson being taken into Intensive Care, I feel a huge sense of sadness that these may be the last hours of potentially the greatest PM in my lifetime. Genuinely hoping he pulls through, gets us through this dark time and does the business for Brexit, this Country needs a character and a leader like him at this time more than ever.
As stated, this is an incredibly dark and dystopian time for the Country and the World, I can only hope that when the dust has settled those culpable will be held to account, be it financially or criminally. This isn't a xenophobic statement either, people and Countries, no matter who they are need to be held accountable for the pain and suffering caused.
text_short_wave1: Feeling blue, feeling weary, but feeling hopeful that in a years time we'll look back and count ourselves grateful for surviving.
text_long_wave2: Hopeful for the future because of the roll out of the vaccines. We need some sort of semblance of normality by Sep 21. 2020 and 2021 so far have been utterly dreadful and wasted years. Hopefully when the nice weather comes people won't be silly and ignore SD rules, fines should be far tougher with more stopping of cars and motorbikes who are quite clearly flouting the rules. Passports should also definitely be mandatory for those who choose to be vaccinated, this is a civic duty that should be mandatory for everyone.
text_short_wave2: Vaccine passports should be mandatory, it is a responsible persons ethical, morale and civic duty to get vaccinated and hasten the return the normal.
text_long_wave3: We've taken our eye off the ball and opened the floodgates, COVID is utterly rife in every aspect of our society, schools, hospitals and workplace and to charge for LFTs is absolutely outrageous. People no longer wear facemasks in the supermarkets and apathy is rife. We need to ensure that LFTs remain free of charge and that facemasks are a mandatory requirement. I've just heard that staff absences in hospitals in the past week have increased by 30% this is not sustainable at all. The UK Govt are now in an awkward position of having paid lip service to lockdowns (blame solely squared on our joke of a PMs shoulders), the conflict in Ukraine has proved a welcome distraction for our Govt.
text_short_wave3: Sheer anger at the apathy shown amongst the general public in supermarkets and shopping centres. Zero facemasks worn, zero SD and a general don't care attitude. This has got to change as their are vulnerable people in society who cannot venture out due to selfish attitudes.
life_event_descr: A blood clot in the brain due to having covid last year

text_long_wave1:
At this very moment, my feelings are mainly of an anxious nature. Due to the unknown, what's going to happen to any of us. This may be due to the health of myself, my family, my friends etc. or it may be due to security (job, house etc.)

I am also feeling slightly angry with how certain people have reacted to this outbreak, whether it's their racist acts/comments towards others, or simply their lack of respect of everyone else, flaunting the rules without a care of anyone else.

I haven't once felt sad throughout the outbreak.
text_short_wave1: I am feeling rather anxious about the whole corona virus situation, however, I am feeling optimistic about the future, as things have their ups and downs. We will get through this as long as people don't disregard the rules, which has angered me in the past.
text_long_wave2: Feel positive towards the fact that vaccines are being given to a lot of people on a daily basis. However, I do feel that people will suddenly think that once they have a vaccine that they can't get Covid, which isn't true. I still see a lot of people disregarding social distancing, and this makes me slightly annoyed. I've found that a lot of people are complaining about others during covid, but don't actually follow the rules themselves. I believe there are still quite a lot of hurdles and challenges to get through before life gets back to 'normal' e.g. convincing anti vax people to vaccinate, as well as certain bubbles of the population.
text_short_wave2: Feeling optimistic for the UK with the current vaccination programme, just hoping that everyone else follows suit!
text_long_wave3: I am currently feeling quite anxious about the covid situation, especially through living in a city as there are many people that are suddenly disregarding covid as a situation now that the government has got rid of all guidelines. People are still getting ill yet people are going around like a normal thing, which makes me quite disgusted and angry at those people. I have a fear for my family to get poorly and people are being quite selfish with regards to social distancing, testing etc. and are now being quite lax about it all.
text_short_wave3: Can't believe people are still going around as if covid still isn't here. Many people not wearing face masks and completely ignoring common sense when in groups of people.

text_long_wave1: Stressed and uninformed. Don't feel enough is being done by the government to help with the NHS crisis or the proper enforcement of social distancing.nhs staff should be tested immediately and given the right equipment to fight the Corona virus. There should be a full lockdown straight away to stop the spread.the equipment side of it is the fact that they aren't really getting enough or even any at all.how can you be expected to take urgent care of someone, and also be worried that you might catch it,or maybe even already have it.
text_short_wave1: Everyone needs to listen and follow the rules  to save lives and stop the spread.being selfish won't stop the virus.
text_long_wave2: I feel really good I've enjoyed being alone with my family .my only worry or fear is seeing everyone when this all ends.its made me realise a lot more of what I want from my life.i have started to invest money for the future and tentatively made goals for a retirement plan.im not worried about the Corona virus, just maybe how people will react when we come out of it. I hope attitudes change with regards to drinking too much and people start to look more after their mental health and get outdoors more often.
text_short_wave2: Feeling good about the future.
text_long_wave3: I have had the virus recently and didn’t feel too bad.I feel more bothered about the fact that if I take time off work I won’t get paid.it will also affect my absence record at work.I don’t think that I should be punished in this way as staying off if I contract the virus would save other people from getting it.i personally think most people would go in to work even after a positive test because nobody can really afford to have the time off without pay.there is also the war going on between Russia and Ukraine so many things have gone up in price.
text_short_wave3: Corona is crippling people financially and the government needs to do more to help.

text_long_wave1: I feel nervous as I don't know when the lock down will end, missing my friends and loved ones, but also feel angry that people aren't all treating it in the same way or as seriously. I am looking forward to not feeling trapped in my house. I feel upset that I am far away from some family members and nervous for family which live overseas, because I now definitely don't know when I can next see them. I am really missing being in university which makes me sad that I'm missing out on the final few weeks of spending the summer with all my friends. I am grateful and thankful for all the staff trying to keep us safe.
text_short_wave1: I am feeling very nervous about the future, missing friends and family whom I can't see, but very grateful for all the staff keeping us safe. I wish everyone would take it seriously and stay inside to flatten the curve.
text_long_wave2: I would very much like to be out of lockdown, however, i understand the need for it still. I am looking forward to when i will be able to socialise with friends and family again. I look forward to the future when we can travel to visit family abroad. I would like things to get back to semi-normal so that i can carry on with life and not feel like my young adult life is being wasted. I am worried that it will take longer than expected to get back to normal as i want to be able to do anything i like whenever i like.
text_short_wave2: I can not wait to be out of lockdown and see my family and friends and go to the pub.
text_long_wave3: I feel fine about the corona situation. I think that they should still encourage regular testing and isolating if there is a positive test, but also like that things are going more back to normal. I would like to be able to travel freely again. I feel sad that things have lasted this long, but also would like to make sure that it stays away or can be treated by a cold. I am looking forward to when corona won't be an issue anymore, as it feeels like for two years i have had my life on hold where now i do not want my life on hold and want to enjoy it with family and friends.
text_short_wave3: I am so over covid now can't wait to have a life again
life_event_descr: Closer as a family

text_long_wave1: This is a very stressful time. Not least because of the deaths and illness occurring. Isolation is also leading to illness and deaths through suicide. It's scary to think about how individuals, particularly those at risk, are coping. As someone with a mental health difficulty I find it easier to cope in times of chaos, albeit it seems confusing to me the state of the world and uncertainty we are facing. Being in 'lock-down' is a very necessary step, and it angers me that some individuals are not following the guidance and advice put in place. Conspiracy theories also anger me, such as with 5G, as it trivialises the situation at hand
text_short_wave1: this is terrifying. stay inside. save those most at risk.
text_long_wave2: I am scared mainly about schools opening, I feel the UK government has been very poor in their handling of the pandemic and I don't believe this will change. I am angered by hashtags on twitter supporting the cause of children not wearing facemasks in school when this is a way it has been shown to protect selves and others. I am angry about the ex Ofsted chief suggesting teachers should be prepared to sacrifice their lives for this pandemic - have lives not been sacrificed enough. I am scared we have all become desensitised to death figures or ICU figures etc. that hearing of people dying due to covid means less to the normal person - every death is a death which shouldn't have happened - its horrible
text_short_wave2: Covid is not going away. Yes, mental health is tough but we must prioritise lives, and come up with better mental health care and solutions for isolation which do not involve breaking covid restrictions. We must all do our part to end this deadly virus
text_long_wave3: I am angry at the way the pandemic is currently being handled by the government, for I feel as though our health is once again being put at risk for the benefit of the economy and with 'herd-immunity' in mind. I have been fortunate to bypass getting covid19 since the pandemic started, but I now know 4 people who haven't had it yet, and have got it in the last 3 weeks. I am increasingly nervous about joining them and experiencing a bad illness, especially as I suffer with bad asthma which can worsen my experiences with respiratory illnesses. At the same time, there is a degree to which I understand the need to move on, but I do still think masks should be mandatory and people should absolutely still have to quarantine if they catch the disease. Without this in place, the government is actively killing people.
text_short_wave3: I am so angry @UKGov, people are dying, why should mask mandates be removed? Why should people not have to isolate, when this is actively killing people? Why are we placing profit above people? It's sickening.
life_event_descr_wave3: Moving to a new city and starting a masters degree

text_long_wave1: I am not unduly worried about the situation as I am not in a category of increased risk, nor do I live in an area with many cases so far. My Friends, partner and wider family are fine and in good health, and my job is highly unlikely to be at risk no matter how long the lockdown continues. I own my house and therefore have no worries about landlord issues. I hope that the situation resolves itself as quickly as possible for the benefit of the whole world, but I am suitably prepared for things to get worse before they potentially get better.
text_short_wave1: Things are different, but they will get better. I am more than able to cope.
text_long_wave2: I feel more positive now because, with the vaccine rollout, the vulnerable have more protection. I am still anxious about vulnerable family members catching it, but less than before because of the vaccine. However I will be much happier when they finally receive their second dose of the vaccine. I am hopeful about the positives as life slowly returns to normal in the coming months. I am anxious about returning to work though. I feel that this will again increase my chances of contracting the virus. I am also missing family members who I have been unable to see for a very long time.
text_short_wave2: Fingers crossed for the future, and that things will be back to normal soon.
text_long_wave3: We are relaxing far too soon, and cases are rising. We must avoid repeating previous mistakes. If we continue to not take action cases will rapidly increase. We may have to look at further boosters of the vaccine. Schools are starting to struggle with the increased number of cases. China is massively locking down to maintain zero covid which is also worrying. It looks like we are in a much better situation than in the previous two years, but getting complacent could cause us future problems. Travel has opened up a lot, and this could eventually cause problems if there are more variants.
text_short_wave3: Numbers are rising, and we are not being cautious enough. We have to keep acting to protect public health.
life_event_descr_wave3: Changing career
life_event_descr: I got a new job that involved more travelling and more consistent hours

text_long_wave1: From seeing the daily death rate increasing and people still getting infected is not great, plus with some of the public still believing they are 'immune' or the lockown rules don't apply to them is frustrating for all who are trying to handle the situation. The press inform regularly but not to the level of scaring people into a frenzy. Panic buying has declined a great deal, social distancing seems to work for a high majority where I live but some still don't get the need to look after themselves and each other. Have signed a petition to see if live animal markets have tighter controls if not banned in China, as I believe that countries with this level of mentality should know better, change their barbaric ways. I understand food sources are a requirement, but needs far better control especially where the pandemic has run rife throughout the world (this all depends on truth of the source of covid19)
text_short_wave1: Stay in, save lives: even the smallest gesture to comply will make a difference
text_long_wave2: Even though everyone around the world is in lickdown of some sort, i feel that we as a race have managed to navigate through a one-in-a-lifetime experience that (hopefully) generations to come wont have to live through. Personally i'm feeling optimistic, but also understand this shift to a 'new normal' may continue for some time, plus economies may find things hard to start with until we're back to as close as pre-covid normal. I am annoyed at people who don't believe in the pandemic, and who flount the rules for selfish reasons, because in all likelihood these people would probably not be directly affected
text_short_wave2: Post-covid 19... A new normal that sees how we can adapt and grow even during the tough times and restraints applied
text_long_wave3: Feel that (in the UK) there has been a lapse in control, since the weather has gotten warmer and more people are vaccinated, which seems to indicate that some people believe they have a carte blanche to do whatever they want. I still occasionally wear a mask in certain situations, but also do have a view that the covid situation has lessened but it's still around. A lot of people though during the pandemic seemed to think with a """"""""wont happen to me"""""""" attitude, and when those who did have that approach became ill with covid, I had much less sympathy than normal, because of their disregard for others purely on the belief they were 'not going to get iill from it'
text_short_wave3: Corona - not all it's crakced up to be, but still best be safe than a fool

text_long_wave1:
I an feeling increasingly bored with days and weekends feeling like groundhog day, slightly anxious for food supply chain, it being squeezed, medical staff falling I'll and the NHS being overwhelmed and that of having to put mine and my families lifes in danger by something as trivial as going to a supermarket.
 Anxiety is also there in the realisation that with SARS and now COVID19, that this is only going to become more frequent and not less.
 The 'holier than thou' attitudes of those on social media also makes me want to invent a way of slapping people over https;
 The sneaking in of anti-privacy legislation is also disgusting.
text_short_wave1: If only we could be trusted with common sense, if people weren't so selfish, if people used their brains, thought about others and refrained from self effacing gushing holier than thou posts on social media then we'd either be out of this within weeks or lockdown w'ld b +bearable
text_long_wave2:
Im mostly upset and saddened by the government putting profits before people, wanting everyone to be vaccinated (including children) and it all being based on skewed stats.
 I'm disgusted at the media blocking alternative views and the public from blindly swallowing everything they are fed.
 As someone is is not old or fat, I am angry about vaccination passports and that we can be controlled so easily and willingly.
 I am saddened that ive been imprisoned in my home for over 2% of my life and that voices like mine are not and never will be listened to, taken seriously or are set only to be that of tinfoil hat wearing anti-vaxers (which they aren't)
text_short_wave2: Imprisoned in my home and forced to be injected with a 'vaccine' I neither need nor want
text_long_wave3:
Im disappointed with world leaders, with the media and the general public in their blind compliance, their welcoming of control and restrictions, the fact that we end up paying for incompetence, that our government had parties as people died alone, at people tearing each other apart according to their views, that people now cheer for Ukraine's 'freedom' when they still wear masks alone outside.
 Im also sad that there is only one side and one narrative related to covid, its effects etc and anything else is blacked out, retrospectively altered or a complete lie.

text_long_wave1:
Concerned about the economic impact for myself and the country. Worried that front line NHS staff are being put at risk due to a lack of PPE or planning. 
Sadness that the world will go back to how it was before, forgetting about how we could change for the better as a result of this pandemic. 
Fearful that lessons will not be learned and that the destruction and damage to the environment will continue resulting in many more globally damaging events. 
Concerned that a drive towards a carbon neutral world will pushed aside as country's try to rebuild and use this as an excuse not to drive forward these initiatives.
text_short_wave1: Proud of the NHS and those that have sought to help others. Hopeful this spirit will live on when this passes
text_long_wave2: Frustrated and angry that a year on the UK has not moved forward. The Government failed to act decisively and strongly when it was needed; a pitfall of a populist Government. Countries like NZ are now benefiting and have an end in sight because they acted decisively, meanwhile the UK and  Scottish government continues to flounder, more interested in political point scoring and self gain than focusing on the failings that brought us here. My desire to leave this country and its failures has never been stronger.
text_short_wave2: Failure to decisively act has resulted in decisively failing
text_long_wave3: I am Less fearful now than when the pandemic first appeared, also more relaxed about certain restrictions that are in place, e.g. the wearing of face mask. Equally I'm confused by the current guidelines....does anyone really know what the rules are now? Accepting of the fact that this virus will be around in some form probably forever. Saddened by the fact that this probably won't be the last virus that is unleashed due to humans selfish desire to constantly put money, greed and power ahead of anything.
text_short_wave3: Confused by current guidelines. But accepting that this virus is here to stay
life_event_descr_wave3: I have a greater desire now to spend less time working and enjoy life more. Time is precious
life_event_descr: Whilst working from home I have worked on a few different teams at work and I now have a better job because of it.
life_event_descr_2: I had the omicron variant of Covid.

text_long_wave1:
I am very worried for both my own health and that of family and friends.

I am concerned for my work colleagues who are even busier due to the crisis and feel guilty and depressed that I cannot help them as I am having to self isolate due to my own health conditions.

this is a strange situation, as I have no control over anything, and no cure or solution in sight, if the lockdown ends, I would still think that everyone would still be susceptible to the virus.

I want to do something to help, but feel inadequate that there is nothing that I can do apart from remain at home, unable to see my loved ones, and just listen to the news of the worldwide crisis.
text_short_wave1: hoping that the scientists and medical professionals can beat this thing and everyone follows the rules to try and limit the spread until a cure/solution can be found! hope to see you in the future if we all survive.
text_long_wave2:
I am concerned for myself, family, and the world in general. Although there are early signs that Covid may be coming under control, no one can accurately forecast whether this is the case. This may be a short-term respite and the world may have to consider further more drastic measures. It is very frustrating that there is no definitive solution to enable forward planning.
It is at times difficult to remain motivated due to myself and my colleagues all working from home. There is a lack of cohesiveness in the virtual workplace with a reduction in morale.
text_short_wave2: covid is in retreat lets hope it stays that way!
text_long_wave3:
Although the virus seems to be limited in its life threatening capabilities at the present time, the infection rate is still very high, and it may only be a matter of time before a new more dangerous variant emerges which could send the death rate soaring again.combining tis with the UK governments decision to stop free testing for the viruy, this may delay the notification of a new surge being seen.
The virus has not gone away which seems to be a myth among many members of the public, leading to the lack of self isolation, social distancing, wearing masks and general good hygiene practices.
I myself will continue using the previous safety measures as both being in a high risk category, and carer for a person in an extremely high risk category, it would not be wise to abandon these measures yet.
text_short_wave3: Covid has gone away? I don't think so, it's just waiting in the background to relaunch itself and bit us on the bum when we least expect it!
life_event_descr_wave3: Succumbed to a spinal problem which was exacerbated in both it's diagnosis and subsequent treatment by delays attributed to Coronavirus

text_long_wave1:
I'm worried about other people more than myself. Been furloughed from work but that's actually a positive at the moment and has helped me feel less anxious than I was before.

Older people do need to take the whole situation more seriously as they're the ones not abiding by the distancing rules and that makes me more worried about them, and the possibility that they're spreading the virus. 

The financial situation is the biggest worry, with wage cut to 80% at the moment, assuming that comes through. Plus the concern that the business I work for may not survive this situation. Therefore it is important for to try not to spend money other than on essentials as I may need it to tide me over until I can find a new job after things reopen. Other businesses may also not be hiring due to financial worries.
text_short_wave1: I wish older people would understand the seriousness of the current situation. They're my main worry other than finances, and finances are something that can be fixed later.
text_long_wave2:
I feel like we were just starting to be hopeful about a genuine beginning of the end of the pandemic but all the talk of a third wave and it being harder to control than the previously ones has really added to my anxiety and leaving me feeling a bit hopeless and sad. I’m also sad about all the things that have been lost as a consequence of trying to survive the pandemic. Im lucky to have not lost anyone close to me so far but I do know people who have been ill and a lot of people who have lost livelihoods and possible futures. 

The thought of how things might struggle to get back to normal and the fallout from the pandemic that will probably last for years to come also add to the sadness and hopelessness.
text_short_wave2: I’m relatively lucky with how the pandemic has touched my life, but it has still left me feeling sad and hopeless. I fear for those it has touched more.
text_long_wave3: I feel the restrictions have been withdrawn slightly early. They should have waiting for the winter to be over to allow for outdoor socialising rather than indoor socialising. I am stressed that people seem to be ignoring covid now after we spent so long trying to get the covid infection rates down. I am anxious all the time being around people without the need to self isolate if you test positive. Especially when people can go to work in a public facing role after testing positive for covid. People are not taking covid seriously enough.
text_short_wave3: Covid restrictions were removed too early. If they’d waited until spring then the rates wouldn’t be like this.
life_event_descr_wave3: I bought my own house

text_long_wave1: At the beginning of the outbreak i don't think people were taking it as serious as it should have been, and even today people are still going out regularly and it's terrible to see how people don't care enough about spreading the virus around but rather see their friends at the park for no reason, I just think its hard to wrap my head around how this whole thing occurred and how quickly its being spread around because of sheer carelessness from the public, in all honesty it makes me worry about the future mixed with the feeling of confusion and anger
text_short_wave1: This goes to everybody around the world, please keep your families and yourself safe by doing the right thing and staying indoors unless you absolutely have to go outside.
text_long_wave2: Glad everything is getting better, my family members are getting vaccinated and things are getting back to normal, though i feel mentally affected from the long run of being stuck indoors, I can take it upon myself to finally start fixing my life, i got through college despite everything and it all seems to be ok, however i still am cautious for the future as we have no idea how things are going to be by the time June 21st rolls around, Just a few more cautious steps towards the end for life to get better again.
text_short_wave2: Glad things are returning to a partly normal flow after the vaccine is getting rolled out.
text_long_wave3: I think the government is not doing well enough despite there being so many cases and deaths at this moment in time, though people are vaccinated I still believe that wearing masks is a necessary thing regardless of the rules, I also believe that being vaccinated should be a rule as it is for the betterment of everybody in society as a whole. other than this, i believe that my university has handled the way of teaching horribly as a post covid environment, I blame it for the methods used in this teaching and I blame both the government and covid for my failing
text_short_wave3: I wish that people would stay safe and responsible by wearing their masks and getting vaccinated
life_event_descr_wave3: university

life_event_descr: I have had to spend my entire univerity experience in lockdown using zoom. I feel like i missed out on what was supposed to be the best years of my life

text_long_wave1:
I feel sad that our freedoms are curtailed, but also know it's for the best long term.  I feel that all the working from home and changes to living standards might help to slightly reform our society for the better when this is done - I look forward to that happening.  I also think the world is realising (as a result of the virus) that we share the planet with each other and with nature, in particular I'm loving how nature is reappearing in places all over the world.  I try and look forward to events I have planned further down the year - but remain nervous that these might also get cancelled each passing week.  I miss my friends and social experiences - especially heading out together and going for runs together.

I support our governments approach - appreciating they've had a very tough line to tread between economic collapse and public health.  It's economic collapse that actually worries me more than the virus itself - that will last far longer than a few months of lockdown!!!  If that can be averted, potentially at the cost of a marginally worse public health outcome, I feel the country would be happier on the whole in the long run.  (Sorry that's a bit of an extreme view I know!)
text_short_wave1: Feeling confident the public are upholding lockdown as best the can.  Feeling less confident that we're avoiding economic meltdown - what can be done?
text_long_wave2: I'm starting to feel optimistic about the situation. The jabs are being given to a wider section of the community, including people I know now. I feel it won't be long until we're broadly back to normal. Biggest worry I have is on employment, even where I work things don't feel as stable as they have done for the previous 20 years! I'm looking forward to being able to start dating (marriage broke up a couple of months before COVID) as I've been single and alone all this time. Also looking forward to a holiday and travelling a little.
text_short_wave2: Get the jab when you're offered it. Many people have developed and trialled it to protect you...so don't insult them and put your community at further risk by refusing it!
text_long_wave3:
i’m excited that it basically feels over. the media are still reporting on it which is now getting annoying as there are now enough antiviral meds and vaccinations that mostly noone need worry about serious infection now. it’s sorted. we need to live with it like we do with measles, etc

it’s good we’re getting rid of testing too. in recent weeks i feel this has continued to stoke fear about covid. with testing gone people can learn to relax once again 

in short i’m excited for tomorrow, feel optimistic and relieved that the whole thing is over
text_short_wave3: so long corona, glad to see the back of you! Hello antiviral meds…my new best friend 😊 Looking forward to a happy and fulfilling life from now on.
life_event_descr_wave3: I have been dating the most beautiful woman ever.

text_long_wave1:
I am worried about my family as they come under the vulnerable category. The government needs to do more and probably needs to initiate lockdown as people are still going outside for non essential reasons. This is the only way we can reduce the number of new cases and deaths each day.

Lots of anxiety over the fact that this has spread all over the world and the death rate and new cases are increasing day by day.
 
I'm scared that the economy will take a bit and worried about my job as well as my husband , how will we be able to manage if we are not able to go to work and earn money, being furloghed means we only obtain 80% of salary which eventually will not be enough to sustain our family
text_short_wave1: I don't understand why people are still going outside, the rules are simple , go out only when needed and nothing more, people playing basketball and sunbathing, this will lead to another increase in cases in 10 days, very worrying indeed. #staysafe and #stayathomd
text_long_wave2: I feel sad thinking about all the things I have missed out on in the last year being stuck at home and not being able to go anywhere. It has affected my child's development greatly and he has missed out on so many opportunities. I haven't been able to see my friends and family for nearly 1 year now, we were due to go abroad to see my in-laws but had to cancel this. It makes me sad to think that they haven't seen my son yet and are not too well at the moment, I hope we are able to go back before their health deteriorates.
text_short_wave2: Can't believe we have lost a whole year to this coronavirus. So much has been missed.
text_long_wave3: I feel a little frustrated that restrictions have been relaxed because the virus is still prevalent in the community, people are no longer protecting themselves or taking any precautions.  More and more people are still getting ill with the virus, I am doing as much as I can to protect myself and my family.  I feel that the government now are more interested in the economy then they are with peoples health, they are more focused on improving their finances then they are with saving lives.  Thankfully my workplace are still taking the virus seriously and have many precautions in the work place.  I am still apprehensive about going out in public places because of others not adhering to any guidances.
text_short_wave3: People are still getting very ill from this virus, the virus hasnt gone, but this government doesnt seem like it cares anymore.
life_event_descr: kids caught it

text_long_wave1: I am worried in particular about the long-term. I hope that normal life can resume quicker than I expect it too but only if it is safe for everyone. I wish that everyone would follow the rules, so that we can get through this quicker rather than cause more issues in the long-term. I hope that a vaccine will come sooner than the current projections. I am not currently struggling with the lockdown but moreso just missing being able to go anywhere I want at any time. I am having trouble trying to find some type of work I can do at home in order to earn extra money.
text_short_wave1: I am currently feeling a lot of anxiety and uncertainty. Although the virus affects more people who are older and with health difficulties, there are still young healthy people who have passed. We do not yet know the true capacity of this virus yet.
text_long_wave2: I feel like things are starting to get better. However, it is still important to remember the current situation we are in and how the past year has gone. It is still important to remain vigilant and follow guidelines in order to eliminate the virus. I am feeling antsy about when places will be able to re-open, as there are places such as hairdressers and non-essential retail that I would really like to be able to go to. I am looking forward to when places open back up, as the current lockdown has felt very long and exhausting. I am excited to be able to travel further, go to attractions, shops and travel again.
text_short_wave2: I am happy seeing the numbers of cases, hospitalisations and number of deaths declining. It is also a good feeling seeing the vaccine rollout across the country.
text_long_wave3: The mask mandate has just lifted where I am (Wales) so it feels much more like a state of relaxation. Cases are however rising which is a slight cause for concern, but so far there has not been an increase in hospitalization or number of deaths to be concerned about. It feels more like the old normal is coming back. I am glad that I will be able to travel more and do more activities that I haven't been able to do for two years. Some people are still concerned about catching covid, however there has to be a point at which we lift restrictions.
text_short_wave3: Although cases are rising, I am feeling more relaxed about covid due to the vaccine and boosters. It is a nice feeling that the mask mandate is no longer in place and that we can start to return to more normality.

text_long_wave1: Angry at the way the government has treated the NHS over the past ten years thus when it comes to a pandemic it is not prepared so what they now have to do is throw money into it and claim they could not foresee this. Correct they could not but the NHS would have been much more prepared if it was funded correctly prior to this. I am also angry at the way some of our population is ignoring social distancing despite multiple pleas from NHS workers, however, not as angry as I am with the current government.
text_short_wave1: Angry at the government for it's handing of COVID-19
text_long_wave2:
Angry at government for not acting correctly during this whole situation. Many deaths avoidable due to their incompetence. Many people have died during this which is unacceptable. Also, many are now out of work. The government incompetence is going to be felt in this country for a very long time. I am also angry that many people would vote the Tories in again because """"""""who else could have done better?"""""""" Shameful.

If the NHS was funded correctly they would be able to manage during times like this and 10 years of a government constantly tightening the NHS was never going to end well in a situation like this.

I think it is amazing how together some communities have came during this period and it shows that there is hope for humanity.
text_short_wave2: Fuck the Tories.
text_long_wave3:
Angry at how the government have handled the whole situation. I feel very let down at a lot of the decisions made. They have now implemented measures on 'saving the economy' which will hit lower income families more due to the government giving out contracts during the pandemic to companies who were unable to fulfil the order to the capacity required.

I understand it was unprecedented but as the pandemic went on the same mistakes were being made time and time again. Getting rid of lockdown measures too early to create short term benefits whilst in the long term we would suffer.
text_short_wave3: This government are a joke and do not care about you at all.
life_event_descr_wave3: We bought a house for the first time.
life_event_descr: Planning a wedding

text_long_wave1: The current situation makes me feel incredibly anxious. i have never been in a place in my life when I was worried about being able to feed myself. Whilst I know shops are open and have plenty of stock, its making sure you can make full, nutritious meals with those ingredients whilst navigating a store which you can no longer use your usual routes in and people are increasingly rude. This causes a lot of anxiety day to day as I am fully responsible for cooking and shopping for myself and two other adults. I also feel absolutely disgusted over the behaviour of others at the minute, as they have no thought for other people. Their reckless behaviour could kill someone and the thought that their recklessness could even lead to me being responsible for killing someone is absolutely terrifying. The lack of leadership in this country is also leaving me rather confused about the whole situation and how it will progress, leaving me fearful of what is really to come.
text_short_wave1: Stay inside for all of us so we can get out of this mess sooner!!!
text_long_wave2: I feel a lot of disgust and anger towards the government for its gross mishandling of the current situation. I fear that people will become complacent too soon with the children returning to schools despite the data showing that schools cause a massive rise in cases. I also feel slightly optimistic that we may be nearing a point where things can become more normal with the mass introduction of the vaccine, though I fear that if the June date isn't stuck to the country will become complacent on any measures.
text_short_wave2: The government is doing a terrible job at containing this and people need to do better until we can kick this
text_long_wave3: The government are trying to kill us all off and don't care about the regular people as long as their rich buddies all make a lot of money out of it. They have removed all help for people affected by the corona virus to cover the public money they gave to their friends. This makes me extremely angry and eager for the next general election. The rapid increase of corona virus running through the country right now is explicitly the fault of the Tory party and Boris Johnson himself. Boris Johnson should be made to resign for his failings.
text_short_wave3: The Tory party has failed us all in favor of lining their friends pockets. They should resign for killing so many innocent people.
life_event_descr: I was in a new relationship after divorce and that relationship has ended. The person I was with needed a lot of emotional support because of covid and I just ran out of energy for it.
life_event_descr_2: Falling and needing a new shoulder. NHS were fabulous but I am very nervous of being in public spaces and in close proximity to unmasked people.

text_long_wave1: I feel out of control. Overwhelmed by this situation. Overwhelmed by news about it in social media and other information channels. I feel highly anxious. I feel if restrictions would be stricter, we could deal with the situation faster. I feel not well informed. I feel lost and scared. I'm worried. I'm slightly angry with people who still don't take this situation seriously. I'm tired and I think that it will be even worse. I have constant negative thoughts and I cannot focus on anything else. I am worrying about the future, about tomorrow, this week... I'm worried about next month and next few months.
text_short_wave1: I don't like this situation. I feel anxiety. I am constantly thinking about the future. Those are not positive thoughts. I'm worried about people whom I care about and about myself. I feel powerless, lost and don't really know what to do. I wish we could live in boring times...
text_long_wave2: I'm still anxious. Many people behave like they are fine with the situation, but circumstances are still the same. Deadly virus is flying around. We are not vaccinated, vaccine is not working in 100 percent, virus have more and more variants, so nothing really changed. I'm frustrated, have enough and I worry a lot. I would like this to be over and I'm angry, because it could be of people would behave and have some common sense. I'm also frustrated, because I see many people (online) that are denying the virus, it's possible outcome or vaccination program. I'm sad that there is so many things that we cannot do or miss out.
text_short_wave2: People are not listening, not taking seriously world (covid) situation. We could have this behind, but not many people care. Now I see that humans can use to every, even bad, situation. We should prevent, not use our energy to fight with eachother. I'm sad, frustrated and angry.
eng_native_wave2: No but I speak it fluently
text_long_wave3: I feel that people behave like the pandemic is over. News are about different things, while virus is still killing people. Almost no one wears mask and I feel odd in the shops, while wearing one, because it's often just me. I still avoid public transport, because buses are full again and most people don't care about social distancing. It's frustrating that all the restrictions disappeared, while we have so many new daily cases. Lack of consistency in restrictions wasn't helping and now people don't feel obligated to be careful anymore.
text_short_wave3: Yesterday we had almost 40k new cases of coronavirus in the UK and 172 people died, but yeah, sure, pandemic is over, who cares. Am I a weirdo for still wearing mask in public places and avoiding people?
life_event_descr_wave3: I don't have a job and it's hard to find a new employment now.
life_event_descr_2_wave3: Health problems
life_event_descr: I got a new job last November. Corona provided me the time to sit back and reflect on what I really wanted to achieve in life.
